<FIRST>r i PM-NoPalestinians     03-30 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No Palestinians,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Bank Arabs Barred from Cleaning Tel Aviv Streets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians from the occupied territories will
no longer be allowed to clean the streets of Tel Aviv, and Jews
will be encouraged to take their place, city officials say.
   ``The Arabs from the territories can't be depended on to get to
work,'' Meir Doron, the municipality's deputy director-general,
said Wednesday.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began nearly 16 months ago, army
curfews on Arab villages and threats by uprising leaders warning
the workers to stay away from jobs in Israel have kept many from
getting to work.
   About 100,000 Palestinians work in Israel, mostly in menial
labor, construction and hotel maintenance.
   Most of the 300 street sweepers Tel Aviv hires on a daily basis
have been Palestinians from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Many days only a dozen or so would arrive,'' municipality
spokesman Benny Cohen said. ``One day only four showed up for
work.''
   But city officials say they may have trouble finding Israelis
who want to sweep streets although they are prepared to pay Jews
more than the Arabs received.
   ``The problem is that people don't want to take this kind of job
because of the stigma once associated with it,'' Doron said.
``People think that cleaning houses or sweeping streets is a job
for laborers brought in from Africa, or Arabs.''
</TEXT>
