<FIRST>u a AM-B-1BGrounded     03-30 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-1B Grounded,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preliminary Inspections Show No Problems With B-1B Bomber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OFFUT AIR FORCE BASE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force found no
problems in inspections Wednesday of at least 19 B-1B bombers,
which were grounded two days earlier after one of the plane's swing
wings punctured a fuel tank, a spokesman said.
   Col. Larry Greer of the Strategic Air Command said six more of
the older B-1B's would be inspected before the Air Force decided
whether to clear them for flight. The inspections were to be
completed at Offut Air Force Base by early Thursday, Greer said.
   SAC has 97 B-1Bs, which are up to 2{ years old.
   The 25 picked for inspection were representative of older B-1B's
at SAC's four B-1 wings, Greer said. Most are stationed at Dyess
Air Force Base in Texas, McConnell Air Force Base in Kansas, Grand
Forks Air Force Base in North Dakota and Ellsworth Air Force Base
in South Dakota.
   Other planes are stationed at a maintenance depot at Tinker Air
Force Base in Oklahoma and a contractors plant in Palmdale, Calif.,
the colonel said.
   Gen. John T. Chain Jr., SAC's commander, will review inspection
reports and make a final decision on whether the bombers should be
returned to service, Greer said.
   The fuel tank damaged during a routine pre-flight check at Dyess
was apparently punctured when the mechanism that sweeps the
bomber's wings back and forth malfunctioned, Pentagon spokesman Dan
Howard said Tuesday.
   ``We are looking at something called the wing-sweeper gear
sub-assembly,'' Greer said Wednesday. ``That's the gear box inside
the swing wings which gives it power to sweep the wings up and
back. You can sweep them back for a sort of delta shape to fly
close to supersonic speeds and you sweep them out for landing and
takeoff.''
   Howard said the Texas bomber's crew was sweeping the wings
forward and backward before taking off and discovered the wings
were not moving evenly together.
</TEXT>
