<FIRST>r a PM-Names     03-30 0925</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKEMAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folk singer Arlo Guthrie plans his first
concert in Woody Guthrie's hometown in conjunction with the release
of an album of his late father's songs.
   The album was recorded Dec. 1 by schoolchildren at the
refurbished Crystal Theatre in Okemah. It features songs written by
his father and by children from Okemah, Langston and Davenport.
   Carolyn Price, chairwoman of the WOODY Educational Fund, said
Wednesday the April 29 concert will be the focus of the community's
Pioneer Day activities. The acronym stands for Woody Guthrie Okemah
Organization for Developing Youngsters.
   Woody Guthrie has been criticized in his hometown for leftist
positions he had taken in the 1930s and 1940s. Ms. Price said she
believes the community is willing to accept him now, 22 years after
his death.
   ``We feel like the door is opening now,'' she said.
   She said Guthrie's remaining critics in Okemah are a small
minority.
   ``Just because they're vocal doesn't mean they're right,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Black Orchid, an upscale restaurant partly
owned by actor Tom Selleck, was fined $35,400 for 173 immigration
law violations, federal officials said.
   In order to prevent illegal aliens from obtaining employment,
all employers must verify that new employees are U.S. citizens or
aliens who have the right to work in the United States.
   ``It is unfortunate that this employer did not comply with the
law,'' the Immigration and Naturalization Service's Harold Ezell
said Wednesday.
   ``We're just shocked to hear it,'' said Randy Schoch, president
and part-owner of the restaurant. ``We have no illegal aliens
working for us, absolute zero. We felt that we had filled out all
the forms.''
   INS officials told reporters Wednesday that illegal aliens were
found working at the restuarant. The agency said it could not give
an exact count.
   The INS checked more than 300 Black Orchid employee immigration
compliance forms and found only 32 were correctly filled out, Ezell
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Doris Day suffered a deep leg cut
and was unable to present the best original score Oscar.
   Miss Day, who turns 65 Monday, was scheduled to present the
award Wednesday night along with actor-dancer Patrick Swayze and
composer Marvin Hamlisch. But she told producer Allan Carr on
Wednesday morning she would be unable to attend, said her
publicist, Linda Dozoretz.
   The actress, who received an Oscar nomination 30 years ago for
the romantic comedy ``Pillow Talk,'' was walking through the
gardens of the hotel she owns in this seaside northern California
community when she cut her leg on a sprinkler. The cut required
stitches, Dozoretz said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version of the following items moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Abbott, born without a right
hand, will be the California Angels' fifth starter and most likely
make his first big-league debut April 8 against the Seattle
Mariners at Anaheim Stadium.
   California Manager Doug Rader said earlier that Abbott would
open the season with the Angels only if he fit into their starting
rotation.
   ``I'm real excited. Real thrilled. This is a pretty big
moment,'' Abbott said Wednesday. ``I didn't really expect it, but I
wanted it real bad.''
   The 21-year-old Abbott, the 1987 Sullivan Award winner as the
country's outstanding amateur athlete, was selected by the Angels
in the first round of June's free agent draft. He was a standout at
the University of Michigan and on the U.S. Olympic baseball team.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic gold medalist Greg Louganis'
housemate and former business manager has been ordered to stay at
least 500 feet away from the diver unless they mutually agree to
closer contact.
   But Superior Court Judge Dzintra Janavs on Tuesday refused to
order R. James Babbitt out of the Malibu home he has shared with
Louganis the past four years.
   Louganis, who won gold medals for springboard and platform
diving in last summer's Olympics, fired Babbitt, his manager for
six years, on March 13. He alleges that Babbitt threatened to make
public ``confidential and private facts'' about him unless Louganis
rehires him or compensates him.
   The 29-year-old Louganis said Babbitt had threatened to destroy
his personal belongings and to shoot him if he tried to enter the
house.
   In a sworn declaration, Babbitt said he has never harassed
Louganis.
   Although Janavs ordered Babbitt to stay away from Louganis, he
allowed him to withdraw $5,000 in living expenses from their joint
account in addition to continue living at the home. Louganis said
he is the sole owner of the house, but Babbitt contended he is a
co-owner.
   Janavs' order came in the form of a temporary restraining order.
He scheduled a hearing April 12 to determine whether to issue a
preliminary injunction against Babbitt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian tennis ace Pat Cash has
separated from his longtime Norwegian girlfriend and mother of his
two children, Anne- Britt Kristiansen.
   The 23-year-old former Wimbledon tennis champion ended months of
speculation about his loss of form and outbursts of irrational
behavior, issuing a statement that the past few months ``had been a
very difficult period for both of us'' and that they had agreed to
a trial separation.
   ``Having made this announcement, we ask the media to respect our
privacy and neither of us shall be making any further statement,''
said the joint statement.
   Ms. Kristiansen, 25, a model, was at the couple's Oslo home with
their two children, Daniel, 2, and Mia, 11 months, and could not be
reached for comment.
</TEXT>
