<FIRST>r w PM-SportPilots     03-30 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sport Pilots,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>New License Would Save Money for Sport Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who want to learn to fly can save as
much as $1,850 by qualifying for a new recreational pilot license.
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced requirements for
the new license Wednesday, saying it was designed for would-be
recreational or sport pilots who are willing to fly short distances
in daylight at low altitudes within 50 miles of the airport where
they train.
   The new recreational certification for flying basic aircraft,
including home-built and experimental models, will require less
training or experience than a private pilot certificate.
   The FAA estimates that the new rules will save a would-be pilot
between $1,200 and $1,850 from what it would take to get a private
pilot license. The cost of training for a full private license is
estimated at between $3,100 and $4,750, depending on hourly fees
charged, said spokesman John Leyden.
   Pilots who get the new license will not have to learn how to use
sophisticated navigational or radio equipment, which is required of
other private pilots, the FAA said in a news release. But they
cannot fly in areas which require communication with air traffic
controllers.
   The FAA said the sport pilot's training will focus on basic
flying skills.
   The new rule limits recreational pilots to single-engine
aircraft with no more than 180 horsepower engines, a fixed landing
gear and no more than four seats. They will be allowed to carry
only one passenger and cannot fly for hire.
   At the same time, the agency imposed new testing requon
student pilots and new annual reviews for inexperienced pilots who
are not rated to fly with instruments.
   The FAA also increased the flight visibility requirement fortudent
pilots from one mile to three miles and r they
pass a written test before their first solo flight.
</TEXT>
