<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-DrugTesting     03-30 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Drug Testing,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Extolling Virtues of Random Drug-Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's chief spokesman is touting
random drug-testing for federal employees and says he thinks it is
shortsighted for White House workers to resist it.
   Commenting Wednesday on a longstanding suit against the testing
by some 30 employees of the Executive Office of the President,
press secretary Marlin Fitzwater called drug abuse ``an insidious
problem'' in America.
   ``It's everywhere. It's throughout our society,'' the spokesman
said. ``And all of our institutions should be taking a look at ways
to curb it. And that's what the federal government's doing.''
   Fitzwater defended the government's right to subject employees
to random drug-testing as the Secret Service disclosed that four
officers accused of drug abuse had been removed from its payroll.
   Spokesman Bob Snow said there had been two resignations and two
firings in the Uniformed Division of the agency, which guards
foreign embassies and the White House grounds. The departure of the
four guards stemmed from an investigation that surfaced last May.
   A source who declined to be named publicly said U.S. Attorney
Jay Stephens' office decided that there should be no prosecution
for the alleged drug use, which was said to involve cocaine. But it
could not immediately be learned whether the two resignations and
the two firings resulted from negotiations with Stephens' office.
   ``From our standpoint, they're gone,'' Snow said. He said the
more than 950 officers in the Uniformed Division are now subjected
to routine drug testing.
   Fitzwater noted that the suit initially was filed in federal
court here against then-President Reagan and that Reagan's name was
replaced with Bush's when the administrations changed Jan. 20.
   The Reagan White House, chafing over revelations of drug abuse
by presidential employees in sensitive jobs, announced June 30 that
everyone on its payroll would be subject to random drug tests in 60
days. But that program has been held up by court challenges.
   The employees say false test results could make them subject to
undeserved penalties.
   Reagan's announcement had been preceded by revelations that two
National Security Council clerks resigned and three Secret Service
officers were suspended while awaiting the outcome of an
investigation into alleged drug use.
   Neither the White House nor the Secret Service would describe at
the time what drugs were involved in the investigation, which led
to the resignations of the two NSC clerks and placement of three
Uniformed Division officers on administrative leave.
   During a speech last week to several Delaware groups involved in
combating drug use, Bush hailed two Supreme Court rulings upholding
mandatory workplace drug testing for people in law enforcement and
public safety jobs.
   ``I hope this will help achieve our goal of a drug-free
workplace,'' he said.
   Neither of the two Supreme Court opinions dealt head-on with the
constitutionality of random drug testing for some 400,000 federal
workers.
   On Wednesday, Fitzwater was asked what Bush thought of the
attempt by employees in the White House complex to stop random drug
testing of some 1,500 of the 1,850 employees in the Executive
Office of the President.
   The spokesman replied that Bush was ``concerned that they don't
understand the need for random drug testing and the need to take
steps to make sure that we keep drugs out of the federal service.
... The evidence is considerable on the importance of random drug
testing and curbing drug use.''
</TEXT>
