<HEAD>Laboratory Scent May Create Fatal Attraction for Peachtree Borers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Male insects whose pursuit of sex leads them
to ravage peach trees are being drawn by an artificial perfume into
wearing themselves out on plastic strips instead.
   Scientists are holding out hope that the method of pest control
by way of birth control will cost less and be safer than
insecticides being used on peach trees.
   The male pests are the lesser peachtree borer, which attacks the
trunk or limbs of the tree, and the larva of a close relative, the
peachtree borer, which chews at the base and roots.
   Both are looking for female borers and are drawn by the scent
into thinking they have found potential mates. But it's a fatal
attraction, say Agriculture Department scientists.
   ``It works like this,'' said entomologist J. Wendell Snow. ``The
insects try to mate daily, from around 11 a.m. until about 2 p.m.
for about two weeks, the lifespan of adults. When the male futilely
approaches the (scent's) dispenser repeatedly, he becomes totally
confused and exhausted.''
   Femalo compete with the artificial sex
scents, remain barren, thereby breaking the reproductive chain, or
egg-larvae-adult cycle.
   The five-yeact, described by the department's
Agricultural Research Serviceled by entomologist J. Wendell
Snow, who delved into the sex scents, or pheromones, emitted by the
female borers.
   Snow, who is in charge he Southeastern Fruit and Tree Nut
Research Laboratory in Byron, Ga., hung disprs containing the
artificial sc in each peach tree of the test ds.
   The sex attractants, whn the tops of test trees,
``achieved almost complete control'' of the borers in several
orchards in central Georgia, he said.
   Snow said t pheromone dispensers, which are made of plastic
and resemble tash bag twist ties, are being reviewed by the
Environmental Pro use.
   The lesser borer resides in Canada and the eastern United
States, while the peachtre inhabits most of the United
States. The pests cost American peach growers an eted $20
million annually.
   Only two chemical pesticides _ Lre
approved for control of the e pheromones leave no
residue (on fruit) and are expected to be cost competitivh
current control methods,'' Sn
   Meanwhile, researchers are evaluating the pheromones for
effectiveness under different groions in South Carolina,
Virginia, Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
