<FIRST>r w PM-Prosecutor-Budd     03-30 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prosecutor-Budd,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Black Named US Attorney for Massachusetts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is easily winning Democratic
support for his choice of moderate black Republican Wayne A. Budd
as U.S. attorney for Massachusetts.
   Bush on Wednesday announced his intention to nominate Budd, a
47-year-old Boston lawyer, to succeed Frank L. McNamara Jr., a
conservative who left office Jan. 30 amid accusations that he used
his prosecutorial powers for political ends.
   Budd has been appointed to state posts by both Democrats and
Republicans and has experience as a prosecutor and in private
practice.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the state's senior senator and
a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, will back Budd, an aide
said.
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, who had pushed for McNamara's resignation,
applauded the selection, praising Budd for his ``enthusiasm,
integrity, balance and professionalism.''
   The nomination is expected to win easy Senate confirmation.
   Budd, a 1967 graduate of Wayne State University School of Law,
served from 1969 to 1971 as an assistant state attorney general and
chief of the state civil rights and liberties division under
Democratic Attorney General Robert H. Quinn.
   In 1972, Budd was appointed by Republican Gov. Francis W.
Sargent as a member of the state Civil Service Commission, and was
named commission chairman b Dukakis in 1983. He served as chairman
until 1987.
   The son of a Springfield policeman, Budd also served as
president of the Massachusetts Bar Association from 1979 to 1980.
   The Bush administration had been considering Budd and Robert S.
Mueller, who had been the No. 2 federal prosecutor in Massachusetts
under former U.S. Attorney William F. Weld.
   Bush, anxious to promote minorities to high-ranking government
posts, favored Budd while Thornburgh wanted Mueller because of his
more extensive prosecutorial experience, The Boston Globe reported.
   Budd will be made an interim appointee to the post until he cuts
his ties with his private law practice, which is expected within
several weeks.
