<FIRST>r w PM-FarmSubsidies     03-30 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Subsidies,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Yields on Demand to Eliminate Farm Subsidies Internationally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials reluctantly concede they will
have to accept a compromise with Europe over elimination of farm
price supports in order to avert the collapse of international
trade talks.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said Wednesday that he had
agreed to a formula that would call for ``progressive substantial
reductions'' of agricultural subsidies. The United States had
originally sought the use of the word ``elimination'' of subsidies.
   ``What we have tried to do is state it in a manner that might be
a little more palatable politically to our European counterparts,''
Yeutter said in an interview on National Public Radio.
   Asked if this was a compromise compared with the hardline
position he took at international trade talks in Montreal last
December, Yeutter answered, ``Not much.'' He added that the
proposed formula ``will get us to the ultimate objective of getting
rid of trade-distorting kind of practices in agriculture around the
world.''
   Another Agriculture Department official, speaking on condition
he not be identified, said the EEC had indicated to U.S.
negotiators that it would accept the compromise. This could pave
the way for progress at a meeting next Wednesday in Geneva of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The Montreal meeting of cabinet members from the 96 GATT members
broke down over the agricultural clash between the United States
and the 12-nation EEC, with members refusing to act on other
pressing trade issues until the dispute is resolved.
   The EEC, which has powerful farming interests, balked at the
U.S. demand for total elimination of the subsidies and was only
willing to discuss reducing the supports.
   The United States contends that the supports for production and
export of agricultural products distort world market prices and
force the administration to prop up American farmers to the tune of
some $25 million annually so they can compete abroad.
   The U.S. position on farm supports has been gradually eroding
since last year, when former President Reagan dropped his original
goal for the worldwide elimination of farm subsidies by the year
2000.
   The United States then took the position that it was not setting
any date for elimination of the supports but was seeking instead a
commitment from all GATT members for eventual elimination.
   In the absence of such a commitment, the United States intends
to press the EEC at the Geneva meeting to reduce its export subsidy
for farmers. Yeutter said the United States has had to keep up with
the Europeans by increasing export supports for farmers and ``it's
really sheer economic madness.''
   Another potential sticking point in Geneva is a new EEC demand
that the United States freeze current limitations on the size of
farm lands used for production. The United States asked farmers to
idle some lands last year because of the drought.
   Yeutter said he would reject the EEC demand.
   ``The European community is trying to lock us into that position
forever and we just can't afford to have that take place,'' he said.
   Agriculture Department officials say they will decide by June 1
whether to maintain the existing limitations on farm production,
depending on their determination of the past winter's drought
damage.
</TEXT>
