demand, President Jose Sarney says.
   In an interview with The Associated Press on Wednesday, Sarney
said the debt burden is giving Latin Americans a sense that ``a
democratic regime, free enterprise, is incapable of solving the
problems of each country.''
   ``No regime can survive if it cannot at least offer solutions
forts people,'' said Sarney, who sphe Palace of the Dawn, the
presidential residene.
   Sarney, a 58-year-old poet and rancher, took office in 1985 in a
military-mandated Electoral College elction after 21 years of
right-wing military rule.
   But chronic economic problems, including a $115 billion debt and
1,000 percent inflatione led to increased popularity of leftist
parties in advance of presidential election.
   It will be Brazil's free presidential election in 29 years.
   Under the constituay not run for re-election.
   ``The transition (to civilian rule) has brought parties with
totalitarian tendies into the democratic game,'' Sarney said.
``While we haven't had military upngs or serious social upheavals,
we also don't have groups of subversives or ones who deny
democratic values.''
   However, Sarney said Latin America's foreign debt was a threat
to democrBrazil and the rest of the region. Latin American nations
