<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     03-30 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit Another High, Dollar Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed today at another record high on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar lost ground against
the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose 430.92 points on
Wednesday, added another 88.85 points, or 0.27 percent, ending the
day at 32,826.13.
   The Nikkei index lost 74.05 points during the morning session
because of profit-taking, but then recovered as individual
investors began buying shipbuilding and chemical issues in the
afternoon, dealers said.
   ``Investors appear not to be very concerned about factors such
as U.S. inflation'' and exchange rates, said Tetsuo Ushijima, an
analyst for Nomura Securities. ``It seems unlikely that the dollar
will continue to rise,'' he added.
   Trading, led by individual players, was active, with volume on
the market's first section estimated at 1.4 billion shares,
compared to 1.3 billion traded on Wednesday.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar finished trading at
132.80 yen, down 0.45 yen from Wednesday's closing of 133.25 yen.
After opening slightly higher at 133.27 yen, the U.S. currency
edged down, ranging between 132.78 and 133.30 yen during the day.
   The dollar weakened as Japanese investors reduced their dollar
buying, mainly due to position adjustments, said a trader with the
Bank of Tokyo.
   ``Concerted central bank intervention in the United States and
Europe for the last two days also indirectly helped stop the
dollar's recent rise,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   U.S. and European central banks intervened in currency markets
on Tuesday and Wednesday in an attempt to stabilize the dollar.
   Other dealers said market players were reluctant to continue
buying dollars because of the upcoming Group of Seven (G-7) meeting
of finance officials from major industrialized nations.
   The G-7 meeting is scheduled to be held in Washington on Sunday.
</TEXT>
