<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Strike     03-30 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Strike,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Battle Workers At Hyundai Shipyard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of riot police battled
workers at the nation's largest shipyard today in an attempt to end
three months of violent strikes by activists demanding recognition
for their union.
   Ten thousand riot police stormed the Hyundai yard in Ulsan
before dawn and fired hundreds of tear gas shells from rifles and
helicopters as strikers retreated to a company dormitory complex,
police and news reports said.
   About 700 striking workers wearing headbands, helmets and
brandishing steel clubs held police at a standoff at the
dormitories for more than six hours before police charged again,
firing tear gas, the Yonhap news agency reported.
   Strikers fought back with water from firehoses, firebombs, rocks
and steel clubs, the South Korean news agency said, and police
gained control of one of the six buildings in the dormitory
complex. Police officials said 200 workers were arrested.
   About 1,000 militant members of an independent labor union
Hyundai refuses to recognize have been staging increasingly violent
protests at the 22,000-worker yard 150 miles southeast of Seoul
since Dec. 12.
   The strikers, who also demand higher pay, have periodically
forced the yard to shut down and the government intervened after
repeated requests from Hyundai. The unrest has repeatedly stalled
operations at the shipya cost the company millions of dollars in
lost revenues.
   The shipyard is a subsidiary of the Hyundai group, the country's
largest conglomerate. Hyundai also owns Hyundai Motor Co., producer
of the popular Hyundai automobiles that are sold in the Uniates.
   Police in combat fati and helmets took over the shipyard just
before dawn today after bulldozers andt trucks tore down iron and
steel barricades erected by strikers. About 1,000 police arrived b
sea in boats.
   The workers fled to the dorm complex and refused police demands
that they surrender. Mattreme of the dormitories to prevent suicide
jumps, police said.
   Police confiscated hundreds of firebombs, clubs, canisters of
propane gas and homemade explosives, Yonhap reported.
   About 10,000 workerociated with the strike were allowed into the
yard to work today.
   The Labor Ministry said today that 422 pad been injured in
violence at the yard since December and that Hyundai has lost $810
million in business. Press reports said most workers at the
shipyard wanted to work.
   Meanwhile, 1,000 students at Ulsan University battled riot
police with firebombs and rocks when police stopped them from
marching to the shipyard to join the strikers, Yonhap reported.
Police said 200 wrs were arrested.
   And at Changwon, a provincial city on the south coast, ab 1,800
workers at the Hyundai Precision Co., another subsidiary of the
conglomerate, rallied in support of the striking workers.
   President Roh Tae-woo's government has warned it will take a
tough line against militant workers, who have staged a ser of often
violent strikes.
   The government urged companies to settle labor disputes
peacefully without official interference.
</TEXT>
