<DOCNO> AP890330-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Oscars-Review     03-30 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oscars-Review,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscars Recipe: Same Soup, Different Cooks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 61st annual Academy Awards on ABC wasn't
the longest Oscar Show on record _ it just seemed that way.
   Perhaps it wasn't even the most boring, although it certainly
seemed to be. It was a visual and aural equivalent of empty
calories. After Wednesday night's three hours and 15 minutes, you
still felt hungry.
   The show, as put together by producer Allan Carr, had a theme of
Hollywood couples. What it sadly lacked was a focus. It begged for
a host to tie it together. It desperately needed a Johnny Carson or
Chevy Chase, who were hosts in previous years, or even a Billy
Crystal or Robin Williams, who provided some of the night's only
laughs.
   It was a show without a single highlight, without a memorable
moment, without an emotional peak. It was flat from start to finish.
   The show's only surprise, the only relief in the tedium, was
Jodie Foster's win as best actress for her role in ``The Accused.''
   Nothing would have helped this show more than chopping its tacky
20-minute opening number and starting it with the presentation of
the best supporting actress award. Carr wanted a shiny vehicle to
pay tribute to Hollywood extravaganzas. What the ABC-TV audience
got was a flaming wreck.
   An interesting thing about the Oscar telecast is that every
producer starts fresh each year. No one ever seems to build on last
year's assets, no one ever seems to learn from previous mistakes.
   The biggest ongoing problem is that every new producer forgets
this is an awards show. The audience wants to see a competition.
They want to see the emotional highs of the winners, and the
let-down of the losers.
   The producers also forget this is a show about the movies. This
year's program seemed to have fewer film clips than any Oscarcast
in recent memory.
   The one thing the Oscar broadcast should not be, yet every
producer seems determined to make it such, is a variety show filled
with overblown production numbers. Next year's producer should be
forced to sign an oath: Remember the movies, forget the
extravaganza.
   The most quotable quote: Walter Matthau saying ``A stage hand
said the show was running long tonight.'' Maybe it should be called
`Awards and Remembrances,''' a reference to ABC's 30-hour
mini-series, ``War and Remembrance.''
   Show's best sight: Sean Connery and Roger Moore, two of the
movies' James Bonds, presenting the Oscar for best supporting actor
with Michael Caine.
   Show's funniest sight: Carrie Fisher and Martin Short in the
same dress.
   Show's best relief from the boredom: Billy Crystal doing Yul
Brynner as Babe Ruth, Edward G. Robinson as a gangster in ``The Ten
Commandments,'' and doing a tap dance sound-alike with a cough drop
in his mouth; and Robin Williams as an overgrown Mickey Mouse.
   A final thought: Douglas Fairbanks presented all of the Oscars
in five minutes at the first Academy Awards presentation in 1927.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0035 </DOCNO>
