<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-AlaskaTourism     03-30 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Alaska Tourism,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Slick Also Dirties Alaska's Tourism Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil that has polluted Prince William
Sound is soiling Alaska's $500 million tourism industry, and some
fear losses from the nation's worst oil spill could last for years.
   Hardest hit since Friday's spill are small businesses operating
in the sound, where salmon fishing and spectacular glaciers draw
thousands of tourists each summer.
   Will Eason of Anchorage owns and operates Prince William Sound
Charters, which provided about 1,000 fishing and sightseeing trips
out of the coastal town of Whittier last year.
   ``I've lost probably about 50 percent of my bookings for this
summer,'' Eason said Wednesday. ``It's going to be devastating for
us.''
   Eason said he may be forced out of business.
   ``It's hard to say. This could even go on for years,'' said
Eason, whose business depends on repeat customers and their
referrals.
   He expects business to slow further as the extent of damage
becomes clear.
   The spill also is affecting tourist businesses hundreds of miles
away.
   ``We got over a dozen phone calls yesterday, not only from
individual clients but also from wholesalers from New York to
California who were wondering if they should be canceling their
trips to Alaska,'' said Ken Leghorn, owner of Alaska Discovery in
Juneau.
   Alaska Discovery provides camping and kayak trips in the
southeast panhandle and the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, areas
hundreds of miles away from Prince William Sound.
   ``They're just assuming that such a large area is affected that
any coastline trip to Alaska is going to be not worth seeing,''
Leghorn said.
   Despite the problems some smaller businesses are reporting,
state tourism officials and representatives of large cruise ship
lines predict the overall damage to the industry, if any, will be
minimal.
   Cruise spokesmen report no itinerary changes, few calls and no
cancellations from tourists who have booked their summer vacations.
   ``We probably got between 10 and 20 calls from travel agents and
consumers in the last two days,'' said Rich Skinner of
Seattle-based Holland America Line-Westtours, the largest cruise
ship operator in Alaska waters. ``They're wondering how it will
impact their vacation, they're wondering how close it is to where
they're going.''
   Holland America, which last year took more than 79,000 people to
Alaska, has scheduled 68 cruises along the Alaska coast this year.
Sixteen of those are to pass through Prince William Sound.
   Columbia Glacier ruises Inc. in Anchorage operates a popular
150-passenger day cruise between Var in the sound. Division manager
Phil Broderick was optimistic nd will be made pristine again
despite the disaster.
   Otherimism.
   ``The tourism industry is a little bit hesitant to say anything
negative because of the impact it c sound this summer, and on the
image of Prince William Sound,'' said John Gans, marketing and
admissions direceadership School in Lander, Wyo.
   The school has offered wiless training courses in Prince William
Sound since 1970, and might cancel those courses this year.
</TEXT>
