<HEAD>`Pelle the Conqueror' Takes Foreign Film Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Pelle the Conqueror,'' an epic drama about
a boy and his father who must carve a new life in unforgiving
Danish farm country won Best Foreign film at the Academy Awards,
the second such honor for Denmark.
   The country won its first Oscar last year in ``Babette's
Feast.'' Wednesday night's nomination was Denmark's fifth in the
category.
   ``I made a film about a poor immigrant from Denmark and here I
am standing in my tuxedo and this shiny thing,'' said Bille August,
the film's director and writer, holding up his golden statue.
   Asked why the austere film was so popular, he said, ``It's a
story about human beings. It's a story about emotion. Everybody can
understand it. It inspires people all over the world with its
emotion.''
   The story is told through the eyes of Pelle Hvenegaard, a
Swedish boy who accompanies his widower father, played by Max Von
Sydow, on a perilous adventure early in the century. Von Sydow,
nominated for best actor, saw the award got to Dustin Hoffman for
his role in ``Rain Man.''
   Pelle finds his new home exciting and forbidding as he draws
inner strength from suffering. ``I think it means a lot to Danish
film,'' August said when asked about the significance of the award.
``It is very important to people in film in my country.''
   He'd like to do a sequel, but addet would be several years away.
His current project is ``The Hou Spirits,'' an adaptation of a book
of the same title by Isabelle Allende. The Warner Bros. project
will be filmed in Argentina in English.
   ``Pelle the Conqueror,'' which drew $1.3 million at the box
office, may sound depressing but August's scriptprises. His work is
showcased in a backdrop of the grand Danish countryside.
   Thirty-one countries submitted entries for consideration in this
year's Acadds. Selection of each nation's entry is made by ry
composed of filmmakers from that country and which need not be
released in the United States, is accepted.
