<FIRST>r a PM-OfficerSlain     03-30 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Officer Slain,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Convicted In Policeman's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three admitted drug dealers were convicted in
the murder of a rookie policeman whose death gained national
prominence in last year's presidential election and led to a major
drive against drug traffickers.
   Scott Cobb, 25, Todd Scott, 20, and Philip Copeland, 23, were
found guilty of second-degree murder and weapons charges Wednesday
evening after two days of jury deliberations.
   All three verdicts were met in the crowded courtroom by cheers
and applause from police officers and friends and family of slain
Officer Edward Byrne.
   Speaking to reporters afterward, Matthew Byrne said his son's
murder was ``meant to send a message to society'' about the power
of the drug dealers. The guilty verdicts, he said, send ``a message
from society ... don't kill cops.''
   Prosecutors said Byrne was killed early in the morning of Feb.
26, 1988, on orders from Howard ``Pappy'' Mason, a jailed drug lord
who was seeking revenge for his weapons conviction earlier that
week.
   Byrne was shot five times in the head at close range as he sat
alone in a patrol car guarding the home of a witness in a drug case
in the borough of Queens.
   In the wake of the slaying, police established the Tactical
Narcotics Team, which put a heavy police presence in the area. The
program has since been extended to other drug-plagued neighborhoods
and has resulted in thousands of arrests.
   Byrne's slaying also gained national attention during last
year's presidential election when the officer's father presented
his son's shield to then Vice President George Bush at a rally.
   The elder Byrne supported Bush's pro-death penalty stance. New
York state does not have the death penalty.
   The defendants each face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life
on the murder charges and five to 15 years on the second-degree
criminal possession of a weapon convictions.
   A fourth defendant, David McClary, is to be tried later.
   Lawyers for the three convicted Wednesday promised appeals.
</TEXT>
