<TEXT>
   William Chappell, a 20-year Florida
congressman defeated for re-election last year amid reports linking
him to the Pentagon procurement scandal, died today after a battle
with bone cancer. He was 67.
   Chappell, a Democrat who had represented northeast Florida's 4th
District, died at the National Institutes of Health, where he had
been hospitalized Feb. 23.
   The former chairman of the powerful defense appropriations
subcommittee lost to Republican newcomer Craig James by 791 votes,
less than 1 percent of about 250,000 votes cast.
   James' campaign emphasized reports linking Chappell to the
Pentagon bribery probe. Chappell never was charged with any
wrongdoing in the case.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Richard Ellis</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard H. Ellis, a retired general and former
head of the Strategic Air Command who also served as the Air
Force's vice chief of staff, died Tuesday of cancer. He was 69.
   Ellis joined the military in September 1941 as an aviation cadet
at Maxwell Field, Ala., and received his commission and pilot wings
in April 1942. He was a highly decorated command pilot, flying more
than 200 combat missions as a bomber pilot in the western Pacific
during World War II.
   Ellis served four years as the commander-in-chief of the
Strategic Air Command, the organization responsible for America's
land-based nuclear missile and bomber forces, until his retirement
in 1981.
   After retiring, Ellis was named in 1982 as chief U.S. delegate
to the U.S.-Soviet commission monitoring compliance with arms
control agreements.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jehiel Elyachar</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Jehiel R. Elyachar, who won U.S. and French
decorations for his World War II work, counseled President
Eisenhower and helped found Albert Einstein College of Medicine,
died Wednesday at age 90.
   Elyachar, who was born in Jerusalem, came to New York in 1928
and served in the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers during World War II.
   He later worked as a counselor to President Eisenhower and was
awarded the U.S. Legion of Merit for laying ``the foundation of
modern military intelligence'' during the war. The French
government awarded him the Legion d-Honeur for his work during the
war.
   Elyachar made his fortune in Manhattan real estate, where he was
a principal in the Straight Construction Co.
   He had contributed at least $1 million to Yeshiva University in
Manhattan and was a founder of its Albert Einstein medical school.
He also helped establish the university's Professorial Chair in
Sephardic Studies and provided scholarship support for Sephardic
students at Yeshiva and other institutions in the United States and
Israel.
