<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madeleine Ozeray, the Belgian actress
whose career spanned a half century of French cinema and received
France's highest cultural honor, has died in Paris at age 80, a
newspaper said today.
   The daily Vers l'Avenir did not say when the actress died or
give the cause of death.
   Miss Ozeray's first major roles came in the 1930s, when she
starred in the French classic ``Une Silhouette dans Knock,'' made
by actor-director Louis Jouvet, her companion for many years.
   In the 1970s, she played in ``La Race des Seigneurs,'' with
Simone Signoret, and ``Le Vieux Fusil,'' with Romy Schneider and
Philippe Noiret.
   Three years ago, she was made a Commander of Arts and Letters,
France's highest cultural distinction.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bernard Blier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Blier, one of the most enduring and
versatile actors in French cinema, died Wednesday night after a
long illness at the age of 73, his son, film director Bertrand
Blier, announced.
   On March 4, Blier received a Cesar, the French equivalent of an
Oscar, honoring the body of his work _ about 150 films in a career
that spanned more than half a century. The formerly rotund actor
appeared weakened and thin as he accepted the award.
   Among his most notable films were ``Hotel du Nord'' (North
Hotel) directed by Marcel Carne (1938); ``Avant le Deluge'' (Before
the Deluge) by Andre Cayatte (1953), and ``Calmos'' and ``Buffet
Froid,'' made in 1975 and 1979, respectively, under the direction
of his son.
