<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Blier     03-30 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Blier,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Actor Bernard Blier Dead at 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Blier, the plump and balding French actor
who incarnated hapless husbands, conniving cops and heartless
hitmen over a movie career that spanned 60 years, has died, his son
announced today. He was 73.
   Blier made more than 150 movies including Yves Allegret's
``Maneges'' (1949) and ``Buffet Froid'' (1979), directed by his son
Bertrand and starring Gerard Depardieu.
   Bertrand Blier said his father died Wednesday night after a long
illness. He did not elaborate.
   Culture Minister Jack Lang said French cinema had lost ``one of
its greatest and most popular artists.''
   Earlier this month, Blier received a special Cesar award, the
equivalent of an American Oscar, honoring his life's work. He
appeared thin and weak as he edged slowly across the stage to take
the golden statue from fellow actor Michel Serrault, who was so
moved he forgot his lines and improvised a poignant presentation.
   Blier was born on Jan. 11, 1916, in Buenos Aires, Argentina
where his father, a biologist, was on assignment for the Pasteur
Institute. He studied drama with stage actor Louis Jouvet, who
reportedly told him he would have a brilliant career starting at
age 50.
   From his first film in 1937, Raymond Rouleau's ``Trois, Six,
Neuf,'' (Three, Six, Nine,) followed by six other movies that same
year, Blier was a workaholic. His last role was in Moshe Misrahi's
``Mangeclous'' in 1988.
   ``My work is my `joie de vivre,''' Blier once said. ``Never do I
go to the studio like one goes to the office.''
</TEXT>
