<FIRST>r a PM-UnderageGambler     03-30 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underage Gambler,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casinos Will Pay Penalties For Underage Gambling Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five casinos accused of giving VIP
treatment to a teen-ager have agreed to pay penalties of up to
$100,000 for allowing a minor to gamble.
   The state Casino Control Commission will meet next week to
actually set the fines, which were proposed in an agreement
announced Wednesday between the casinos and the state Division of
Gaming Enforcement.
   The casinos were charged with treating 17-year-old Debra Kim
Cohen as a high roller even though she was under the legal gambling
age of 21.
   Miss Cohen lost thousands of dollars playing blackjack and was
offered free rooms, drinks, limousine rides, shows and meals by the
casinos.
   Leonard Cohen tried to stop his daughter's compulsive gambling
by sending the casinos letters and photographs of her and warning
security guards to turn her away. In some cases, Miss Cohen
continued on as a preferred customer.
   The proposed penalties were: Caesars, $100,000; Resorts
International, $21,762; Harrah's Marina, $36,387; Trump Plaza,
$7,287, and Elsinore's Atlantis, $14,562.
   Gaming regulators had rejected the casinos' initial proposal to
make donations to medical facilities instead.
   ``Although it sounds like a lot of money, it's a slap on the
wrist to these industry giants,'' the teen-ager's father said.
``It's like paying a parking ticket.''
   He advocated legislation to tighten penalties against casinos
that allow underage gambling.
   Last year, Miss Cohen pleaded guilty to underage gambling and
was ordered to attend Gamblers Anonymous meetings.
   If the fine set by the casino commission is less than the
proposed penalties, the gaming halls will donate the difference to
treatment centers for compulsive gamblers, said Assistant Attorney
General Mitchel Schwefel.
</TEXT>
