<FIRST>r a PM-TurkeyPoint     03-30 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey Point,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuke Plant Operators Fail Tests; Reactor Shut Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A utility turned off a nuclear reactor after nearly
half the control room operators who took a refresher exam flunked.
   Unit 3 at the Turkey Point nuclear plant was shut down Wednesday
following a meeting between Florida Power &amp;Light Co. and the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   Utility spokeswoman Stacey Shaw insisted the NRC had not ordered
a shutdown. Agency spokesman Ken Clark agreed, but added, ``I don't
think we would have been satisfied with anything less.''
   The NRC has fined Turkey Point about $1 million over the last
five years for safety and security violations, identifying the
plant as one of the nation's 10 worst.
   Clark said at least three of six control-room crews and 11 of 24
individuals who took requalification exams earlier this month
failed all or part of the test, which is given to operators at
regular intervals.
   The plant has 52 control-room operators. Those who fail any part
of the test cannot work in the control room until re-certified,
Clark said. Workers take the exams individually and are also tested
on their ability work as a team.
   Ms. Shaw said the reactor will remain closed while the utility
demonstrates to the NRC that those running it are qualified. She
said the plant was to shut down later this week in any case for
routine maintenance.
   Ms. Shaw said only a couple of those who failed are actively
operating the plant's reactors. Many who flunked, she said, are no
longer working in the control rooms.
   Unit 3 was reduced to hot shutdown, allowing it to return on
line quickly if the NRC agrees. Unit 4, the other generator, was
out of operation for refueling.
   Clark said that NRC also is demanding that the utility present a
plan by May to solve training deficiencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
