<HEAD>Mother Removes Life Support From Stabbing Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a stabbing victim removed
her son's life-support system today over the objections of the
assailant, who fears he will be charged with murder.
   Sylvia Lane said she withdrew her son Mark Weaver's feeding tube
at 12:01 a.m. before leaving for her job on the early morning shift
at a nursing home. A probate judge on Feb. 27 gave her permission
to do so beginning today.
   The feeding tube has kept her son alive nearly four years. Mrs.
Lane said doctors believe Weaver, 26, will die in a week or two.
   Only then will prosecutors say whether they will file a murder
charge against Noel Pagan, who served three years in prison for
aggravated assault on Weaver. A judge this week refused to allow
Pagan to intervene in the case.
   Doctors said Weaver has no prospect for recovery from a
``persistent vegetative state'' caused by stab wounds to the neck
that deprived his brain of oxygen.
