<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     03-30 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Launch Attacks on Depot, Christian District; Two Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-fired rockets hit a fuel depot in
Christian east Beirut today and triggered explosions that rocked
the city and shattered windows for miles around. Another Syrian
attack on a Christian neighborhood killed two people, police said.
   A police spokesman said 14 people suffered shrapnel and glass
shard wounds from the butane gas explosions after the attack on the
depot.
   Syrian gunners also fired two rockets into the city's Sin El-Fil
district this morning, said the spokesman, who cannot be named
under police regulations. Two people died there and three were
injured, he said.
   The casualties raised the overall toll to 125 people killed and
405 wounded since March 8 in fighting between Christians and
Moslems.
   The spokesman said more than 250,000 of Beirut's 1.2 million
residents have fled to southern Lebanon since the clashes erupted
between the Christian soldiers of Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian
forces backing militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's
Progressive Socialist Party.
   The rockets struck tanks of butane cooking gas at the Dora
district depot, where fires sparked by earlier shelling already
have destroyed 60 percent of Lebanon's gasoline reserves and 60
percent of its diesel reserves.
   ``Butane is leaking from nearby tanks and exploding in balls of
fire in midair over Dora,'' a local reporter said by telephone.
   The police spokesman said the explosions smashed windows in a
three-mile radius.
   A senior oil ministry official, Raymond Roufaiel, said the fire
blazing uncontrolled in Dora had consumed $10 million worth of
gasoline and more than 3.5 million gallons of diesel oil.
   ``We can hardly manage to encircle the blaze and try to prevent
it from spreading to outside the tanks' region,'' said a Beirut
fire official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Moslem-Christian rift deepened six months ago when President
Amin Gemayel's term expired and Parliament was unable to agree on a
successor.
   Just before leaving office, Gemayel named Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic, leader of an interim military Cabinet.
   Moslems and Syria rejected the appointment because it violated
an unwritten national covenant that gave the premiership to the
Sunni Moslems, the presidency to the Maronites and the house
speakership to the Shiite Moslems.
   They pledged allegiance to Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who
seeks political reforms that will give the country's Moslems an
equal share of power with the traditionally dominant Christians.
   The latest violence round of began when Aoun clamped a blockade
March 6 on illegal militia-run ports, which deprive the government
of tax revenues and are used to bring in supplies for the war.
   Jumblatt retaliated by shelling Christian territory. The Syrians
later joined in the artillery duels across the 310-square mile area
where the country's Christians live.
</TEXT>
