<SECOND>PM-Oscars-Degree,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' Script Brings Oscar To Writer _ And Maybe A College Degree</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after he left college one
credit short of graduation, Oscar-winning screenwriter Barry Morrow
has been offered a chance to earn his degree by submitting his
script for ``Rain Man.''
   Morrow and co-author Ronald Bass won at the Academy Awards
Wednesday night for original screenplay for ``Rain Man,'' the story
of an autistic man whose disability teaches his conniving brother
compassion.
   Morrow attended St. Olaf College in the late 1960s. He
transferred to the University of Hawaii for his junior year, then
returned to St. Olaf, but some credits were not transferred.
   All Morrow has to do is submit his script to St. Olaf's
speech-theater department, which will grade it and give him enough
credit to graduate, said Bob Englund, director of the college's
news services.
   ``There's always something perversely funny about coming one
short of graduating,'' Morrow said. But he said since he's turned
40, it's time to complete his ``unfinished business.''
   ``I didn't really matriculate until now as a professional
screenwriter, so it seems a good and fitting ceremony to celebrate
the success of `Rain Man,''' Morrow said.
