<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Says He Will Travel to U.S., Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today
he wants to travel to the United States later this year and to meet
Polish-born Pope John Paul II at the Vatican.
   An adviser said the trip to Italy probably will take place in
late April.
   ``I will thank him for always remembering about Solidarity and
our country, that thanks to his and our prayers Poland can have
such possibilities (for national accord) that it now has,'' Walesa
said.
   He made his comments while answering reporters' questions before
a meeting with the visiting Belgian prime minister, Wilfried
Martens, at the Belgium Embassy in Warsaw.
   Walesa said he hopes to go to the United States either in
September or November.
   An adviser to Walesa, the Rev. Henryk Jankowski at St. Brygida's
Church in Gdansk, said by telephone that the visit to the Vatican
tentatively is planned for the second half of April. He said he had
no other details immediately.
   Walesa last met with Pope John Paul in June 1987 during the
pontiff's most recent visit to his homeland. The pope, born Karol
Wojtyla, served as archbishop of Krakow before his pontificate
began in 1979.
   The Solidarity leader made his first foreign trip in seven years
in December when he went to Paris for a meeting of Nobel Peace
Prize laureates organized by French President Francois Mitterrand.
   Walesa had difficulty obtaining a passport to travel abroad
until late last year, when authorities agreed to enter into
negotiations with Solidarity again for the first time since the
1981 imposition of martial law.
