<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Switzerland 2ndLd-Writethru a0532 03-30 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Switzerland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0532,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Consul Ordered Out of Iran; Publisher Gets Death Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with death threat against Swiss publisher planning
to print Satanic Verses. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said it ordered the Swiss consul in
Tehran expelled today, an apparent response to Switzerland's
insistence that Iran's consul in Geneva return home after being
accused of spying.
   Tehran Radio said Swiss ambassador Heinrich Reimann was summoned
to Iran's Foreign Ministry and told his consul, Jakob Schranz, had
one week to leave.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the ambassador was told
Schranz was an ``undesirable element,'' because he had been
involved in ``activities incompatible with his diplomatic status''
_ a term the normally implies spying.
   An operator who answered the telephone at the Swiss Embassy in
Tehran said there were no officials there to comment on the radio
report.
   The expulsion appeared to come in retaliation for Swiss pressure
on Iran's consul in Geneva, Manouchr Tale-Massouleh, to return
home. The Iranian diplomat left Wednesday for Tehran, according to
Iranian officials in Geneva.
   Swiss officials in Geneva said Iranian authorities had agreed to
have Tale-Massouleh leave after the diplomat was accused of spying.
   Josef Hermann, a spokesman for the Swiss federal prosecutor's
office, said Tale-Massouleh was not being expelled because an
accord had been reached on his departure.
   Hermann said Swiss authorities were conducting a criminal
investigation into two people suspected of helping the Iranian
diplomat gather information, but their nationalities or whereabouts
have not been disclosed.
   Questions about Tale-Massouleh's activities surfaced after the
Geneva consulate was occupied for five hours Dec. 14 by six Iranian
militants.
   The Iranians read what they said were confidential documents by
telephone to accomplices outside.
   At their trial in Geneva in January, they claimed the documents
showed Tale-Massouleh led efforts to spy on Iranian refugees in
Switzerland.
   Transcripts sent to Swiss authorities and media were dismissed
by the Iranian diplomat as forgeries.
   But Hermann said Swiss authorities verified ``certain points''
among the ``very voluminous'' documentation. He did not elaborate.
   The consulate occupiers, six men aged 25 to 41, all received
four-month suspended prison sentences. They said their action was a
protest against executions in Iran.
   The Geneva court threw out the prosecution's most serious charge
of hostage-taking. It said the accused deserved clemency because
their motive of ``drawing attention to the dramatic situation in
their country'' was honorable.
   In St. Gall, Switzerland, a Swiss publisher who planned to print
``The Satanic Verses'' in German received a death threat, prompting
police to provide him protection, authorities said today.
   Iranian clerics last month offered $5.2 million to any Moslem
who kills the novel's British author, Salman Rushdie, who has
remained in hiding since then. Many Moslems find the book
blasphemous.
   A St. Gall police spokesman said that after an anonymous
telephone threat against the publisher, Hans-Joerg Tobler,
``necessary measures were taken'' for his safety. The spokesman,
who declined to be identified, would not give further details.
   A spokeswoman for Tobler's company Panorama, based in Altstetten
near St. Gall, declined to say when the book was scheduled for
publication.
   News reports said Tobler was reconsidering whether to print the
book, but the spokeswoman said he was not available for comment.
   The novel includes passages in which prostitutes go by the names
of the prophet Mohammed's wives and which suggest Mohammed wrote
the holy Koran instead of Allah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
