<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MX-Midgetman     03-30 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MX-Midgetman,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Missile Plan Comes Under GOP Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ranking Republican on the House Armed
Services Committee is calling on the Bush administration and his
GOP colleagues to reject a Democratic plan to overhaul the nation's
land-based missile force.
   Rep. Bill Dickinson of Alabama said the plan under which 50 MX
missiles would be moved from silos to a mobile rail garrison basing
mode is a ``bad deal'' because it would place unacceptable limits
on key defense programs.
   He said it would limit the number of 10-warhead MX missiles to
the 50 already fielded and start construction of 300 to 500 of the
smaller, Midgetman intercontinental ballistic missiles.
   It also would mean negative growth in the defense budget and
reduced funding for Star Wars and the stealth bomber programs as a
way of paying for the Midgetman.
   ``Unless the terms of this deal improve dramatically, I hope
that President Bush and (Defense) Secretary (Richard B.) Cheney
ignore it altogether,'' Dickinson said in a statement issued
Wednesday.
   ``The illusion of small ICBM inevitability that has been
cultivated by congressional Democrats in recent months is just that
_ illusion,'' he added.
   Democrats have favored the single-warhead Midgetman while former
President Reagan and many congressional Republicans have pushed for
the 10-warhead MX. As a member of the House, Cheney was an MX
supporter.
   Since taking over as defense secretary, however, Cheney has not
indicated if he would back a plan based on the MX, the Midgetman or
a combination of the two. National security adviser Brent Scowcroft
is an opponent of the MX.
   On Capitol Hill, support has been building among majority
Democrats for the plan to move the 50 existing MX missiles from
vulnerable silos to a rail garrison basing mode _ placing them on
railroad cars and moving them around the country _ and build a
Midgetman force of 300 to 500.
   Dickinson said, however, that the plan represented a variant of
previous efforts to reduce Pentagon spending.
   ``What we are seeing now on the small ICBM is the same
two-fisted attack on defense that we see from the liberals on the
defense bill every year,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
