<SECOND>PM-Hungarian Hijack, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0528,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extradition Could Take Months For Teen-Age Hijackers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to INCLUDE identification of teen-agers,
plane returning to Hungary. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Czechoslovak teen-agers who
hijacked a jetliner after shooting their way onto the aircraft in
Prague may face extradition, but the process could take months, an
official said today.
   Hungary's state-run MTI news agency reported that the Malev
airlines jet had returned to the capital, Budapest, along with its
four crew members and the Hungarian consul-general, Lajos Taba.
   Taba traded himself to the hijackers Wednesday to gain the
release of most of the passengers before the plane took off for
Frankfurt.
   MTI and the official Czechoslovak news agency CTK identified the
youths as Stefan Macicko, 17, and Dusan Styk, 16, both of Banska.
Frankfurt police did not release their names.
   Frankfurt prosecutor's spokesman Hubert Harth said he did not
know if the hijackers had requested political asylum in West
Germany. ``Our main concern is dealing with the criminal act of
hijacking,'' he said.
   Officials say the two initially wanted to go to the United
States but were foiled when the crew said the Soviet-made
Tupolev-154 could not make the trip over the Atlantic.
   The teen-agers, armed with a sawed-off shotgun, rifle and fake
hand grenade, commandeered the aircraft Wednesday in Prague. They
surrendered less than three hours later, and no one was injured in
the accident.
   Harth said in a telephone interview the hijackers may be
extradited to Czechoslovakia but that it would be a slow process.
   ``A decision on possible extradition would have to be made at
federal government level, and that won't come quickly. It could
take months.''
   Hans Neitzel, chief spokesman for the Frankfurt police
department, said officials did not know why the boys decided to
hijack the airliner.
   ``They said they wanted to go to America, but why they wanted to
go, whether they have relatives there or what, we don't know. Maybe
it was just youthful adventure,'' he said Wednesday night.
   Witnesses at Prague's Ruzyne Airport told The Associated Press
the hijackers seized a woman, crashed through a glass wall of the
VIP lounge, fired several shots and threatened a flight attendant
to gain access to the jet.
   About 100 people were on board the jet, which had arrived from
Budapest and was en route to Amsterdam. Taba traded himself for 82
passengers.
</TEXT>
