<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Chemicals     03-30 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Chemicals,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wrecked Ship Found, but Chemicals Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wreck of a ship that sank two weeks ago with a
load of dangerous insecticide has been found, but a container of
the chemical is still missing, the Department of Transport said
today.
   The 263-ton Indonesian ship Perintis was found 35 miles
southeast of Brixham, on the south coast of England, said a
transport spokesman.
   The ship sank in the English Channel in a storm March 13, and
five of its six containers of Lindane insecticide were recovered.
The missing container was lost when tow ropes snapped as it was
being hauled back to Cherbourg in France.
   Ecologists have warned that if the container spills, it could
cause an ecological disaster with dire consequences for 30 years
afterward.
   The transport spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with
British custom, said the wreck was found by a remote-controlled
camera on a vessel chartered by the department.
   He said the container in which the chemical is stored has an
underwater life of a year.
   Lindane is a toxic insecticide used widely by farmers and
gardeners.
