<DOCNO> AP890330-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spy'sWife     03-30 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy's Wife,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Let Anne Pollard Be Transferred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today refused to move the wife of spy
Jonathan Pollard from a federal prison hospital where she says she
is isolated and mistreated.
   U.S. District Judge Harry MacLaughlin ordered that Anne
Henderson Pollard, 28, remain at the Federal Medical Center in
Rochester, and he denied an independent medical review.
   Mrs. Pollard had sued to be moved back to a federal prison in
Danbury, Conn.
   She said the hospital, where she was sent for a gastrointestinal
disorder and other conditions, was making her worse because she is
the only woman there, the staff hates her and she was put under
24-hour surveillance.
   Authorities said that the surveillance has been lifted and that
Mrs. Pollard was making herself sicker by not eating.
   MacLaughlin today said he found ``no deliberate indifference''
to Mrs. Henderson's needs.
   Jonathan Pollard, 34, was sentenced in 1987 to life in prison
for supplying classified documents to Israeli agents. Mrs. Pollard
was sentenced to five years in prison on charges including being an
accessory after the fact.
</TEXT>
