<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Acropolis     03-30 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Acropolis,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acropolis Restorers Gather to Save Temples</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 experts will meet Friday to
look at ways of saving the 2,400-year-old Acropolis temples from
the ravages of time and pollution.
   The Committee for the Preservation of the Acropolis Monuments
said the experts will focus on restoring the Parthenon temple's
eastern portico.
   The portico, which stood behind the monument's eastern colonade,
formed the antechamber to the main Parthenon temple and was one of
the most important places on the monument, said Charalambos Bouras,
who heads the committee.
   The participants, who include seismologists, architects and
chemists, will evaluate progress on the 10-year restoration work
that started in 1985.
   ``The Acropolis temples belong to humanity and are of
inestimable worth ... it's not only up to the Greeks to restore
them but the whole international community,'' Bouras said.
   Greece spends $9.6 million annually on restoration work on the
Acropolis, which was built between 447 B.C. and 405 B.C. The site
draws more than 2 million visitors every year.
</TEXT>
