<DOCNO> AP890330-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Shopping     03-30 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Shopping,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowd Incident Highlights Shortage of Consumer Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The line for imported boots started forming just
after dawn, but the goods sold out in 30 minutes.
   As the crowd pushed forward in vain, a railing gave way and four
people were hurt when they fell 12 feet to the ground.
   The incident, which occurred Tuesday and was reported Thursday
by the newspaper Moskovsky Komsomolets, highlights the dreary
outlook for Soviet shoppers who search the city for items such as
sugar, detergent, men's socks and chocolate.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has told them improving food
supplies and consumer goods are his top priority, although it will
take time. Frustrated consumers complain things have only gotten
worse.
   The weekly newspaper Moscow News recently counted 500 people
lined up for fur hats and 300 waiting to buy nightgowns made of a
synthetic fabric.
   Moskovsky Komsomolets said the four people who were hurt in the
shopping incident all lived outside of Moscow, some of the
thousands of Soviets who stream into the capital to search for
goods not available in their towns and villages. Bare as they are,
Moscow's shelves have more than provincial cities.
   Moscow News said it found a 62-year-old woman who had traveled
900 miles from the Caucasus city of Ordzhonikidze to shop in the
GUM department store on Red Square. She spent more than 90 minutes
in line to buy two nightgowns, one red and one blue.
   ``The red one is for my daughter, the second ... well, I don't
want it, old as I am. My daughter has a friend,'' it quoted her as
saying. ``If the girl doesn't like it, our next door neighbors
would, perhaps. I'm retired on a pension, so I am here to do some
shopping. Where I live, the shops are empty.''
   In another line, a young couple who took their vacation to shop
in Moscow bought three pairs of Romanian-made boots even though
they didn't fit.
   Shoes and boots have long been a sore spot with Soviet consumers.
   Economist Abel Aganbegyan, a key adviser to Gorbachev, said in
1987 that the Soviet Union produced 788 million pairs of leather
shoes in 1985, more than twice the number produced in the United
States, but nobody wanted them.
   ``These shoes lie around because they're not very comfortable,
they're not fashionable, they're not attractive,'' he said. ``If
someone buys them, it's only because there's nothing else. And if
they buy them, they never wear them.''
   That makes imported shoes highly desirable. In the Tuesday
incident, the line formed outside the shoe store an hour before the
shop opened, and the 200 pairs were gone in 30 minutes.
   Economics professor Tatyana Koryagina told the Moscow News the
only way to end the lines is to encourage a market economy in which
prices are set by demand rather than by the government. But
consumers oppose price increases and Gorbachev has promised there
won't be any for several years.
   There was a faint note of hope Thursday for shoe shoppers. The
Tass news agency said deals have been concluded with manufacturiers
in Italy and Yugoslavia to build 10 shoe factories in the Soviet
Union in the next decade.
   ``A flood of top-quality fashion shoes will engulf the Soviet
market,'' Tass said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0084 </DOCNO>
