<FIRST>u i PM-PrisonRevolt 2ndLd-Writethru a0594 03-30 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Revolt, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0594,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rebels Accept Gov't Offer to End Mutiny</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 6 grafs on accord reached; Pick up 4th graf pvs:
`Between 75...' Edits to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CATARINA PINULA, Guatemala (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel inmates who seized
control of Guatemala's largest prison agreed today to end their
5-day-old uprising, a government negotiator said.
   ``We have an agreement in principle,'' Gonzalo Menendez de la
Riva, the head government negotiator told reporters when he emerged
from a morning meeting with the rebels.
   Menendez, the special attorney general for human rights, said he
would take the accord to the capital, 15 miles west of the prison,
for the signature of Interior Minister Roberto Valle Valdizan, then
return to the prison.
   He said he expected a the agreement would be signed by both
sides today.
   Red Cross officials were reportedly preparing to evacuate the
civilians inside the prison once the accord was signed.
   The government offered late Wednesday to replace the warden and
all the guards at the 1,350-inmate Pavon prison farm if the rebels
surrendered. the warden and the guards if the mutineers surrender.
   Between 75 and 100 rebel inmates armed with M-1 rifles have been
in control of the prison, Guatemala's largest, since Sunday. At
least four guards and three inmates died in the Easter revolt.
   About 600 people _ mostly women and children _ were visiting
when the uprising began. Some stayed inside with the inmates, and
authorities differed on whether they were hostages or whether they
stayed to protect their loved ones from security force reprisals.
   The government said it would consider the rebels' request for
pardons for crimes committed during the uprising and guarantee
their physical safety once they surrendered their arms and the
roughly 500 people with them.
   About 110 prisoners who took no part in the revolt fled
Wednesday from the section that remained under inmate control and
were taken into custody.
   Twenty relatives of inmates trapped inside when the uprising
started began also made their way out.
   In its Wednesday offer, the government also promised to promote
``strict application'' of a law providing for reduction of
sentences through work and present to Congress the mutineers'
demand for a nationwide reduction of all prison sentences by five
years.
   Any pardon or amnesty for crimes committed during the rebellion
would have to be enacted by Congress.
   However, Edmundo Vasquez Martinez, president of the Supreme
Court, said Wednesday that the court could not grant pardons for
crimes committed at Pavon.
   The inmates offered to surrender if the warden and guards were
replaced at Pavon, which is about 15 miles east of Guatemala City,
negotiator Julio Escobar Arango said.
   About 100 black-helmeted military police arrived Wednesday to
reinforce the 1,000 police and army troopers ringing the prison.
President Vinicio Cerezo has said force would not be used unless
prisoners try to shoot their way out.
   The rebels were described as hardened criminals serving long
sentences for crimes such as murder and kidnapping. They reportedly
include former security forces members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SheriffResigns     03-30 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sheriff Resigns,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Resigns After Admitting Hot Tub Session With Inmate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff has resigned after admitting he
took an inmate home for dinner and shared a hot tub with him.
   Jack T. Dolan on Wednesday denied any impropriety and said his
only wish was to help an inmate perform a community service.
   County commissioners had removed the 53-year-old sheriff from
his separate job as head of the corrections department two weeks
ago after learning he was under investigation by the attorney
general's office and a special prosecutor.
   The 18-year sheriff said he brought Mark Woosley, 21, to his
home several times to work on a woodshop project and had dinner
with him before sending him back to jail.
   ``Following a job well done ... I offered the inmate the use of
my hot tub. In the presence of my brother, I spent approximately 10
to 15 minutes in the hot tub with him,'' Dolan said.
   Dolan said that when Woosley told other inmates, Woosley ``was
harassed for working with the sheriff and derogatory comments of a
sexual nature were made.''
   The inmate's girlfriend complained, and sheriff's department
officials contacted the attorney general's office.
   The sheriff said he erred by ``departing from the normal and
traditional model of the jailer-prisoner relationship and in
failing to foresee that my actions could be misperceived by
others.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
