<FIRST>r w AM-People-Brady     03-30 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Brady,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Press Secretary Given Standing Ovation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House Press Secretary James Brady
won two standing ovations Thursday as he presented awards to two
community colleges honored for outstanding assistance to the
disabled.
   Brady, who was shot in the head in the 1981 assassination
attempt on President Reagan, returned to the scene of the crime,
the Washington Hilton, to make the awards to Catonsville (Md.)
Community College and John Wood (Ill.) Community College.
   Brady, who is brain-damaged and must use a wheelchair as a
result of the shooting, was recently named vice chairman of the
National Organization on Disability.
   ``I am pleased to recognize the important work you have done,''
he told the presidents of the two colleges. ``But I also call on
you, as I call on everyone, to do more.'''
   Brady said educators in particular have a special role in making
American life accessible to the disabled, and that means more than
building wheelchair ramps. ``It means removing attitudinal
barriers,'' he said. ``I call on you to make America a better place
for all of us.''
   The National Organization on Disability-J.C. Penney awards were
presented at the 69th annual conference of the American Association
of Community and Junior Colleges. The educators rose to their feet
after Brady's brief speech and again when he was introduced by
association president David Ponitz as a man who ``should have a
chapter in the profiles of courage.''
   The Maryland college was honored for its programs for deaf,
blind and hearing-impaired students; the Illinois college was cited
for a special needs transition program that eases disabled
students' paths to employment and further education.
</TEXT>
