<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0568 03-30 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0568,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fishermen Help Clean Up; Spill Spreads to 500 Square Miles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with today's cleanup activities. Edits to
tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos; LaserGraphic NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government today said it won't
take over cleanup of the nation's worst-ever oil spill but will
watch closely because of the slick's ``enormous potential'' for
damage to the environment.
   The 500-square-mile slick continued to spread, uncontained by
the efforts of 444 personnel from the Coast Guard and other
agencies and dozens of fishermen backed by three Coast Guard
helicopters, two cutters, 33 contract vessels, five tugboats and a
dozen skimmers.
   Only 6,000 barrels of the 240,000 that spilled from an Exxon
tanker Friday have been recovered, officials said.
   ``Anyone who goes up and looks at the slick has to be humbled by
it,'' said Chief Petty Officer Todd Nelson.
   At the White House, Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner,
Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William Reilly and
Coast Guard Commandant Adm. Paul Yost reported their first-hand
observations to President Bush, who decided against a federal
takeover.
   Bush gave ``top priority to assessing the adequacy of
environmental protection,'' Reilly said.
   ``This is obviously a disaster of enormous potential magnitude
on the environment,'' Reilly said. The habitats of sea otters and
sea lions are likely to be hardest hit, and the government also
will monitor salmon and herring in Prince William Sound, where the
disaster occurred Friday, he said.
   Exxon, whose 987-foot tanker Exxon Valdez struck a reef 25 miles
from Port Valdez, is doing a ``very craftsmanlike job'' with the
cleanup, Yost said.
   Skinner said the response ``could have been quicker,'' and
``most of the damage was done in the first few hours.''
   Yost defended Coast Guard radar operators who failed to spot and
warn the tanker, saying it was not in a treacherous or narrow area.
He said the Coast Guard will look into the license of the tanker's
captain.
   A daily newspaper covering shipping reported today that the
captain failed to disclose in his last license application that he
had been convicted of drunken driving twice in the previous five
years. A Coast Guard commander in New York told the Journal of
Commerce that Capt. Joseph Hazelwood checked ``no'' in 1986 to the
application's question about traffic violations.
   Of the 1.2 million barrels of crude oil the tanker was carrying,
Exxon said about 480,000 were transferred to another tanker, which
left for Hawaii today.
   Crews maneuvered another vessel to take the remainder of the oil
from the grounded ship. The operation is expected to take until
Saturday.
   In Anchorage, the first of an expected flood of lawsuits was
filed. The class-action suit seeking unspecified damages was filed
in the names two Prince William Sound fishermen. They accuse Exxon,
the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. and the state of gross negligence
in the spill and cleanup.
   The Wall Street Journal reported today that a barge intended as
a key piece of equipment against oil spills was not working Friday,
and Alyeska conceded it violated its own requirement that it notify
state environmental officials that the vessel was out of commission.
   Exxon, which has been heavily criticized for its response to the
10.1 million-gallon spill, said it will re-evaluate how it handles
such problems.
   ``Now that (the spill) has happened, it's incumbent on us and
the industry to profit in the maximum extent from the experience,''
said William Stevens, president of Exxon USA, the parent of the
Exxon Shipping Co. Inc.
   Wind and currents have stretched the slick into ragged patches
of iridescent oil on crystal blue water. The heavy goo surrounds
several islands.
   The oil is headed toward the Montague Strait, an outlet to the
Gulf of Alaska. Gov. Steve Cowper said that is where everyone hopes
the oil goes, ``rather than bouncing around like a pinball in
Prince William Sound and polluting it for years.''
   Mayor John Devens has estimated the loss to the fishing industry
at $150 million.
   ``This spill will devastate the ecosystem long after wildlife
that now has been exposed has died,'' said Jon Lyman, a spokesman
for the Alaska Department of Fish and Game. He said thousands of
birds, including bald eagles, may die in the coming years.
   In another development, William Woody, chief of the four-member
National Transportation Safety Board team assigned to the disaster,
said a Coast Guard officer told investigators he smelled alcohol on
Exxon Valdez skipper Joseph Hazelwood's breath a few hours after
the ship ran aground.
   But the Guardsman and a harbor pilot agreed Hazelwood appeared
competent, Woody said.
   Exxon officials said Hazelwood was not on the bridge when the
accident occurred a half mile outside shipping lanes. Third mate
Gregory Cousins, who the Coast Guard says lacked proper
certification, was giving the orders.
   On the advice of their lawyers, Hazelwood and Cousins have
refused to talk to investigators, Woody said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
