<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion-BrighamYoung     03-30 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion-Brigham Young,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Confirm Fusion Research Results At Brigham Young University</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third researcher has achieved cold
nuclear fusion, Brigham Young University reported, nearly a week
after two University of Utah scientists stunned the scientific
world with their own announcement.
   BYU Chemist Steven Jones will discuss his experiments in
room-temperature nuclear fusion at a colloquium at Columbia
University in New York City on Friday, school spokesman Paul
Richards said Wednesday.
   Nuclear fusion, the energy secret of the sun, has been sought by
scientists for 20 years.
   University of Utah researchers announced March 23 that they had
used a simple, low-cost experiment to achieve fusion.
   The announcment ignited skepticism and curiosity in the
scientific community and widespread interest among businesses eager
to cash in on the discovery.
   It also prompted speculation that the Utah researchers rushed to
disclose their findings to claim the limelight before the work
underwent close scrutiny in scientific publications.
   Electrochemists Stanley Pons of Utah and Martin Fleischmann of
the University of Southampton in England announced they had
sustained a controlled nuclear fusion reaction for more than 100
hours in a small glass flask.
   They said their process involved an electrical current used to
drive nuclear particles through a lattice of palladium and platinum
electrodes, forcing positively charged particles to fuse together
and create a new atom.
   Practical ways to achieve controlled nuclear fusion have long
been sought because of its potential as an inexpensive, virtually
inexhaustible source of energy that produces less radioactive waste
than nuclear reactors.
   Nuclear reactors are powered by fission, in which atoms are
split, not fused.
   Pons' and Fleischmann's process has not been subjected to peer
review, and the experiment has yet to be duplicated elsewhere.
Attempts are under way at several laboratories, including Los
Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico and Italy's National
Association of Alternative Energy near Rome.
   Richards confirmed a report in the Wall Street Journal on
Wednesday that Jones had discovered that the nuclei of deuterium
atoms, a heavy form of hydrogen, can fuse inside a solid crystal
unaided by an external catalyst or the superhot temperatures
previously thought necessary for hydrogen fusion.
   Unlike the University of Utah experiment, which reportedly
produced four times as much energy as it consumed, Jones' work
produced extremely small amounts, Richards said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0090 </DOCNO>
