<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nekrasov     03-30 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nekrasov,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer Posthumously Readmitted to Writers Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ukrainian Writers Union has posthumously
readmitted author Viktor Nekrasov who once won a Stalin prize but
was banished for speaking out in defense of Alexander Solzhenitsyn,
Tass said Thursday.
   Nekrasov won what was then the Soviet Union's highest literary
honor in 1946 for his book ``In the Trenches of Stalingrad'' about
the defense of the Volga River city in World War II.
   But the Kiev native expelled from the Writers Union and was
forced to leave the Soviet Union in 1974 for defending
Solzhenitsyn, who had been expelled. He settled in France and died
in 1987.
   ``Our organization has come out for Nekrasov's books to be
published anew and for his works written abroad to be printed in
Ukrainian journals,'' Yuri Mushketik, head of the Ukrainian Writers
Union, told Tass.
   He said a plaque will be hung at the Kiev house where Nekrasov
lived.
</TEXT>
