<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryOrders     03-30 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Orders,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orders Post First Back-to-Back Declines in Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods dropped 2.3 percent in February, the second straight monthly
decline, the government said Thursday in a report offering more
evidence the economy may be slowing.
   Orders fell to a seasonally adjusted $230.7 billion last month
after dropping 1.2 percent in January, the first back-to-back
declines since orders fell for four consecutive months starting in
February 1986, the Commerce Department said.
   Last month's decline was in line with a spate of other
government reports that showed slower growth in February and with
widespread expectations that the economy will cool off in this
seventh year of its record peacetime expansion.
   ``This confirms that February was a very weak month,'' said
economist David Wyss of Data Resources Inc. in Lexington, Mass.
``It leaves unanswered the question of whether this is the start of
the slowdown we're expecting.''
   The decline would have been even bigger were it not for a 22.4
percent surge last month in defense orders, which are subject to
wide swings depending on when government contracts are signed.
   Excluding the military, orders were down 3 percent last month.
   The biggest negative factor in last month's orders picture was a
7.2 percent decline in the transportation category, reflecting
fewer orders for planes and cars.
   But even excluding the volatile transportation area, all other
orders still were down 1.4 percent last month.
   Economist Michael P. Niemira of Mitsubishi Bank in New York said
that while the economy is growing at a slower pace than last year,
the drop in factory orders was largely a fallback from strong
demand in December, when orders rose 4.7 percent.
   ``It's more of a reaction to the strong numbers that we saw in
the past as opposed to true weakness,'' Niemira said.
   The Federal Reserve Board for a year has been pushing up
interest rates in an effort to restrain economic growth to reduce
inflationary pressures.
   The economy grew a robust 3.9 percent last year, the best
showing in four years, but analysts believe the pace will be closer
to 2.7 percent this year, with the slowdown most evident in the
second and third quarters.
   Factory orders had increased a healthy 9.7 percent in 1988 in
part due to an export-led boom that showed signs of stalling late
in the year.
   The back-to-back declines in orders during the first two months
of 1989 may suggest the Fed's slowdown campaign is taking effect,
Wyss said.
   ``The Fed's been raising rates for a year now,'' he said. ``It's
about time we started to see it in the real growth (statistics).''
   In the key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a
good indicator of future industry investment plans, orders dropped
8.2 percent in February to $37.1 billion after rising 2.3 percent
in January.
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, items expected to last
three years or more, were down 3.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted
$124.2 billion after dropping 2.8 percent during the previous month.
   Declines were recorded in nearly all major industries, including
a 3.2 percent drop in orders for primary metals, with the steel
industry accounting for much of that decline.
   Demand for non-durable goods was down 1 percent to $106.5
billion last month, with the largest decreases coming in orders for
chemicals and rubber and plastics products.
   Shipments of manufactured goods were down 1.7 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $227.6 billion in February. It was the biggest
decline since March 1986, when shipments were down 2.4 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
