<FIRST>u w PM-LatinLeaders 1stLd-Writethru a0593 03-30 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Latin Leaders, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Meet With Latin Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Updates throughout with visit by Costa Rican president</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will meet soon with three Latin
American presidents _ Venezuela's Carlos Andres Perez, El
Salvador's Alfredo Cristiani and Costa Rica's Oscar Arias _ Bush's
spokesman said today.
   Perez, who took office in early February, will visit the White
House on Saturday for a working breakfast with Bush, Secretary of
State James A. Baker, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and
national security adviser Brent Scowcroft, press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   The group is expected to discuss the Latin American debt crisis,
an issue on which Perez has taken a leadership role. Brady recently
announced an administration plan to deal with the more than $440
billion owed by the Latin countries.
   Cristiani, who won last week's election in El Salvador, will be
in Washington on April 7 for a meeting with Bush. At the time of
his election, Bush telephoned his congratulations to Cristiani and
expressed U.S. support for Salvadoran democracy.
   U.S. officials are known to be concerned about human rights
violations, some of them committed by the nation's military in the
violence-plagued country.
   Vice President Dan Quayle issued a stern warning to military
leaders and others on a one-day visit to el Salvador in February,
making clear that future U.S. aid would be conditioned on progress
in that area.
   Cristiani's conservative Arena party has been accused of
affiliation with death squad activity in the past, especially its
former leader Roberto D'Abuisson, who denies such involvement.
   Fitzwater said Arias will stop in Washington on Tuesday en route
to Canada. He and Bush are expected to discuss the emerging Central
American peace process, focusing on Nicaragua. Arias has been a
leader in the meetings of the five Central American presidents as
they attempt to work out a plan for disbanding the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels.
</TEXT>
