<HEAD>Failure of Disneyland Flying Elephant Ride Slightly Injures Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mechanical failure of Disneyland's
Dumbo the Flying Elephant ride caused one car to tip sideways and
slightly injured a couple and their little girl, a spokesman said.
   The fiberglass elephant in which the family was riding partially
separated from a supporting arm Wednesday and tipped about 45
degrees, said Bob Roth, a spokesman for Disneyland.
   Eli Martinez, 33, of Garden Grove was belted in but his upper
body apparently grazed an elevated concrete walkway around the ride
and he suffered bruises and scrapes, Roth said. Martinez's wife and
child, also belted in, suffered lesser bruises.
   Dumbo features cars on the end of arms that go up and down as
the ride rotates. The faulty car was about 6 feet off the ground
when it broke, Roth said.
   The ride was closed to determine the cause of the failure.
   It was the second accident at the park in March. A hundred
riders were stranded for up to four hours when the aerial Skyway
buckets halted March 18. That ride was put back in operation March
22.
