<FIRST>u w PM-NaziDeported 1stLd-Writethru a0476 03-30 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nazi Deported, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nazi Death Camp Guard Deported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 2-4 with 2 grafs to update with Eckert's arrival
in Austria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael S. Bernstein's final assignment for
the Justice Department before his death in the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 last December was to negotiate the deportation of a
former Nazi death camp guard to Austria. The deportation is now
completed.
   Josef Eckert, 65, who was an SS guard at the Auschwitz death
camp during World War II, flew out of the United States on Tuesday
night and arrived today in Salzburg, Austria via Zurich,
Switzerland.
   Justice Department spokesman Loye Miller said Wednesday that
Eckert had fallen asleep at Heathrow Airport in London and missed
his connecting flight that day.
   Eckert had concealed his Auschwitz service from U.S. immigration
officials when he obtained a visa to come to the United States in
1956, the department said. At the time, he was living in Austria.
   Eckert, who had been living in La Puente, Calif., admitted last
Sept. 27 that he had been a member of the SS guard unit assigned to
Auschwitz where he guarded prisoners. Millions of people were
murdered during his time of service there.
   Bernstein, a member of the department's Office of Special
Investigations, negotiated with the Austrian government to arrange
Eckert's return to that country, and Austria agreed to the return
last December.
   Bernstein was flying home from those negotiations when the plane
exploded over Scotland on Dec. 21.
   ``The successful completion of the Eckert case is a fitting
tribute to Mike Bernstein's prosecutorial and diplomatic skills and
to his dedication to the pursuit of justice,'' Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh said in a statement.
</TEXT>
