<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     03-30 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Police Seized Large Amounts Of Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official Thursday
accused ethnic Albanians of trying to stage an armed uprising in a
southern province and said authorities had seized weapons and
explosives.
   Stane Dolanc, vice president of Yugoslavia's collective state
presidency, said the ``separatists'' want to force Kosovo to secede
from Yugoslavia.
   Riots in Kosovo, an autonomous province in the republic of
Serbia, broke out Monday and Tuesday after legislators approved
constitutional changes giving Serbian officials greater control
over the region.
   The Belgrade newspaper Vecernje Novosti said 29 people died in
the unrest. The state-run Tanjug news agency put the death toll at
27, while Kosovo officials said 23 died and more than 200 were
injured.
   The province, under a dusk-to-dawn curfew, was quiet Thursday.
   Serbs contend the constitutional changes, which took effect
Tuesday, are necessary to protect Kosovo's Slav minority from the
ethnic Albanian majority, who make up 85 percent of the 1.9 million
population.
   Ethnic Albanians claim the changes threaten autonomy they won
under Yugoslavia's 1974 constitution.
   Dolanc, in a speech to the state Parliament in his native
republic of Slovenia, said documents seized by police in Kosovo
revealed the ``true aims'' of ethnic Albanian ``separatists'':
secession from Yugoslavia.
   ``An open call was made for armed revolt, as supported by the
fact that a large amount of explosives, weapons and other war
material was seized'' in Kosovo, Dolanc said.
   Dolanc was the federal Interior Minister in 1981, when riots by
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo killed nine people.
   There have been frequent allegations since then that Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians have organized an underground movement that seeks
to separate the region from Yugoslavia and unite it with
neighboring Albania. Ethnic Albanians deny it.
   The Slovene Communist Party daily Delo took the unusual step of
publishing what it said were casualty figures from an emigre
Albanian group in Brussels. Those figures listed 137 dead and 370
injured Monday and Tuesday.
   ``I can guarantee to you that this is a lie,'' Dolanc said.
   There were persistent reports in Pristina, Kosovo's capital,
that up to 150 ethnic Albanian intellectuals were detained or
questioned by police.
   The Belgrade daily Borba said ``intellectuals who have long been
known to act from hostile positions of Albanian nationalism and
separatism have been detained, or isolated.''
   In addition to the ethnic problems, Kosovo is Yugoslavia's
poorest region. It has an unemployment rate of 30 percent, compared
with the nationwide rate of 15 percent.
</TEXT>
