<FIRST>r i AM-Hijack     03-30 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Says Czechoslovakia Requested Extradition of Hijackers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said
Thursday the Czech government has asked for the extradition of two
teen-agers who hijacked a Hungarian airliner and forced it to fly
from Prague to Frankfurt.
   The extradition request would be ``very carefully considered''
before it will be acted upon, said Peter Rothen, a spokesman for
the Foreign Ministry in Bonn.
   The state-run Czech news agency CTK reported the extradition
request was delivered to the West German Embassy in Prague, the
Czech capital.
   Rothen, citing a 1970 international agreement on aircraft
hijacking, of which West Germany and Czechoslovakia are a party,
said the agreement stipulates only that hijackers will be
prosecuted.
   ``It will definitely take some time. This is a decision that
must be very carefully considered,'' Rothen said in an interview.
   The CTK reports identified the youths as Stefan Macicko, 17, and
Dusan Styk, 16, both of Banska Bystrica in Czechoslovakia. The two,
armed with a sawed-off shotgun, rifle and fake hand grenade,
commandeered the aircraft in Prague on Wednesday.
   They got aboard the jetliner after seizing a woman hostage and
crashing through a glass wall at the VIP lounge in Prague. The
woman was released shortly thereafter.
   The incident ended less than three hours later when they
surrendered after the plane landed at Frankfurt airport. No
injuries were reported.
   Officials have said the hijackers initially wanted to go to the
United States but changed their minds when the crew convinced them
the Soviet-made Tupolev-154 jet could not make the trip across the
Atlantic.
   The hijackers released 82 passengers, including all women and
children, before the airliner left Prague.
   In Budapest, the state-run MTI news agency reported the Malev
airlines jet returned to the Hungarian capital with the crew of
four and Hungarian consul-general Lajos Taba.
   Taba traded himself to the hijackers Wednesday to gain the
release of all but 11 passengers before the plane left Prague.
   Prosecutor's spokesman Hubert Harth, when asked if the youths
applied for political asylum in West Germany, responded: ``I don't
know if they asked for asylum. Our main concern is dealing with the
criminal act of hijacking.''
   Harth said they appeared in juvenile court and were told of the
charges against them.
</TEXT>
