<DOCNO> AP890330-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-30 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Detainees End Embassy Sit-In, Denounce British Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six black activists left the
British Embassy in anger Thursday, complaining of maltreatment
during a 26-hour sit-in protesting police restrictions on their
activities.
   An escaped detainee remained at the U.S. Consulate in
Johannesburg, a day after he eluded guards at a hospital where he
was on a hunger strike.
   Prominent anti-apartheid church leaders, including Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu, conferred with Law and Order Minister
Adriaan Vlok about the fate of the estimated 250 activists who
remain detained without charge, including up to 50 reportedly on
hunger strikes.
   ``I expect some action in the next few days,'' said the Rev.
Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African Council of
Churches, who joined Tutu and two other clergymen in urging Vlok to
free all detainees.
   The six former detainees who entered the British Embassy in
Pretoria on Wednesday expressed bitterness at Britain's refusal to
provide them with food, water and mattresses or to allow use of
toilets and telephones during their stay in an entrance hall. They
also said they would defy restrictions imposed on them following
their release from jail.
   Lawyers for the six said South African authorities had given
assurances the activists would not be arrested if they left the
embassy. No assurances were given that restrictions would be
lifted, the lawyers said.
   Scores of detainees released following recent widespread hunger
strikes have been placed under restrictions, barring them from
political activities, confining them to their homes at night, and
requiring them to report twice daily to police stations.
   British officials made clear from the start they disapproved of
the activists' protest and asked them to leave. The six requested
Britain to pressure South African authorities to lift all
restrictions on former detainees, and the embassy replied that
Britain could make effective representations only if the sit-in
ended.
   Tutu expressed disappointment at Britain's handling of the
protest, saying: ``I would have hoped they behaved in a way that
showed they cared about the welfare of people.''
   The National Union of Mineworkers, an anti-apartheid black
union, described Britain's stance as ``shocking and inhuman.''
   ``Denying them facilities necessary for human habitation
confirms our long-held views that apartheid repression is fully
supported by the British government for the realization of super
profits accruing from their sanction-busting companies in South
Africa,'' the union said.
   The protest coincided with a visit to neighboring Zimbabwe by
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who urged negotiations to
resolve South Africa's racial conflict.
   Simon Ntombela, 27, remained in the U.S. Consulate in a
Johannesburg office building after escaping Wednesday from a
hospital in Durban, 360 miles away. Ntombela, a black teacher and
anti-apartheid organizer, reportedly took a commercial flight to
Johannesburg.
   The Human Rights Commission, a private group, said Ntombela was
seeking unconditional freedom for all detainees. Before his escape,
he had been on a hunger strike for two weeks.
   The government said Wednesday it would place hunger strikers in
prison or in hospitals in Bloemfontein, a relatively remote
provincial center, to prevent escapes and publicity about them.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained for varying
periods under a state of emergency declared in June 1986 to quell
unrest in black townships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
