<FIRST>r w AM-AgentOrange     03-30 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Service Agencies Awarded Grants From Settlement Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight agencies serving Vietnam veterans and
their families were awarded grants Thursday from settlement of a
suit by veterans who claimed exposure to Agent Orange gave them
cancer and other illnesses.
   The programs will provide a wide range of services, with
emphasis placed on helping veterans' children who have birth
defects and other disabilities.
   Among the recipients was an agency that offers legal advice to
disadvantaged Vietnam veterans in San Francisco, another that
enables veterans to participate in the Outward Bound program and a
housing program in New Mexico for the families of veterans
receiving treatment for post-traumatic stress disorder.
   The eight grants, totalling $581,000, are the first of many to
be allocated from a $52 million fund. The fund is expected to grow
with interest to $70 million during the seven- to 10-year life of
the program.
   The money is part of a $240 million settlement of a class action
suit brought more than 10 years ago by veterans who claimed
exposure to the defoliant Agent Orange during the Vietnam war
caused cancer, birth defects in their children and other illnesses.
   The chemical was sprayed over Southeast Asia during the 1960s by
the U.S. military, which hoped to deprive communist troops of crops
and cover.
   A large portion of the settlement, $170 million, has been
allocated to the Agent Orange Veteran Payment Program, which
provides cash payments to totally disabled Vietnam veterans and to
the widows or children of veterans who died. Distribution of these
payments began earlier this month.
   The Agent Orange Class Assistance Program, from which the grants
are being awarded, was designed to reach veterans and their
families who do not meet the eligibility requirements for direct
payments.
   Settlement of the lawsuit, brought in 1978, was reached in 1984
on the eve of trial in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, N.Y., when
the veterans and defendants _ seven manufacturers of Agent Orange _
agreed to the terms. The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the settlement
last June.
   Dennis Rhoades, executive director of the assistance program,
said at a news conference that special attention would be made to
fund programs that are innovative and that can strengthen a network
of services for Vietnam veterans and their families after the
settlement fund is exhausted.
   He described the eight grants awarded Thursday as ``flagship
grants'' that would form the basis of the program's direction.
   Because of concern expressed by veterans about children with
birth defects and other developmental disabilities, Rhoades said
those areas would be given the highest priority in funding.
   The eight organizations receiving grants were:
   _The Federation for Children with Special Needs in Boston,
$50,000 for a program of training and networking of Vietnam
families with disabled children.
   _The Occupational Center of Essex County, N.J., $71,000 for a
program of respite care for severely disabled children of Vietnam
veterans.
   _The National Handicapped Sports Association in Bethesda, Md.,
$64,000 for a program of outdoor recreational training for disabled
children of Vietnam veterans.
   _The Team of Advocates for Special Kids in Fountain Valley,
Calif., $61,000 for an advocacy training and referral program for
veterans' families of disabled children.
   _Swords to Plowshares of San Francisco, $90,000 for a legal
advocacy program for disadvantaged Vietnam veterans.
   _The American Red Cross Chapter in Albuquerque, N.M., $95,000
for a program of housing and other support for the families of
veterans receiving treatment for post-traumatic stress disorder.
   _The Family Services Association of Green Bay, Wis., $55,000 for
a counseling program.
   _The Paralyzed Veterans of America in Washington, D.C., $95,000
for a program allowing Vietnam veterans being treated for
post-traumatic stress disorder to participate in the Outward Bound
wilderness experience.
</TEXT>
