<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Chappell     03-30 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Chappell,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Chappell Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William V. Chappell, an influential
congressman who lost his House seat last year amid questions about
whether he was tied to the pentagon procurement scandal, died
Thursday. He was 67.
   Chappell, a Democrat who had represented the 4th District in
northeast Florida, died at the National Institutes of Health in
Bethesda, Md. He was hospitalized Feb. 23 for treatment of bone
cancer, which he had battled privately for at least three years.
   ``He fought the good fight. He never gave up and never lost his
sense of humor,'' Judith Chappell Gadd, his eldest child, said
Thursday.
   Florida political leaders praised Chappell's long public service
and defended his name, which had been linked to the Pentagon
procurement scandal.
   Chappell, of Ormond Beach, lost to Republican newcomer Craig
James of DeLand last fall by 791 votes, less than 1 percent of
those cast. Chappell challenged the outcome for a month before
conceding.
   James' campaign emphasized reports that federal agents were
investigating whether Chappell received funds diverted from defense
contractor Unisys Corp. through Armtec Inc., a small subcontractor
in Chappell's district. The Palatka manufacturer closed after its
records were seized by FBI agents in a raid June 14 and Unisys
canceled its contract.
   No criminal charges were filed against Chappell and he
vehemently denied wrongdoing.
   ``Despite how the career might have ended, he certainly was a
long-term servant of the people of Florida and I'm sure in his many
years of serving his community that he was able to bring a lot of
federal assistance to his district,'' said Gov. Bob Martinez.
   In Washington, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, called
Chappell a ``great legislator ... the kind of man we wanted to help
make them when Congress has to make tough choices. He was a
champion of a strong Navy _ going all the way back to his days as a
naval aviator in World War II.''
   Chappell was chairman of the powerful House defense
appropriations subcommittee.
   Before his 10 terms in Congress, Chappell served in the Florida
House for 10 years and was its speaker in 1961. He was a county
prosecutor from 1949 to 1954.
   The former congressman recently told an interviewer that he was
enjoying his forced retirement and was fishing and enjoying his
family.
   His wife, Jeane, kept a vigil by her husband's hospital bed, and
his four children and two stepchildren were in Bethesda when he
died.
   Services were scheduled Tuesday at churches in Daytona Beach and
Ocala.
</TEXT>
