<FIRST>r w AM-UnitedProtest     03-30 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-United Protest,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Flight Attendants To Protest Stalled Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendants at United Airlines, upset
with stalled contract negotiations, plan a series of informational
pickets at 11 major U.S. cities served by the carrier, their union
said Thursday.
   The Association of Flight Attendants said the pickets would
begin Friday at airports in Washington, Miami, Chicago, Cleveland,
Denver, Seattle, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Honolulu and Newark,
N.J.
   LaGuardia airport in New York will be added to the sites Sunday,
the union said in a statment.
   The pickets will be off-duty flight attendants and service
should not be affected, the union said.
   The union represents 13,000 United flight attendants. The union
and the airline for 19 months have been trying to negotiate a new
contract. A tentative agreement was reached in November 1987 but
was rejected by 78 percent of the union members who voted on the
proposal.
   The airline has been seeking wage and other concessions from the
union, which has argued those demands are unfair because United
posted record operating profits last year.
   The flight attendants union has authorized a strike vote against
United but will not decide for at least two weeks whether to
schedule one, a union spokeswoman said.
