<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Swiss     03-30 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Swiss,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Expels Swiss Consul In Response To Swiss Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Thursday ordered the Swiss consul
to leave Tehran and accused him of spying after its own consul in
Geneva was forced to leave.
   Switzerland's ambassador in Tehran, Heinrich Reimann, lodged a
formal protest after the Iranian Foreign Ministry summoned him
Thursday afternoon and told him the consul, Jakob Schranz, had to
leave, a Swiss spokesman said.
   Tehran radio said the Foreign Ministry told the ambassador that
Schranz was an ``undesirable element'' because he was involved in
``activities incompatible with his diplomatic status,'' a term used
to denote spying.
   Josef Hermann, a spokesman for the Swiss Federal Prosecutor's
office, said Iran's consul in Geneva, Manouchehr Tale-Massouleh,
``engaged in certain activities that led to his having to leave
Switzerland'' Wednesday night, but he did not elaborate.
   Reimann, whose embassy also handles U.S. interests in Tehran,
told Iranian officials the Iranian order was ``unacceptable''
because ``no real reason'' was given, Swiss Foreign Ministry
spokesman Michel Pache told reporters in Bern.
   Pache said Switzerland considered it a ``purely retaliatory
measure'' after Tale-Massouleh was forced out of the country.
   Swiss authorities wanted Tale-Massouleh to leave at the end of
February, but Iran wanted him to stay until his tour of duty
expired at the end of April, Pache said. A compromise was reached
for him to leave at the end of March, he said.
   Hermann said Swiss authorities are investigating two people
suspected of helping the Iranian diplomat gather information, but
their nationalities or whereabouts were not disclosed.
   Questions about Tale-Massouleh's activities surfaced after the
Geneva consulate was occupied for five hours Dec. 14 by six Iranian
militants who said they were protesting executions in Iran.
   At their trial in Geneva in January, they claimed documents in
the consulate showed Tale-Massouleh led efforts to spy on Iranian
refugees in Switzerland, but the diplomat denied it.
   Hermann said Swiss authorities verified ``certain points'' among
the ``very voluminous'' documentation. He did not elaborate.
   The consulate occupiers, six men aged 25 to 41, all received
four-month suspended prison sentences.
</TEXT>
