<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FamilyKilling     03-30 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Killing,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator Has Found Flaws In Prosecution Of Man Imprisoned In
'67 Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farm worker imprisoned for life after
his seven children were fatally poisoned in 1967 was not fairly
treated by prosecutors two decades ago, an official investigating
the case was quoted as saying.
   Dade County State Attorney Janet Reno, appointed by Gov. Bob
Martinez to review the case of James Richardson, met with Martinez
and aides to state Cabinet members Wednesday. The governor and the
six independently elected Cabinet members will hold a hearing next
week to decide whether to pardon Richardson.
   Ms. Reno refused to comment on the investigation. But the St.
Petersburg Times, in Thursday's editions, quoted several officials
who attended the meeting as saying that she has uncovered
significant flaws in the murder conviction.
   Peter Dunbar, general counsel for Martinez, told the newspaper
there was obviously a serious question in Ms. Reno's mind about
whether Richardson should be in prison.
   Dunbar said Ms. Reno found ``approximately six inches of
documents'' that should have gone to defense attorneys when
Richardson was tried. Under state law, a defendant has a right to
information collected by prosecutors, particularly information that
could exonerate him.
   Richardson, now 53, was sentenced to die in Florida's electric
chair in 1968 after an all-white jury convicted him of the
first-degree murder in the oldest child's death. Richardson is
black.
   His sentence was commuted to life in prison in 1972 when the
U.S. Supreme Court outlawed the death penalty.
   The Richardson children died after eating a lunch heavily laced
with the insecticide parathion. Prosecutors charged Richardson
poisoned the food before he left for work, in order to collect
insurance. Jurors were never told that Richardson had only asked
about an insurance policy and never purchased one.
   Richardson's supporters have accused Bessie Reese, the
children's baby sitter, of killing them. The elderly woman is now
mentally incompetent and in a nursing home.
   The documents withheld from defense attorneys apparently
included a request for a search warrant indicating that Ms. Reese
had traces of parathion on her clothes.
   ``There is what I was afraid of,'' said Jim York, chief deputy
for Attorney General Bob Butterworth. ``The prosecutors didn't give
the defense everything. When it comes up this late in a
prosecution, it's serious.''
   York said that in addition to the clemency study being conducted
in the executive branch, he's asked his criminal appeals division
to look at the case.
   If the problem is as serious as it appears, York said, the
division would probably ask if the prosecution can give Richardson
a new trial. If the 20-year lapse of time makes that impossible,
Richardson could be set free, York indicated.
</TEXT>
