<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam     03-30 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Acknowleges Shortcomings In Reform Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's ruling Communist Party has
blamed itself for ``many shortcomings'' in carrying out economic
reforms endorsed two years ago, Hanoi radio reported Thursday.
   The criticism came at a Central Committee meeting that ended
Wednesday, the radio said.
   It broadcast a committee statement noting improvements since the
reforms began _ particularly in agriculture, the mainstay of the
economy _ but added that ``improvements achieved so far have not
been uniform and fundamental while the socio-economic situation
remains fraught with acute difficulties.''
   ``The party's leadership task and the state's management work
have displayed many shortcomings,'' it said.
   Party leaders have been slow to implement party congress
resolutions and renovate the party and state organizations, the
statement said, adding that the 10-day meeting's purpose was ``to
review two years' implementation of the sixth party congress
resolutions and establish orientations and tasks for the next three
years.''
   The Sixth National Party Congress of late 1986 endorsed
decentralization, Western-style economic reforms and more relaxed
policies in other areas of society.
   Vietnamese officials have said the reforms boosted production in
some areas but barriers remain, including a traditionalist
bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
