<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Taxes     03-30 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Taxes,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Defends Support for Closing Tax Loopholes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's spokesman said Thursday that
the administration's support for closing tax loopholes does not
violate the president's ``no new taxes'' pledge.
   Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We're always vigilant
to close tax loopholes, and if we can find any loopholes that allow
us to get more revenue, we're always willing to take action if we
can.''
   Fitzwater was asked to respond to remarks by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady, who suggested that budget negotiations with
Congress might produce mesures to close loopholes in the tax system.
   Brady said that such measures should not be interpreted as tax
increases. He said the ones he had in mind were small.
   Fitzwater said Brady was ``not sending any particular signals.
... We are not signaling new revenue increases.''
   Asked how the administration defined the difference between a
tax increase and a loophole-closer, Fitzwater said, ``Well, it's
like pornography; we'll know it when we see it.''
