<DOCNO> AP890330-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b a BC-Pulitzers-Journalism 4thLd-Writethru a0678-a0692 03-30
0996</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pulitzers-Journalism, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0678-a0692,1014</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chicago Tribune, Philadelphia Inquirer Win Two Pulitzers Each</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES pvs urgent series; SUBS 8th graf pvs, `A team ...'
with three grafs to CORRECT year of plane crash to 1986 sted 1985 and add
detail on series; SUBS 12th graf, `The spot ...' with four grafs with comment
and background from winners.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Tribune and The Philadelphia
Inquirer each won two 1989 Pulitzer Prizes in journalism Thursday,
and the Anchorage Daily News won the public-service gold medal for
a series on alcoholism and suicide among native Alaskans.
   The Inquirer's Donald L. Bartlett and James B. Steele won for a
series on provisions in the 1986 Tax Reform Act that would have
given special tax breaks to politically well-connected individuals
and businesses. The two reporters also won a Pulitzer in 1975 for
national reporting on the Internal Revenue Service.
   The newspaper's David Zucchino won the Pulitzer in feature
writing for his series ``Being Black in South Africa.''
   Clarence Page of the Tribune won the Pulitzer in commentary for
columns on local and national affairs, and the newspaper's Lois
Wille won in editorial writing.
   The Pulitzer for general news reporting was won by the staff of
The Louisville Courier-Journal. The newspaper was cited for its
initial coverage of a bus crash that killed 27 students and for its
examination of the accident's causes and implications.
   Bill Dedman of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution won the
investigative reporting prize for a series on racial discrimination
practiced by the city's lending institutions.
   The series, which led to banking reforms, also won a 1988
Southern Journalism Award for investigative reporting.
   A team from The Dallas Morning News won the explanatory
journalism Pulitzer for their coverage of a 1986 airplane crash.
The journalists _ reporter David Hanners, photographer William
Snyder and artist Karen Blessen _ also were cited for their
coverage of the crash's investigation and its implications for air
safety.
   The 12-page special section ``Anatomy of An Air Crash: The Final
Flight of 50 Sierra Kilo'' examined from start to finish the
investigation by the NTSB of the crash of a jet carrying executives
of a New Jersey company. The plane went down in in bad weather near
Redwater, Texas, killing seven. The NTSB report, filed 22 months
later, cited controller error and malfunctioning radar equipment.
   ``Even though, our three names are on it, it was a team
effort,'' Hanners told colleagues in the newsroom. ``It was a
relatively simple story, eloquently told with words, pictures and
graphics.''
   The Pulitzer for specialized reporting went to Edward Humes of
The Orange County (Calif.) Register for reporting on the military
establishment in Southern California.
   The Pulitzer board awarded two prizes for international
reporting. One went to Glenn Frankel of The Washington Post for
reporting from the Middle East, and the other was won by Bill
Keller of The New York Times for coverage of the Soviet Union.
   The Pulitzer for criticism was won by Michael Skube, book editor
of The News and Observer of Raleigh, N.C. The editorial cartooning
prize went to Jack Higgins of the Chicago Sun-Times.
   Pat Dougherty, Anchorage Daily News city editor, said the
paper's public-service prize ``will give us a chance to reiterate
the point of the stories done in the first place: we've got a
serious problem up here.'' The paper won a public-service Pulitzer
in 1976 for a series on the Teamsters union in Alaska.
   The paper's 10-day, 44-story series found that alcoholism is
rampant in rural Alaska and the suicide rate for Eskimos and
Indians is four times the national rate. The series also detailed
high rates of domestic violence and child abuse among native
Alaskans. The series attributed these problems to a lack of job
opportunities and a clash of cultures between native Alaskans and
whites.
   The spot news photography prize was awarded to Ron Olshwanger, a
free-lance photographer, for a picture published in the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch of a fire fighter giving mouth-to-mouth resuscitation
to a child who had been pulled from a burning building. Manny
Crisotomo of the Detroit Free Press won in feature photography for
a series on student life at Southwestern High School.
   ``My hair's a mess, it's got champagne all over it. This is
wonderful,'' said Crisostomo.
   Each of the Pulitzers carries a $3,000 prize, except for public
service, which is recognized with a gold medal.
   Zucchino's winning entry for feature writing was originally
entered in the international reporting category and recommended as
one of several possible winners to the Pulitzer Board. The board
transferred the series to the feature-writing category and gave it
the prize for feature writing.
   The Courier-Journal's coverage of the bus crash was not one of
the finalists recommended by the Pulitzer jury to the Pulitzer
Board. Robert Christopher, board secretary, said the board asked
for the names of additional nominees and chose the Courier-Journal
story from that group.
   In awarding the general news reporting prize to the
Courier-Journal, the Pulitzer Board passed over three entries
nominated by the jury that read all the entries in the category.
The entries passed over were submitted by the Gwinnett Daily News
of Lawrenceville, Ga.; The Billings (Mont.) Gazette, and The Miami
Herald.
   Humes said of his prize for specialized reporting: ``It's great.
We're all standing here, there's little bits of paper all over the
place and I'm dripping wet. It's pretty unexpected. I had no idea.
Maybe someone here might have, but they didn't tell me.''
   Bill Drozdiak, foreign editor of The Washington Post, said of
the prize for Frankel's Middle East reporting: ``We're absolutely
delighted. We feel that it's a wonderful tribute to the fine work
that Glenn has done for us in his entire three-year assignment in
Israel, and even going back to his earlier assignment in South
Africa. He's one of our finest foreign correspondents and has done
superb work under very difficult circumstances.''
</TEXT>
