<FIRST>r w AM-Defense-Missiles     03-30 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense-Missiles,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armed Services Chairman Pushes for Missile Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House chairman said Thursday that reaching
concensus in Congress on modernizing the nation's land-based
missile force requires both building Midgetman missiles and basing
MXs aboard railroad cars.
   ``If we want to settle the ICBM issue once and for all, we need
a program that will take the 50 MX missiles out o silos and put
them on rails and that will build 300 to 500 Midgetman missiles,''
Armed Services Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., said in remarks in Los
Angeles.
   Lawmakers have wrangled for years over whether to choose the
smaller, single-warhead Midgetman missile supported by many
Democrats or instead back the mobile, 10-warhead MX missile that is
a favorite of Republicans.
   A newly unveiled Democratic compromise offer calls for
converting the 50 existing MX missiles from vulnerable silos to a
rail garrison basing mode _ placing them on railroad cars and
moving them around the country _ and building 300 to 500 Midgetman
missiles.
   Aspin said Democrats will not accept more than 50 MX missiles.
   ``For political consensus we are probably going to have to have
both rail MX and Midgetman,'' Aspin said. Copies of his speech were
released by his office in Washington.
   But Rep. Bill Dickinson, R-Ala., the top Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, on Wednesday called the plan a ``bad deal''
because it would place unacceptable limits on defense programs,
including capping MX production at the 50 already fielded.
   He also was criticial of the plan's envisioned development of
the Midgetman at a cost of $25 million to $35 million, negative
growth in defense spending and cuts in funding for Star Wars and
the B-2 stealth bomber.
   Dickinson urged his fellow GOP lawmakers to vote against the
Midgetman unless Democrats agree to President Bush's call for an
increase in defense spending after fiscal 1990.
   Bush has proposed zero growth in defense spending in fiscal
1990, 1 percent growth in fiscal 1991 and fiscal 1992 and 2 percent
growth in fiscal 1993.
   ``The small ICBM is a good system, and our national security
would benefit from having it,'' Dickinson said in a two-page
statement. ``But if the cost of the program is gutting SDI and
other programs while defense budgets continue to be reduced, then
we are better off with no deal.''
   In his speech, Aspin suggested sequential spending to finance
the plan with construction of the rail MX first and the Midgetman
second or vice versa. He also proposed ``flattening the SDI budget
... or slipping the B-2 or knocking out some operational weapons in
order to free up money for modernization.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney supported the MX while he served
in the House, but he has not indicated if he would back a plan
based on the MX, the Midgetman or a mix of the two. National
security adviser Brent Scowcroft is an opponent of the MX.
   Last week, Gen. Larry Welch, Air Force chief of staff, discussed
the plan with legislators but was publicly rebuked by Cheney for
``freelancing.'' Aspin called Cheney's criticism a ``bum rap.''
   ``Welch wasn't trying to put a deal together. He made plain he
wasn't speaking for the president. He was just exploring the
outlines of a possible compromise with Congress with no intention
of cutting the new secretary out of the deal,'' Aspin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
