<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Education     03-30 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Education,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Against Private School Tax Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House on Thursday corrected the
impression left by President Bush that he opposes giving tax breaks
to parents who send their children to private schools.
   Bush still supports the notion of tuition tax credits in
concept, but believes the government cannot afford them now in an
era of big budget deficits, said White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater.
   ``That's what he meant to say,'' Fitzwater said with a smile.
``That's what a careful reading will show.''
   Bush had said Wednesday that all taxpayers have an obligation to
support the public education system.
   ``And then, if on top of that, your parents think that they want
to shell out, in addition to the tax money, tuition money, that's
their right and that should be respected. But I don't think they
should get a break for that.''
   The issue arose when Bush fielded questions from a group of
young people.The president said he had been ``intrigued with the
concept of tuition tax credits. And some say, well should that
include parachoial schools. And I've said, yes.''
   However, Bush said, ``We can't afford to do that.''
   Backpedaling from Bush's comments, Fitzwater said, ``He hasn't
changed his position at all in terms of how he views the tuition
tax credit but he does not believe we can afford it at this time.
He still supports it in concept.''
   Bush will send a package of education proposals to Congress on
Wednesday but it will not contain tuition tax credits, Fitzwater
said.
   In a speech Thursday to the American Association of Community
and Junior Colleges, the president put in a plug for his
alternative teacher certification proposal.
   ``I believe secondary and elementary schools can learn a lot
from your success, starting with your policy of flexibility,'' he
said. ``By this, I mean the way in which you tap local talent and
draw on the knowledge of experts from the private sector.''
   ``When a Ph.D on sabbatical cannot volunteer as a teacher in
many school districts, something is very wrong,'' Bush said. He
said that's the reason he wants ``to open classrooms to every
qualified person with the talent, the knowledge and the desire to
teach.''
   Bush said ``we must all pitch in to restore our educational
system'' and to help America's workers compete with those in other
countries.
</TEXT>
