<FIRST>r a AM-ComingHome     03-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coming Home,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disgraced War Hero Ready to Come Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Army Col. David Hackworth, a hero whose
disenchantment with the Vietnam War led to a self-imposed exile,
wants to return to the United States, a magazine reported.
   Hackworth, who went to Australia after the war and made millions
in a restaurant business and a duck farm, hopes to move to Colorado
and become a military commentator, Parade says in its Sunday issue.
   The article was written by former Secretary of the Navy James
Webb, who praised Hackworth but also said he could learn much by
coming back to the United States and seeing ``how we have been
slowly and honestly coming to grips'' with the Vietnam War. Webb
was Navy secretary in the Reagan administration.
   ``My first love has always been the Army,'' Webb quoted
Hackworth, 58, as saying. ``I think I have some important insights
to offer, especially in the area of readiness and training.''
   Hackworth was awarded two Distinguished Service Crosses, nine
Silver Stars, four Legions of Merit and eight Bronze Stars and was
an almost certain candidate for general when his downfall began.
   During his four years in Vietnam, he became increasingly
frustrated by what he saw as the Army's lack of overall objectives
and its failure to adapt its tactics to the enemy.
   By 1971, Hackworth said, he was convinced the war was lost and
decided to ``hurt the Army as badly as she'd hurt me. I went out of
my way to break every regulation I could.''
   He castigated the Army's strategy and leadership on the
television program ``Issues and Answers,'' and predicted in a
Newsweek interview that the North Vietnamese flag would be flying
over Saigon in 1975. He was nearly court-martialed before he
retired from the military.
</TEXT>
