<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Botswana-Expulsion     03-30 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botswana-Expulsion,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine South Africans Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine South Africans were deported
Thursday after being arrested in a town where two alleged South
African commandos are serving prison terms, authorities said.
   Police and army officials said the nine claimed to be salesmen
marketing cleansers. One of the group had a rocket flare and
another had a pair of handcuffs, the officials said.
   A police official said on condition of anonymity that
authorities had insufficient evidence to file any charges.
   The official said the men, some of them white and some black,
had very little money with them and seemed to lack expertise about
their products.
   They were arrested Tuesday in Francistown, where South Africans
Theodore Hermansen and Johannes Basson began serving 10-year prison
terms last year after their capture during an aborted South African
cross-border raid.
   A South African army unit had been sent into Botswana on a
mission against the African National Congress guerrilla movement.
The soldiers encountered a Botswana police patrol and fled back
into South Africa after firing on the unarmed policemen, injuring
three of them.
   Hermansen and Basson, dressed in plainclothes, were arrested at
a roadblock near the scene of the shooting. In December, they were
convicted of assault.
   During their trial, their Botswanan defense laywer and a black
South African were arrested and charged with plotting to free the
two white commandos from prison. That case has not been completed.
</TEXT>
