<DOCNO> AP890330-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NationalGuard-Drugs     03-30 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National Guard-Drugs,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>12 States Will Expand Guard Role in Drug Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cheney Interview, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said Thursday he
had approved plans submitted by 12 states to step up the use of
their National Guard units in fighting drug trafficking.
   Cheney's approval means the 12 states will be eligible for extra
federal funds from a special congressional appropriation approved
last year to finance such National Guard operations.
   ``I signed off this morning on the packages for 12 states,
letters to the governors, announcing to them that their plans for
using some of that $40 million that Congress appropriated for the
Guard have been approved,'' Cheney said in interview.
   Late Thursday, the Pentagon released a list of the project
approvals, showing the 12 states would divide $11.8 million _ or
29.4 percent _ of the $40 million that Congress set aside.
   ``Based on recommendations from law enforcement agencies, plans
from 12 border states were accorded the highest priority ...,'' the
Pentagon said in a statement.
   ``Plans from the other states have been reviewed and approved by
the Defense Department and have been sent to the Department of
Justice for further review.''
   The 12 states whose plans were approved Thursday include
Alabama, Arizona, California, Florida, Georgia, Hawaii, Louisiana,
Mississippi, New Mexico, Oregon, Texas and Washington.
   The Pentagon said that, in general, the states are planning to
increase National Guard operations by emphasizing more ``aerial
photography and other imagery; radar surveillance; long-range
reconnaissance; assistance in searching containers, and the
transportation of law enforcement personnel, equipment and seized
substances.''
   In addition, the Pentagon said some of the state governments
planned to ``expand training of law enforcement personnel and
increase the loans of military equipment.''
   ``This expanded role does not include direct participation by
Guard personnel in police activities such as arrest and seizure,''
the Pentagon stressed.
   The goal is ``supporting civilian drug law enforcement agencies
in the nationwide crusade against drugs.''
   Earlier Thursday, Cheney made it clear he opposed the idea of
turning soldiers into policemen with the power to make arrests.
   ``I think it's important for everybody to remember that the
mission of the Defense Department is to defend the country,'' he
said. ``It's not a law enforcement function.''
   The Pentagon said the state of Florida was receiving the largest
grant of those announced Thursday at $3.4 million. The other states
and the amounts they will receive are:
</TEXT>
