<FIRST>u a BC-Pulitzers-Arts 2ndLd-Writethru a0689 03-30 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pulitzers-Arts, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0689,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wasserstein Captures Drama Pulitzer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Sheehan's account ...,' to show Sheehan nominated
in three categories; INSERTS 1 graf after 10th graf, `Tyler, 47 ...,' with
background on ``Breathing Lessons;'' SUBS 14th graf to show Wilbur former
poet laureate.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' Wendy Wasserstein's
play about one woman's voyage from the 1960s to the 1980s, won the
1989 Pulitzer Prize for drama on Thursday.
   The prize for fiction went to Anne Tyler's ``Breathing
Lessons.'' The award for general non-fiction went to ``A Bright
Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and America in Vietnam,'' by Neil
Sheehan.
   Two history prizes were awarded, to ``Parting the Waters:
America in the King Years, 1954-63,'' by Taylor Branch, and to
``Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil War Era,'' by James M. McPherson.
   The biography prize was won by the late Richard Ellmann for
``Oscar Wilde.'' Richard Wilbur's ``New and Collected Poems'' won
the poetry prize, while Roger Reynolds' ``Whispers Out of Time''
won for music.
   Each prize carries with it a $3,000 award.
   Wasserstein's play was an off-Broadway hit that made the move to
Broadway. It won the drama award over two other finalists, ``M.
Butterfly'' by David Henry Hwang and ``The Piano Lesson'' by August
Wilson.
   Sheehan's account of the life of a career officer in Southeast
Asia previously won the National Book Award. His book was nominated
in three categories; he won the Pulitzer for general non-fiction
and was nominated in the biography and history categories.
   Branch's book on the King years was a winner of the National
Book Critics Circle Award, as was Ellmann's biography of Wilde.
   Wasserstein previously had written numerous plays, including
``Uncommon Women and Others'' and ``Isn't It Romantic.''
   Tyler, 47, is the author of 11 novels, including ``The
Accidental Tourist,'' which was adapted to the screen in a popular
film starring William Hurt and Academy Award winner Geena Davis.
   ``Breathing Lessons'' is the story of a long-married couple and
their trip to Pennsylvania for the funeral of a friend.
   Sheehan, 52, a native of Holyoke, Mass., was the reporter for
The New York Times who wrote the Pentagon Papers stories about the
origins of the Vietnam War. A former war correspondent, he spent 16
years writing the award-winning story of John Paul Vann.
   McPherson, 52, is a professor of American history at Princeton
University who has published five books on the Civil War era.
   Ellmann had previously won the National Book Award in 1959 for a
biography of James Joyce. He died in 1987 of amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, also called Lou Gehrig's disease, before his Wilde
biography _ acclaimed as the definitive work on the British writer
_ was published.
   Wilbur, 68, was the poet laureate of the United States until he
retired last year. He also is a renowned translator.
   Music award winner Reynolds' ``Whispers Out of Time'' premiered
on Dec. 11, 1988, at Amherst College.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0150 </DOCNO>
