<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-FSX     03-30 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-FSX,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Urges U.S. To Resume FSX Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan urged Washington Thursday to resume talks to
ease U.S. worries over joint development of Japan's next fighter
jet and said the project was important to the security of both
nations.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi said no date had
been set for a new round of talks on the FSX fighter but that Japan
wanted more meetings ``as quickly as possible.''
   Japan took an initial step on its part of the project Thursday
when the government signed a contract with Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, Japan's main contractor for development of the jet, the
Defense Agency said.
   Japan had set aside more than $80 million for the project in its
fiscal 1988 budget, and the agency would have lost the money if it
had not acted before the fiscal year's end on Friday.
   Seiki Nishihiro, the agency's deputy director general, left
Washington Wednesday without reaching an accord on
``clarifications'' sought by the United States on an agreement for
joint development.
   U.S. officials said the talks were continuing at ``other
levels.''
   The countries agreed last November to jointly develop the FSX.
But the White House ordered a review after congressional critics
charged that the project was an $8 billion giveaway of U.S.
technology that Japan could use to compete in the civilian airplane
industry.
   ``We think that the effective and smooth implementation of the
U.S.-Japan Security Treaty is a cornerstone of security for Japan
and it's also very important for the United States as well,''
Haraguchi said before the Mitsubishi contract was signed. ``And we
think this joint development plan of FSX is an important
contribution for this arrangement.''
   Japan refused to buy U.S.-made F-16 jet fighters and initially
planned to develop its own jet to replace the F-1. But it agreed
under U.S. pressure to share the more than $6 billion project to
build 100 FSX jets.
   President Bush has said he backs the project, negotiated by the
Reagan administration, but wants safeguards for U.S. technology.
   The original agreement called for Mitsubishi and General
Dynamics to build the FSX using the F-16 as a model. Japan would
cover all the project's costs and retain control over the fighter's
design and any new technology to emerge.
   But U.S. negotiators reportedly want clarification of which side
would own the new technology and what portion of the fighters would
be constructed in the United States. They also want to know how the
sophisticated U.S. computer software used to fly the plane would be
protected.
   Criticism is mounting in Japan over Washington's handling of the
FSX issue.
   Naotoshi Sakanjo, a senior fellow at the Research Institute of
Peace and Security, called the U.S. approach unfair.
   ``They want to restrict advanced technology transfer to Japan
but, on the other hand, want any technology developed by Japan
without any conditions and want a greater share of jobs in
development and production,'' said Sakanjo, a retired vice admiral
of the Marine Self Defense Force.
   On Wednesday, 43 legislators from the governing Liberal
Democratic Party presented a petition urging the government to
proceed with development of the fighter with or without U.S. help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
