<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SchoolTechnology     03-30 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Technology,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criticize Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 773 largest school districts use
computers but have limited access to other technology and are not
planning adequately for the future, according to a survey released
Thursday.
   Nine of 10 districts reported having at least one VCR per
building and three-quarters said they could generate tests with
computers, according to the survey issued by the National School
Boards Association and Control Data Corp.
   More than 60 percent of the school districts said they were
capable of long-distance communication using computers, had a cable
TV channel for their own use and owned a videodisc player.
   The study compared school districts unfavorably to business in
that they do not seem to be anticipating technological development.
Some 90 percent of the superintendents surveyed said their
districts had a written technology plan but only 213 actually
submitted their plans, and most of those ``did not have a
comprehensive flavor,'' the report said.
   Among the technology plan shortcomings uncovered by the survey:
   _The most common focus was curriculum, but one-third of the
plans cited only computer literacy without mentioning math,
science, reading or language arts.
   _Most of the plans referred only to stand-alone computers; a
minority discussed computer networks. Only a handful of plans
addressed other technologies such as satellites, VCRs or cable TV.
   _More than half the plans were for instructional use of
computing only and a handful addressed administrative use only.
   _Many plans were drawn in 1986 or 1987 and had no evident
provisions for updating.
   The survey of 773 districts with 10,000 students or more was
conducted by the research firm of Andersen, Niebuhr and Associates
Inc. Questionnaires were returned by 5,150 superintendents, school
board presidents, technology specialists, elementary and secondary
curriculum specialists, third-party funding administrators and
administrators in charge of programs for disadvantaged children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
