<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-30 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Chief Defends Crackdown, Trials of Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief defended
recent trials of dissidents and declared Thursday that promoters of
Western-style political pluralism are trying to ``poison social
consciousness.''
   Milos Jakes also made clear the Soviet-led invasion of of August
1968 still is officially viewed as just and leaders of the liberal
``Prague spring'' that caused it will not be forgiven.
   Karoly Grosz, leader of the Hungarian party, hinted at a meeting
of his Central Committee on Wednesday that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev had disapproved the Soviet military interventions in
Hungary in 1956 and Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   Jakes used a speech to the Czechoslovak party Central Committee
to condemn ``attempts by opposition forces to influence public
opinion by casting doubt on the right of the state to intervene
against unlawful activities, disrupting public order and even
(attacking) the foundations of the social system.''
   He accused opposition groups of inciting civil disobedience and
putting ``ruthless psychological pressure'' on those who disagree
with them.
   People he described as enemies of communism at home and abroad
``strive to poison social consciousness through uncertainty, to
provoke ill-considered acts, to promote political pluralism in the
bourgeois (Western) sense,'' Jakes said.
   Members of the opposition demand independent courts, ``but if
they are justly punished, simultaneously they organize petitions
with which they want to intimidate the courts,'' he asserted.
``There is no way to give in to these pressures. Laws must be valid
for everyone.''
   The party rejects a petition signed by about 2,000 well-known
artists and scientists who criticized police violence against
dissidents and the subsequent trials, the party chief said in the
speech, reported by the official news agency CTK.
   He claimed ``foremost artists'' and most members of official
artists' unions did not take part.
   Prague police broke up peaceful demonstrations in January. In
February, the government jailed banned playwright Vaclav Havel and
other leading dissidents.
   Jakes also castigated ``church structures'' and church
dignitaries who were ``abusing the religious feelings of people ...
to open up another front of the struggle against socialism
(communism).''
   Of Aexander Dubcek, then party chief, and others who led the
Prague spring reforms, he said:
   ``Some former leading officials who had to leave the Communist
Party have become active. They are trying to present themselves as
pioneers of restructuring and from this they deduce the demand for
the rehabilitation of the policy of 1968, in particular of persons
who were active then, including their comeback into political
life.''
   Gorbachev calls his reform program perestroika, the Russian word
for restructuring.
   Referring to the peaceful demonstrations of January, Jakes
declared: ``Diaologue cannot be carried out in the streets, where
people are anonymous. It must be carried out in work places,
classrooms, in meetings of citizens ... where people know each
other.''
</TEXT>
