<FIRST>u a AM-Pulitzers-CategorySwitches     03-30 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pulitzers-Category Switches,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feature Winner Was Switched from International Category</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pulitzer Prize entry by David Zucchino of
The Philadelphia Inquirer, which won in the feature writing
category, was not a finalist in that category. But it was a
finalist in the category of international reporting.
   Zucchino's series on ``Being Black in South Africa'' was
relocated to feature writing _ where he captured the prize over
three other nominees, including an Inquirer co-worker.
   Those nominees were Tad Bartimus of The Associated Press, Bob
Ehlert of the Star Tribune, Minneapolis-St. Paul, and Loretta
Tofani of The Philadelphia Inquirer.
   Under Pulitzer rules, juries are supposed to recommend no more
than three items from their category to the Pulitzer Board. The
Board has the final determination of the winners and can move an
item from one category to another or select a winner not among the
finalists.
   In the general news reporting category, the board passed over
the three finalists: Nancy Badertscher of the Gwinnett Daily News,
Lawrenceville, Ga.; the staff of The Billings (Mont.) Gazette; and
Justin Gillis and Lisa Getter of The Miami Herald. Instead, the
board asked the jury chairman for additional entries, and then
selected The Louisville Courier-Journal staff for its coverage of a
bus crash which killed 27 people.
   There were also three winners nominated in multiple categories:
   _Donald L. Bartlett and James B. Steele of The Philadelphia
Inquirer, who won for national reporting, were also nominated in
public service for their 15-month investigation by of ``rifle
shot'' provisions in the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
   _Bill Dedman of The Atlanta Journal and Constitution, a winner
for investigative reporting, was also a nominee in the public
service category.
   _Neil Sheehan, author of ``A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann
and America in Vietnam,'' was nominated in three categories: he won
the Pulitzer for general non-fiction and was a finalist in the
history and biography categories.
</TEXT>
