<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0627 03-30 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Hit Fuel Depot, 50,000 Flee Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 10th, `His statement...' with Aoun quote
from interview. Pick up 11th pvs, `Jumblatt's militia...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockets fired by Syrian troops in their
battle with Christian army units hit the city's main fuel depot
Thursday, causing fires and explosions that forced 50,000 residents
to flee.
   A witness reached by telephone said: ``Butane is leaking from
nearby tanks and exploding in balls of fire over Dora,'' where the
depot is located in Christian east Beirut.
   Police said Syrian gunners fired at least six Katyusha rockets
into east Beirut, killing two people and wounding three. He said
shrapnel and glass shards from the gas explosions wounded 14 people.
   Thursday's casualties brought the toll to 125 killed and 405
wounded in the artillery duel that began March 8 between the 20,000
Christian troopers commanded by Gen. Michel Aoun and an alliance of
Syrian forces and Walid Jumblatt's Druse militia. Most of the
casualties are civilians.
   Explosions at the fuel depot could be heard all over the
capital. Police said the blasts shattered glass within a three-mile
radius and about 50,000 people had been evacuated from the densely
populated residential districts around Dora.
   ``More tanks are full of butane and other types of gas,'' a
police spokesman said. ``If the fire reaches them we will face a
catastrophe.''
   Butane in small tanks or bottles is used for cooking stoves and
many heaters. Power plants have been heavily damaged and nearly all
facilities from hospital operating rooms to bakeries use generators
fueled by diesel or gasoline, also stored at Dora.
   A relay station at Jamhour, in Christian territory east of
Beirut, was hit by Syrian shellfire Tuesday, and Beirut now gets
electricity less than four hours a day.
   Aoun, who also leads an interim Christian government that
competes with a Moslem cabinet, urged ``humanitarian organizations
to shoulder their responsibilities and prevent the spread of this
barbaric Syrian crime.''
   His statement said the Arab League should send its six-member
mediation committee on Lebanon to see first-hand ``the war of
annihilation carried out by the Syrian occupation forces against
the Lebanese people.''
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press later, he
said the Syrians were committing ``a criminal act against the
population. They bomb the gas stations, fuel depots of the city and
the center of electricity production.''
   Jumblatt's militia began shooting two days after Aoun's forces
blockaded illegal ports run by Moslem militias, which cost the
government's five legal ports an estimated $100 million a year in
revenue.
   The conflict stems from a political crisis that began in
September, gave birth to the competing governments and split the
military on sectarian lines. Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib commands the
22,000 Moslem soldiers, who are poorly equipped and have stayed out
of the fighting.
   Nasrallah Sfeir, the Maronite Catholic patriarch, issued a
statement Thursday pleading for a ``consolidated cease-fire,
guaranteed by observers ... to save man in Lebanon.''
   Voice of Lebanon, a Christian radio station, said: ``Damascus,
like any invader, wants to reduce Lebanon into mere fire and
ashes,'' and urged the ``free world not to remain silent regarding
Syria's acts of terrorism.''
   Neighboring Syria has about 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a
under a peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League issued in 1976, a
year after the civil war began, and has become the country's main
power broker.
   Aoun has blames the Syrians for the current violence, the worst
in four years, and has vowed to drive them out.
   More than 250,000 of Beirut's 1.2 million people have deserted
the city for south Lebanon or other safer areas since the rain of
shells and rockets began more than three weeks ago.
   Christians leave their besieged 310-square-mile enclave by ship
for the ``security zone'' Israel maintains, with the aid of a
predominantly Christian militia, just inside south Lebanon. Moslems
drive south in long convoys.
   President Amin Gemayel chose Aoun, a fellow Maronite, to lead an
interim government in September when his six-year term ended and
Parliament could not agree on a successor. Moslems rejected the
choice and supported Salim Hoss, the Sunni Moslem who was premier
under Gemayel.
   By unwritten agreement dating to independence from France in
1943, the president is Christian, the premier Sunni and the
parliament speaker Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
