<FIRST>r i AM-Gander-Crash     03-30 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gander-Crash,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge to Review Investigation of 1985 Air Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disputed investigation into Canada's worst
aviation disaster _ the 1985 Gander crash that killed 256 Americans
_ will be reviewed by a retired Supreme Court judge who could
recommend a new inquiry.
   Retired Judge Willard Estey, named Wednesday to review the
Aviation Safety Board's three-year investigation, will have 90 days
to deliver his report.
   Transport Minister Benoit Bouchard made clear the review will
stop short of the full judicial inquiry demanded by the
investigation's critics. But he told a news conference in Ottawa
that Estey could approve the board's report or decide further
investigation or even a full inquiry is merited.
   ``Justice Estey can recommend whatever he wants,'' Transport
Ministry spokesman Rene Mercier said in a phone interview Thursday.
``So it's from A to Z in terms of possibilities.''
   The Arrow Air charter DC-8 crashed shortly after takeoff from
Gander, Newfoundland, on a refueling stop Dec. 12, 1985, carrying
248 U.S. troops home to Fort Campbell, Ky., from Middle East
peacekeeping duties. The eight American crew also died.
   Bouchard asked Estey in a letter ``to review the entire record
of the investigation ... (and) consider whether any other
explanation as to the causes and contributing factors of the
accident is consistent with the evidence gathered by the board.''
   The minister said public confidence in the nine-member board
``has been jeopardized'' by internal division during the
investigation, which found in December that ice on the wings
probably caused the crash.
   Five members approved the final report. Four said in a minority
report that an in-flight fire or explosion was the most likely
cause.
   Demands to reopen the investigation have been heard ever since.
   The Toronto Star said in an editorial this month: ``A total of
256 people died in the Gander crash. Their families and friends,
not to mention Canadians who rely on Ottawa for air safety, now
deserve a public inquiry.''
   Bouchard had expressed his confidence in the board's
investigation and accepted the icing theory. The Ottawa Citizen,
however, obtained an internal Transportation Ministry report that
said board investigators mismanaged the probe and focused on a
``preconceived'' icing theory at the expense of other possible
causes.
   Bouchard also named a judge to handle an investigation of the
March 10 crash of an Air Ontario Fokker F-28 jet that killed 24
people at Dryden, Ontario, although the safety board already sent
its own investigators to the scene.
   ``The actions I have taken will assist in restoring the
credibility'' of accident investigations, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
