<FIRST>r i AM-Prison-Scene     03-30 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison-Scene,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoners' Relatives Describe Hardships</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Prison Revolt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CATARINA, Guatemala (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marta Abal Reyes went 30 hours
without a sip of water and for two days ate only pumpkin leaves.
But she said Thursday that was not the worst of her ordeal inside
Pavon prison.
   ``My nerves are killing me,'' she said, tears in her eyes, as
she sat in the back of a Red Cross ambulance that carried her and
seven other women and children to the organization's Guatemala City
headquarters for medical checkups.
   They were among 575 people _ mostly women and children _
evacuated from Pavon penitentiary Thursday after the end of a
four-day revolt by inmates.
   Many children showed signs of dehydration, said Dr. Gabriel
Salazar of the Red Cross.
   Authorities cut off food and water to the prison on Wednesday in
an effort to pressure the rebellious inmates to surrender.
   ``I was afraid,'' said Mrs. Reyes, who was trapped inside Sunday
while paying an Easter visit to her husband, Feliciano, a prisoner.
``I would get desperate, then recover my spirits, but you never
knew what was going to happen.''
   Georgina Lopez, escorted out of the prison with her two young
children, said: ``We were locked up by the mutineers. That was
hard.''
   Some officials suggest earlier in the week that family members
might have chosen to remain in the prison to support the rebel
inmates' demands.
   ``That's a lie. Why on earth would we want to stay in there
under those conditions?'' Ms. Lopez asked.
   ``The bullets made us scared,'' Eva Estrada said of the sporadic
gunfire heard in the prison throughout the week.
   Mrs. Estrada and several other women interviewed were concerned
about the fate of prisoners who did not take part in the uprising.
   She said no more than 50 of the prison's 1,350 inmates
participated. Authorities had estimated the number of rebel
prisoners at 100.
   ``Now we're afraid the army or the prison guards could take
reprisals against innocent people,'' Mrs. Reyes said.
   The government promised ``to guarantee absolute respect for the
physical integrity'' of the inmates.
</TEXT>
