<FIRST>r a AM-Atlanta-Pulitzer 1stLd-Writethru a0799 03-30 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta-Pulitzer, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0799,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Reporter Returns to Atlanta for Pulitzer Celebration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Dedman then...,' to fix typo in `McCutchen.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter who is no longer at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution won a Pulitzer Prize for his work there, and
quickly gave thanks to an editor who is no longer there either.
   Reporter Bill Dedman, who quit his job in February to join The
Washington Post, hopped a plane to Atlanta to join in the
celebration as soon as he heard the award announced on Thursday.
   Once back in the Journal-Constitution newsroom, Dedman thanked a
long list of editors and assistants. He reserved top credit for
former editor Bill Kovach, who resigned last November in a bitter
and highly publicized management dispute, and to Sonny Rawls, a
Kovach lieutenant who remains at the paper as assistant managing
editor for news.
   Dedman then accepted a plastic cup of champagne from Managing
Editor Glenn McCutchen and, referring to staff turmoil and turnover
prompted by Kovach's departure, said, ``I think we all had a rough
year, but I think this will probably taste real good.''
   Dedman's stories exposing unequal patterns of home loans to
blacks and whites in Atlanta won the Pulitzer Prize for
investigative reporting for the Journal-Constitution.
   ``We documented a social ill,'' Dedman said. ``I'm excited that
the Pulitzer Board would honor stories that tell the white
community things the black community already knew and things that
take the editor's guts to put in the newspaper.''
   Dedman and a special projects team developed the series of
stories by analyzing reams of computer printouts, obtained under
the federal Home Mortgage Disclosure Act of 1977, of home loans
made by census tracts.
   Dedman, a 28-year-old college dropout who joined the Atlanta
newspapers in April 1987, spent five months developing the story on
so-called ``redlining'' of mortgage loans to blacks, who make up
two-thirds of Atlanta's population.
   The newspaper's analysis of loans made by every bank, savings
and loan association and large credit union in Atlanta from 1981 to
1986 showed that white neighborhoods received five times as many
home loans as black neighborhoods with the same income level.
   ``While our newspaper, and particularly Bill Dedman, were
honored today, Atlanta also ought to feel very good because of the
way it behaved,'' Publisher Jay Smith said. ``A lot of communities
would have gotten their backs up. ... The political leadership
said, `We've got to fix this thing and we've got to fix it in a
matter of days or weeks, not months.'''
   Journal-Constitution Editor Arnold Rosenfeld credited his
predecessor, Kovach, who is now studying as a Nieman Fellow at
Harvard.
   Kovach, reached by telephone, said, ``It's a proud day when
journalism recognizes work of this quality. I hope it stands as a
goal for which the reporters and editors there will continue to
strive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
