<DOCNO> AP890330-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Korea     03-30 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Korea,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Premier Expresses Remorse To Korea Over Past Militarism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita expressed ``deep
remorse'' to all Koreans on Thursday over Japan's militaristic past
and said his nation sought to improve relations with communist
North Korea.
   Japan ruled Korea as a colony for 35 years, until Japan's World
War II surrender in 1945.
   Takeshita spoke before a parliamentary committee as a goodwill
mission from the Japan Socialist Party, the largest opposition
party, left for Beijing on its way to Pyongyang for talks with
North Korean leaders.
   The Socialists said their mission, led by former party
Secretary-General Makoto Tanabe, had the government's backing in
efforts to find a breakthrough in relations with North Korea. Japan
and North Korea have no formal ties.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi said that following
Takeshita's statement, ``we hope for some response (from the North)
but have no expectations.''
   Asked if the statement was a prelude to full diplomatic
relations with the North, he replied: ``Many steps remain before we
go into that stage. ... We are sending a signal that we'd like to
have meaningful dialogue with North Korea.''
   Haraguchi said Japan made its position clear to North Korea on
several occasions in messages conveyed through third countries. He
would not elaborate.
   Takeshita said, ``On this occasion when the situation
surrounding the Korean peninsula is entering upon a new era, I
would like to express, toward all the people of the peninsula, our
deep remorse and regret for the unfortunate past.''
   ``The government and people of Japan are profoundly aware that
past actions by Japan have inflicted great suffering on the peoples
of nearby lands,'' he said, adding that Japan was determined ``that
it shall never happen again.''
   He said Japan ``hopes to improve relations with the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea on the basis of the above-mentioned
reflection, giving due consideration to the new situation on the
peninsula.''
   Kyodo News Service said it was the first time a Japanese prime
minister had used North Korea's official name.
   ``The government has made public since last year its hope to
enter into discussions, without any preconditions, with the ...
(North) on any aspect of pending issues,'' Takeshita said.
   Japan offered a similar apology when it normalized relations
with South Korea in 1965. After Japan's defeat, Korea was split
into capitalist, pro-Western South and Communist North.
   The 1950-53 Korean War deepened enmity between the two Koreas,
but in recent months they have held contacts aimed at easing
tensions.
   Japan's efforts to improve relations with North Korea coincided
with South Korea's call for its allies and non-communist friends to
help create a climate favorable for efforts toward Korean
reunification.
   Seoul has adopted a new ``northern policy,'' seeking trade and
diplomatic ties with Communist countries.
   So far, the Japan-North Korea Parliamentarians Friendship League
and the Socialist Party have been Japan's main bridges to North
Korea.
   North Korea's Foreign Ministry issued a statement on Jan. 20
accusing Japan of a hostile attitude toward Pyongyang and demanding
an apology for ``past crimes.'' It said Japan supported
perpetuation of Korea's division in a ``two-Korea policy.''
   Japan's Foreign Ministry said in a policy statement: ``Japan has
no intention of supporting the perpetuation of division desired by
neither North nor South.''
   Ministry officials have said that in moving toward improved
ties, the government also hoped for the speedy release of two
Japanese seamen sentenced in December 1987 to 15 years in prison
for alleged spying against North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
