<FIRST>a i AM-ChinaDaily Adv06   03-30 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China Daily, Adv 06,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, April 6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>China's Only English-Language Daily Toes the Semi-Open Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's crime in the streets, rivers are polluted
and children are dropping out of school, the China Daily informs
its readers.
   ``Scholars foresee a national crisis,'' it headlines. ``Price
rises start panic buying,'' it warns. ``Officials' power abuse is
major concern,'' it says.
   For the foreign visitor expecting a tightly controlled good-news
press, China's only English-language daily is full of the
unexpected.
   But a crusading Communist daily? Hardly.
   Like the increasingly lively Chinese vernacular press from which
it takes most of its more eye-opening material, the China Daily
sticks to those social ills the government wants exposed.
   Criticism of senior leaders, questioning one-party rule or
delving into sensitive subjects such as unrest in Tibet are
strictly off limits.
   What the eight-page paper does offer, particularly for a
foreigner far from home, is up-to-date figures from world stock
markets, international news from the Western news agencies and a
wide-ranging sports page carrying the latest in American
basketball, European soccer or Asian table tennis.
   ``Our philosophy is to provide our readers with what is
happening in China and what is happening in the world,'' said
Deputy Chief Editor Chen Hui.
   Chinese press authorities began mulling the idea of an
English-language daily in 1979, the year China embarked on its
economic reforms and open-door policy. Before that, non-Chinese
speakers or readers lived in a news vacuum except for several dull,
propaganda-filled English-language periodicals.
   The China Daily, with technical assistance from the Australian
Thomson Foundation and the Melbourne Age, began publishing June 1,
1981, with a first edition of 10,000 copies.
   Within two years it had an air-mailed North American edition and
in 1987 began satellite transmissions to London for distribution in
Western Europe. Besides London, it now publishes in New York, San
Francisco, Hong Kong, Canton and Shanghai.
   Originally printed five days a week, the paper now comes out six
days and has a four-page business paper on Sunday. Chen said
domestic circulation has risen to about 130,000, with two-thirds of
the readership being Chinese.
   Chen said the daily, which delivers to major hotels for
foreigners, is China's first not to depend entirely on the plodding
post office for distribution. It is also the first, with about 25
percent of space devoted to ads, to obtain a large percent of its
revenues from advertisements.
   The paper also is financed by sales _ it costs only 30 fen (8
cents) a copy _ and, like all Chinese papers, government subsidies.
   Chen insists, though, that government backing does not make the
China Daily ``official.'' Papers like the Communist Party's
People's Daily (Renmin Ribao) ``have the role of explaining
government and party policies to the people. That's not our
purpose. We can't get the foreigner to do anything.''
   The editorial board, which puts together a weekly commentary and
oversees daily articles, is not subject to outside influence, Chen
said.
   But like all Chinese media, the China Daily exercises
self-censorship and doesn't ``report for the sensationalism
involved to widen readership,'' Chen said.
   Asked why the paper carries reports of strikes in Poland but
little about strikes in China, he said, ``We must exercise a little
more care in considering the social consequences'' of events closer
to home.
   Charles Frankel, one of about 10 foreigners on one-year
contracts at the paper, said that on sensitive issues such as
anti-Chinese riots in Tibet or recent confrontations between
Chinese and African students who say they are victims of racial
prejudice, the paper's reporters make no effort to get the
``other'' side of the story.
   ``If they did, they didn't report it,'' said Frankel, who worked
28 years for The Honolulu Star-Bulletin and taught journalism at
Hawaii University before coming to China.
   Frankel noted that although China was one of the biggest victims
of Japanese aggression in World War II, the China Daily, again
following the government lead, has made no appraisals of the role
of the late Emperor Hirohito of Japan in the war.
   Chen acknowledged that statements by the Dalai Lama, the exiled
Tibetan religious leader, appear only as background in articles
where the Chinese side condemns his calls for Tibetan autonomy.
   ``It would be better to report the straight news first,'' he
said.
   Frankel's wife, Helga, who also works at the paper, said
reporters are shocked at the way Westerners find fault with their
governments.
   ``There's no bridging the gap that you (reporters) criticize
your leaders.''
   But Charles Frankel said the paper shouldn't merely be judged by
American standards.
   ``It serves its purpose. I'm glad this paper exists because it
does present a window on the world.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, April 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
