<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-SavannahRiver-Westinghouse Adv03   03-30 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah River-Westinghouse, Adv 03,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, April 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Savannah River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Sees Defense Plant Role as Long-term Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. says that when it
bid last year to take over operation of the Savannah River Plant it
was not aware that the nuclear reactors would have to be shut down
because of safety and structural problems.
   But the company insists its decision to take the job will prove
to have been sound.
   James Moore, president of a Westinghouse unit that will run the
federal weapons plant, said money was not a motivation for seeking
the assignment, which will pay a maximum of $7.5 million over the
first six months _ or zero, if the Energy Department determines
that plant performance is too far below minimum standards.
   Moore, in an interview, cited three key reasons for assuming
responsibility at one of 16 major nuclear weapons plants, a complex
that a government auditing agency called ``one of the more
potentially dangerous industrial operations in the world.''
   _It offers the possibility of blunting the spread of bad
publicity about nuclear power to the commercial nuclear field,
which is Westinghouse's main business.
   ``There was an element of defensiveness, I guess, to try to get
involved to see if we could bring our capabilities and experience
to move forward here and get more positive publicity,'' Moore said.
   _The company's nuclear specialists can remain ``involved and
motivated'' in their field at a time when new activity in the
commercial nuclear sector is at a standstill.
   _Savannah River's other facilities, including its research
laboratory and new plant for processing high-level radioactive
waste, can put Westinghouse at the cutting edge of nuclear
technology.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
