<DOCNO> AP890330-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-Every18Hours Adv02   03-30 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Every 18 Hours, Adv 02,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Murder Every 17 Hours</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Drugs and Daffodils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So far this year, four people have been killed
in the streets of Washington every three days. That's the rate of
one every 18 hours.
   The city has been dubbed the murder capital, surpassing
Detroit's per-capita murder rate.
   As of midday Wednesday, the police say 123 murders have
occurred, compared to 78 at this time last year, 372 for all of
last year. The previous record for Washington was 287, set in 1969.
   In almost every case, the victim is a black male, and he meets
his demise in one of the city's poorest neighborhoods, according to
a report by Washington's Office of Criminal Justice Plans and
Analysis.
   Four out of five times, the report says, the slaying is
drug-related _ a prospective drug seller trying to encroach onto
another dealer's turf, a drug courier trying to keep more than his
share of the profits, or a user who didn't come up with the $10 or
$20 he owed his dealer.
   The murders start to look alike _ a black man between the ages
of 18 and 32 ends up lying in the street, shot in the head or
peppered with gunshot wounds from an automatic or semi-automatic
weapon.
   The slums have become a battleground for rival crack dealers
trying to gain a foothold on the market, the police say. Crack, a
cocaine derivative, which arrived in the city two or three years
ago, gives an intense high for a very short time. The cravings that
follow drive people to violence more than most other drugs, they
say.
   Murder has become a way for dealers to settle disagreements and
keep others in line, the police add.
   ``Homicide is highest in communities that have the greatest
inequalities, extreme differences in income and wealth,'' said
criminologist Lawrence Sherman, president of the Crime Control
Institute. ``And that is certainly the case in Washington compared
to other cities.''
   The district is 67 percent black, 28 percent white and 5 percent
other races. The black migration intensified after 1950, when job
opportunities lured blacks from the South, according to Gan Ahuja,
a demographer with the city's Office of Policy.
   A high birth rate among black women, coupled with the declining
number of births to white women, produced more black offspring,
Ahuja said, and many whites moved to the suburbs to take advantage
of better housing and schools.
   The district has the second highest per capita income in the
nation, according to the 1980 census _ yet 14 percent of its
residents live in poverty. The youth unemployment rate was 30
percent higher than the national average. More than 28 percent of
adults over age 25 have a college education, but 16 percent never
finished elementary school, according to the census.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
