<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Elections at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Continent in Crisis-The Test, b0790-b0791</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on the
South American countries holding presidential elections this year,
with dates in parentheses. (Source for statistics is United Nations
Economic Commission on Latin America and the Caribbean.)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARAGUAY (May 1) _ Principal candidates: Gen. Andres Rodriguez,
who ousted long-reigning military ruler Alfredo Stroessner in a
coup Feb. 3, is the candidate of the very dominant Colorado Party
and considered extremely likely to win. None for a fractured
opposition, which has complained the election was called too
quickly. Major issue: corruption. Foreign debt, $2.2 billion.
Population, 4 million. Annual inflation, 16.8 percent.
Unemployment, 9.2 percent. Per capita GNP growth 1981-1988, minus
3.0 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BOLIVIA (May 7) _ Principal candidates: former military dictator
Hugo Banzer of the rightist Nationalist Advance, Gonzalo Sanchez de
Losada of governing conservative Revolutionary Nationalist
Movement, and Jaime Paz Zamora of the Revolutionary Leftist
Movement. If no candidate gains an absolute majority, winner is
picked by Congress. Major issues: unemployment, social services,
controlling cocaine trafficking. Foreign debt, $3.9 billion.
Population, 6.9 million. Annual inflation, 21.5 percent.
Unemployment, 11.7 percent. Per capita GNP growth 1981-1988, minus
25.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ARGENTINA (May 14) _ Principal candidates: Eduardo Angeloz of
the governing Radical Party and Carlos Menem of the populist
Peronist Party. Major issues: economic stagnation and soaring
inflation, foreign debt obligations. Foreign debt, $56.8 billion.
Population, 31.5 million. Annual inflation, 388 percent.
Unemployment, 6.5 percent. Gross national product (GNP) growth per
capita 1981-1988, minus 15.2 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BRAZIL (Nov. 15) _ Principal candidates: parties have yet to
decide, but among the strongest prospects are Gov. Leonel Brizola
of Rio de Janeiro, the Democratic Labor Party, and Luis Inacio Lula
da Silva, leftist Workers Party. Possible candidates on the right
include former President Janio Quadros; Gen. Leonidas Pires
Goncalves, the army minister; House Speaker Rep. Ulysses Guimaraes,
and a television network owner, Silvio Santos. Major issues:
economic disorder, debt servicing, public corruption. Foreign debt,
$114.6 billion. Population, 144.4 million. Annual inflation, 934
percent. Unemployment, 4 percent. Per capita GNP growth 1981-1988,
1.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   URUGUAY (Nov. 26) _ Principal candidates: Most parties have yet
to decide, but contenders include Jorge Batle or Enrique Tarigo of
the governing Colorado Party's majority faction and Jorge Pacheco
Areco of the minority Colorado faction; Alberto Zumaran, Carlos
Julio Perreira or Luis Alberto Lacalle of the center-left National
Party and Liber Seregni of the leftist Broad Front. Major issues:
stagnant economy, public education and human rights violations by
the former military rulers. Foreign debt, $6.05 billion.
Population, 3.1 million. Annual inflation, 69 percent.
Unemployment, 9.2 percent. Per capita GNP growth 1981-1988, minus
9.8 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CHILE (Dec. 14) _ Principal candidates: to be chosen, but a
strong contender is centrist Christian Democrat candidate Patricio
Aylwin, who seeks the backing of a 17-party opposition coalition.
President Augusto Pinochet, the army general who lost a referendum
in November to extend his rule until 1997, is legally barred from
running unless the constitution is amended. Possible rightist
candidates include Finance Minister Hernan Buchi and Sergio Jarpa
of the National Renovation. Major issues: democratic constitutional
reforms, raising wages, social services, and human rights
violations by the military. Foreign debt, $19.1 billion.
Population, 12.7 million. Annual inflation, 12.7 percent.
Unemployment, 11.2 percent. Per capita GNP growth 1981-1988, 2.4
percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
