<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-TakeoverTrauma Adv09-2Takes   03-30 1067</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Takeover Trauma, Adv 09 - 2 Takes,1095</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Front Lines of the Takeover Wars _ Lots of Losers, Any Winners?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Juli is cq in 28th graf, bgn, `This is a ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Since a pair of young East Coast investors
launched a takeover bid for the holding company Interco, things
have changed in Hermann, Mo. The shoe plant, the biggest employer
in town and an Interco division, closed to make up some of the
millions spent fending off the financiers. Longtime plant workers
have gotten severance checks: $30 for each year worked. What they
haven't gotten is a satisfactory explanation of why an inconclusive
skirmish in the corporate takeover wars left so many casualties in
a little hardworking town.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SHARON COHEN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HERMANN, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In her $5-an-hour workaday world, Linda
Eikel never cared much about Wall Street wheeler-dealers or
billion-dollar buyouts. Not until it hit home and tore apart her
life.
   Millions were spent on a bid to buy her company, millions to
successfully block it, and now that it's over, the shoe factory
worker has no job, no insurance and no security.
   ``I'm kind of bitter,'' she says. ``I think the big shots, the
ones real high up, do not realize we have to struggle to make a
living.''
   Eikel worked at the Florsheim shoe plant, the biggest employer
in this small town until it closed in February as part of a giant,
complicated plan that allowed the parent company, Interco Inc., to
fend off a $2.7 billion hostile takeover.
   The four-month fight by Interco is the kind of saga that's
become more common in the merger-mania '80s: a Fortune 500 company
facing two thirtysomething corporate raiders and duking it out in a
fight that leaves many outside the ring bloodied and dazed.
   It's also a story of how a hostile takeover bid can be a
moneymaker for those with the least stake in the company _
financiers and lawyers _ and a heartbreaker for those with the most
basic vested interest _ the loyal employees.
   Elwood `Woody' Wesselschmidt made shoes for nearly 30 years and
was manager of the 275-worker Florsheim plant in Hermann. ``The big
people _ all they decide is what they want to buy and sell,'' he
said. ``The little guys are the ones who lose their jobs.''
   The losers may be obvious, but the winners of this skirmish in
the takeover wars aren't that clear. Take Interco, for exmple.
   To reorganize and avoid a takeover by Cardinal Acquisition
Corp., controlled by Steven and Mitchell Rales, Interco estimates
it'll pay more than $65 million to banks, lawyers, advisers and
others.
   It also borrowed $1.9 billion and developed a restructuring plan
that involves cutting $75 million over the next year and selling
off all but four or five of about 20 major companies.
   One cost-cutting measure, estimated to save $2 million annually,
was closing the Hermann plant and a second Florsheim factory in
Paducah, Ky., which together employed 650 people. Their work will
be consolidated elsewhere.
   For those keeping score, it might seem as if it's Interco 1,
Raiders 0. Not so. The raiders appear to have made millions, and
while Interco executives kept their jobs, they will be running a
shrunken, debt-burdened company.
   ``They end up selling their crown jewels to cover their
expenses,'' said said Kathryn Rudie Harrigan, strategic management
professor at Columbia University's Graduate School of Business.
``They're not in better shape now.''
   Interco recently sold Londontown Corp., maker of London Fog
outerwear, as part of a plan to sell all its apparel and most of
its retail groups. The $3.34 billion corporation will keep its
footwear and most of its furniture divisions, although one of its
most prestigious names, furniture maker Ethan Allen, is for sale.
   The corporation's managers will have to make the remaining
companies ``sell better,'' said Budd Bugatch, research director at
the investment banking firm Ferris, Baker Watts, Inc. ``They have a
real monkey on their back.''
   For Interco, with $1.15 billion in loans to pay back by May
1990, much remains uncertain. But one thing about its
``restructuring'' is for sure.
   The plant closing has hurt Hermann, a proud German town in
wine-making country where shoes have been made since the beginning
of the century.
   ``There's a lot of the German work ethic here,'' said Perry
Lovett, city administrator in this eastern Missouri town of 2,700.
``There are a lot of people who've never been out of work.''
   ``I haven't looked for a job in almost 30 years,'' Wesselschmidt
said. ``I've never written a resume in my life. Yes, it's scary.''
   Still, he's more disappointed than angry.
   ``You bust your buns to make (the shoes) look good,'' he said.
``Then something like this happens and you feel betrayed. ... We
did our best. Now our best isn't doing us any good.''
   Pam Terrill, the union president, is angry.
   ``They said quality was No. 1. The people took it seriously. And
they closed the plant anyhow,'' she said. ``I wish they'd go under,
personally. I've heard that from quite a few other people.''
   The Florsheim workers can't realistically expect to find new
jobs in their industry. In just the last decade, 317 U.S. shoe
plants have closed, according to Footwear Industries of America.
Imported shoes make up 81.6 percent of the market.
   Many now rely on unemployment compensation. Severance pay came
to $30 for each year on the job, with a 15-year minimum and 30-year
maximum.
   ``They've caused our life to be in a heck of a turmoil,'' said
Eikel. ``I think people are bitter toward Interco, not Florsheim. I
don't think the big guys from Interco are hurting. ... They got
themselves into this takeover.''
   Interco, through its public-relations firm, Fleishman-Hillard,
refused to discuss the attempted takeover or any plans, but some
analysts say Eikel's assessment isn't far off.
   ``This is a management that acquired some wonderful brand names
... and did nothing with them,'' said Juli Niemann, analyst with
Stifel Nicolaus Inc., an investment banking firm. ``The stock
languished for years. Call it lack of stellar management.''
   Bugatch concurred: ``They did not operate the business in a way
that maximized shareholder value.''
   The result: Interco was ripe for raiders to come in, carve up
the company and sell it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-TakeoverTrauma Adv09-1stAdd   03-30 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Takeover Trauma, Adv 09 - 1st Add,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>HERMANN, Mo.: sell it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Enter the Rales brothers, two aggressive, savvy, Washington,
D.C., businessmen with interests in tools, consumer plastics and
tire-changing equipment who reportedly were attracted to the
furniture business.
   They made four bids, starting with $64 a share, ending with $74
a share.
   Interco, which rebuffed the bids as inadequate, countered with
its own restructuring and recapitalization plan it said was valued
at $76 a share _ counting cash and securities to be offered to
shareholders, plus the stock's residual value.
   The company also adopted a ``poison pill'' defense, designed to
make an unwelcome takeover prohibitively expensive. According to
government documents the Rales brothers filed, 23 Interco
executives were to receive golden parachutes totaling more than $16
million if control of the company changed.
   By November, the Rales brothers nonetheless controlled nearly 93
percent of the stock _ their original stake of 8.7 percent plus 84
percent tendered by shareholders.
   But they let their final offer lapse, believing the fight had
dragged on too long and that Interco's value was deteriorating,
said Neil Call, their spokesman. The brothers declined to be
interviewed.
   They didn't acquire Interco, but they didn't lose either.
   The St. Louis Post-Dispatch said the Rales brothers sold their
stock for a gross profit of $59.7 million, and analysts estimate
the takeover bid cost about $10 million, figures Call doesn't
dispute.
   Among Interco's costs are $40.5 million in fees to four banks
that arranged the $1.9 billion in loans, up to $9 million to a
financial adviser and $15.5 million to lawyers, accountants,
printers and others.
   There are better uses for the money, Niemann said. ``I'd like to
see $65 million in capital spending. Instead it's for lawyers and
investment bankers to send their kids to college.''
   ``The middlemen always win,'' Professor Harrigan said.
``Regardless of whether they catch their prey or not, they get
paid.''
   Other winners include shareholders who bought and sold stock as
it rose from $42 a share in March to $68.50 in July.
   As for the shoe plant workers, ``They're going to grab their
boots and pull them up a little higher and grab their belts and
make them a little tighter and see that it works out,'' said Tom
Cabot, president of the Hermann Area Chamber of Commerce.
   A printing company has expressed interest in the old Florsheim
building, which the city of Hermann purchased.
   And Eikel has a wish for the corporation.
   ``I hope Interco gets their thing together and gets back on the
right road,'' she said, ``so they don't have to do this to any more
people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Overall Adv14-16   03-30 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Overall, Adv 14-16,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, April 14-16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Park Overall Has Built Career on Playing Redneck Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Park Overall just about holds a copyright on
portrayals of ``trashy'' Southern women, but what you see isn't
necessarily what you get.
   On NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' starring Richard Mulligan as a recently
widowed Miami pediatrician and Kristy McNichol and Dinah Manoff as
his daughters, Overall plays LaVerne, the nurse with the sharp
tongue and the Southern twang.
   ``I spent four and a half years in New York and I didn't lose my
accent,'' the Tennessean said. ``It's been very good to me. I think
it's so sad so many Southerners don't let on they're Southerners.
This business is about types. I do trashy Southern real well. Maybe
later they'll let me do something else.
   ``I'm limited but it don't bother me none. I can do other
things. I went to New York because I was tired of Yankee girls
playing Southern girls. I'm most comfortable with an Appalachian
accent. I can do a Tidewater accent, but it's a little snooty,''
said Overall, whose unusual monicker is an old family name.
   Wearing skintight jeans, thigh-high boots and a motorcycle
shirt, she sat cross-legged on a couch in her dressing room during
a break in filming. ``These boots improved my social life,'' she
said. ``The crew got very feisty.''
   She also wears a timer device that tells her when she can have a
cigarette. She doesn't smoke on camera. ``They like LaVerne to be
real clean,'' she said.
   ``LaVerne's married to a baseball player. A bad baseball player,
which doesn't make her happy.''
   LaVerne has been criticized as a demeaning Southern stereotype
by Linda Bloodworth-Thomason, creator of ``Designing Women,'' who
objects to such jokes as LaVerne's remark, ``What do I know about
opera? I come from Arkansas.''
   ``I can't say I don't like a line. I'll get fired,'' Overall
replies, but she adds, ``I won't do incest jokes or bestiality
jokes.''
   She was Rowena the prostitute in ``Biloxi Blues'' on Broadway
and in the movie. She was three different voices on ``Talk Radio.''
In ``Mississippi Burning'' she was ``the beauty parlor thing with
the kerchief on my neck and the beehive hairdo.''
   But don't believe the stereotype. True, until she was 27, she
lived in Greeneville, Tenn., about 90 miles northeast of
Chattanooga. However, her father was a federal magistrate and her
mother was an English professor who taught at the University of
Tennessee, Vanderbilt and Randolph-Macon. When her mother took a
sabbatical at Oxford University, Overall attended an English
boarding school. Later, back in Tennessee, she got her college
degree in teaching.
   In her first movie, ``Tainted,'' a low-budget feature made by
some people in Hendersonville, N.C., she played an evil crematorium
operator. ``I got $50 and thought it was the living end,'' she
said. She had acted in school plays all through high school and
college. ``I met my boyfriend doing that movie. He was an assistant
cameraman. We've been together since.'' She has never seen the
movie, however.
   ``My first real professional job in New York was playing Becky
Lou in `The Tooth of the Crime,''' she said. ``I played a rock moll
with a red wig made for me by Paul Huntley. He gave me the wig, and
I wore it to auditions. It's my lucky wig. I still have that wig,
you betcha. It got me `Biloxi Blues.' That wig is to die for, it's
so gorgeous.''
   ``I wanted to wear the wig for LaVerne and make her a nurse in
the fast lane. But they didn't want any nonsense. She's very
wholesome. She has a dry wit, and I think that's turned out to be
right. She's got Southern wit and wisdom. Everything's black or
white, and that's how she gets through the day.''
   Overall kidded that she had to move to New York to see the
South. She was cast there for ``Talk Radio,'' which was filmed in
Dallas, ``Biloxi Blues,'' filmed in Fort Smith, Ark., and
``Mississippi Burning,'' filmed in Georgia and Alabama.
   ``I was just learning to be rude in New York,'' she said. ``Then
I moved to Los Angeles and had to be sweet again.''
</TEXT>
