<DOCNO> AP890330-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MilkenProfile     03-30 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milken Profile,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Trader Key to Drexel's Junk Bond Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Milken Indictment, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Michael Milken, accused
racketeer, also has been called a devoted father, a generous
supporter of charity and creator of the most innovative financial
engine of the century.
   Milken, 42, head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high-yield
bond division, was indicted Wednesday by a Manhattan federal grand
jury for massive securities law and racketeering violations in the
Ivan Boesky insider-trading probe.
   While the indictment apparently will cost the trader his job and
compensation of more than $100 million a year, the much-publicized
investigation has done little to dim Milken's image in the eyes of
friends _ and those who have profited from the junk-bond market he
created.
   As recently as January, Barbara Firestone, who runs a Los
Angeles organization for retarded or emotionally disturbed
children, sang the praises of a man who has donated hundreds of
thousands of dollars and given unstintingly of his time.
   ``It's not the man you see in the newspaper,'' Ms. Firestone
said of Milken.
   Through three family foundations, Milken and his brother,
Lowell, gave more than $17 million to 200 charities over the last
six years.
   Milken's place in modern financial history appears assured by
his role as the virtually single-handed creator of the modern
market in junk bonds.
   The high-risk, high-interest bonds have been used to quickly
raise large cash war chests for corporate takeover strategists and
to fund business expansion by those who couldn't persuade banks or
more conservative venture capitalists to back their efforts.
   A dozen years ago, Milken began preaching the value of the
bonds, which were issued by companies not strong enough to command
favorable ratings from the agencies that advise investors on the
soundness of corporate bonds. Because they are low rated, junk
bonds have to offer higher interest rates to attract investors than
do bonds with higher ratings.
   Milken reasoned that by buying a diverse portfolio of junk
bonds, an investor could hedge against the risk of default by any
one company. The explosive growth of the junk bond market,
responsible in part for waves of corporate takeovers in recent
years, is credited to Milken's fervant advocacy.
   Drexel dominated the market, largely because of Milken, who
presided over an informal network of satisfied clients. Those who
had successfully financed a deal by selling junk bonds stood
willing to buy bonds issued by others.
   In 1977, Milken pulled off a coup by persuading Drexel to let
him move the junk bond division from Manhattan to Beverly Hills,
near his boyhood home of Encino.
   He lives there now with his children and wife, Lori, in a home
once owned by Clark Gable.
   ``Being separated from my life's work is an extremely difficult
step,'' Milken said in a statement Wednesday. ``I am enormously
proud of my 20 years with Drexel Burnham Lambert and it has been an
honor to work with the company's dedicated employees.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TankerSpill-Retirements     03-30 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Retirements,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Oil Spill Experts Reportedly Took Early Retirement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least nine oil spill experts, including Exxon
Corp.'s senior environmental officer, left the company during
personnel cutbacks in 1985 and 1986, a specialist in oil pollution
said.
   It's not clear whether the departures affected the company's
response when one of its tankers struck a reef off Alaska and
leaked 10.1 million gallons of crude oil, said Richard S. Golob,
publisher of Golob's Oil Pollution Bulletin.
   But, he said Wednesday, ``It might be a contributing factor
because they do not have the same experienced cadre of oil spill
professionals that they had prior to the 1986 early retirement
offer.
   ``This is not just an Exxon problem. It's an industry-wide
problem,'' he added.
   Exxon Co. USA spokesman Les Rogers said the company is confident
it has the expertise it needs to tackle Friday's spill in Prince
William Sound. In addition to its own staff, he said, those who
have retired are readily available and the company already has
tapped two former employees as consultants.
   ``One went up on the first plane'' from Houston to Alaska on
Friday, Rogers said.
   Seven of the nine experts left five Exxon subsidiaries and
affiliates in 1986 during an industrywide slump, when Exxon and
other oil companies offered retirement incentives to reduce their
workforces, Golob said.
   An eighth expert in oil spill response departed in 1985, and a
ninth left either in 1985 or 1986, he said.
   Even earlier, the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., the consortium
operating Alaska's Port of Valdez, cut back its staff of oil-spill
experts, The Seattle Times reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper quoted James Woodle, general manager of the port
from 1982-84, and Jerry Nebel, Alyeska oil-spill response
coordinator in 1981-82, as saying they were fired for complaining
about the cutbacks.
   Exxon's Alaska coordinator, Don Cornett, told the newspaper he
was not aware of any such cutbacks at Alyeska. Exxon is part of the
Alyeska consortium.
   Golob said the frequency of major spills has declined in the
last few years and career opportunities in the field have
decreased. But an environmentalist said staff departures should
raise a red flag.
   ``It would be troubling if the company did not replace those
people with equally knowledgable spill response personnel,'' said
Lisa Speer, senior staff scientist with the Natural Resources
Defense Council in New York. ``While Exxon is clearly trying to do
everything they can right now, the response has really been
inexcusably slow.''
   ``We think we have acted responsibly and promptly,'' Exxon's
Rogers said from Houston. ``We were moving a good deal of material
up to the Alaska area from the very start, and we were employing
that equipment and materiel as soon as it got there.''
   A New York oil industry analyst confirmed deep staff cuts at
most oil companies, but said he had no indication that oil spill
control suffered more than any other area of the industry.
   Stephen Smith, an analyst with Bear Sterns, compared keeping a
large staff of oil spill experts to buying insurance. ``If it's not
a here and now present danger, those people are not essential,'' he
said.
   A spokesman for Atlantic Richfield Co. said the company had
trimmed its workforce by more than 19 percent starting in 1985, but
insisted its oil spill programs had not been affected.
   ``Obviously in the process there we lost a number of skilled
people,'' ARCO spokesman Albert Greenstein said in an telephone
interview from Los Angeles Wednesday. ``But to imply that the oil
spill effort suffered as a result of that is really off base.''
   ``It's not a matter of having a handful of `experts' who know
how to fight spills,'' Greenstein added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0207 </DOCNO>
