<FIRST>r f PM-MilkenIndictment Bjt   03-30 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milken Indictment, Bjt,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Financier Faces Mammoth Prison Terms, Billion-Dollar Fines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors are seeking staggering
prison terms and billions of dollars in penalties _ plus $257
million in interest _ against Michael R. Milken and two others
charged in a mammoth racketeering and fraud indictment.
   A federal grand jury in Manhattan handed up a 98-count
indictment Wednesday against the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. junk
bond financier, his brother Lowell and former Drexel trader Bruce
Lee Newberg.
   The long-expected indictment was the biggest development yet in
the snowballing Ivan Boesky insider trading investigation that has
stunned Wall Street for more than two years.
   The three are charged with turning Drexel into a billion-dollar
racketeering enterprise that allegedly used its high-yield, or
junk, bond department for a series of securities fraud schemes with
various unindicted co-conspirators, including the now-imprisoned
Boesky and members of defunct investment partnership
Princeton-Newport LP.
   ``This three-year investigation has uncovered substantial fraud
in a very significant segment of the American financity,'' said U.S. Attorney
Benito Romano.
   Romano said the $1.85 billion in forfeitures were tgainst individuals
under the federal Racketeer Influenced
and C   Milken has headed Drexel's junk bond department since the
mid-1970s and is credited with turning the high-risk, high-yield
securities into a $175 billion annual market. The bonds often are
used to finance corporate takeovers and the growth of small- to
medium-sizedompanies.
   The indictment described the Beverly Hills, Califbased
department as ``the driving force behind Drexel's business,''
noting that between 1983 ait accounted for nearly half of
Drexel's profitl three defendants denied wrongdoing and said they would
plead
nnocent.
   ``The allegations against me are b Lowell Milken said
in a statement. ``The proof will show that  virtually no
contacts with Ivan Boesky, and that I had little, if anything, to
do with the events the prosecumisrepresent in order to
construct their charges.
   ``I have been thrown into this indictment because of a fact in
which I take great pride _ I am Michael Milken's brother.''
   Michael Milken said he would plead innocent ``and vigorse accusations.''
   ``In America an indictment marks the beginning of the legal
process, not the end. After  2{ years of leaks and
distortions I am now eager to present all the facts in an open and
unbiased forum,'' hitatement said.
   Newberg and several Princeton-Newport partners were indicted
last year on fraud and racketeering counts in another stock case,
which defentorneys claimed was brought to pressure them into
cooperating against Drexel.
   Newberg's lawyers, Gerald Lefcourt and Frederick P. Hafetz,
called the second racketeering indictment ``a total perversion of
the RICO statute.''
   If convicted on the racketeering counts alone, prosecutors said,
the defendants face maximum fines of $3.7 billion each. All three
face maximum prison sentences of 20 years on e two
racketeering charges.
  ition, the three are subject to forfeiture proceedings on
virtually all money they have made through their Drexel dealings
since 1984, an estimated $1.85 billion.
   That includes $1.2 billion in salaries, $112 million in Drexel
stock, $205 million in corporate finance fees, $37 million in
tradingon allegedly tainted deals and $257 million in
``calculated at a blended rate of 7.91 percent.''
   Michael Milken also was charged with all of the 96
non-racketeering counts, which include numerous mail, wire and
securities charges. Lowell Milken was charged with 11 counts and
Newberg was charged with 20 counts.
   Each faces a maximum penalty of five years and at least $250,000
in fines on each of the non-racketeering charges _ making Michael
Milken subject to $24 million in fines and a total of 520 years
imprisonment.
   The indictment palleled the Securities and Exchann's sweeping civil
insider trading action against Drexel,
Milken and others last September.
   In December, D struck a plea bargain with federal
prosecutors that called for the dismissal of Milken and the
withholding of most of his 1988 compensation _ estimated at be100 million
and $200 million.
   As part of the plea bargain, which Drexel says it made to avoid
crippling racketeering charges, the firm agreed to plead guideral felony
charges and pay $650 million in fines and
penaltie
   Drexel has not yet pleaded to the charges, and settlement of the
criminal case remained sval.
   Drexel also agreed to withhold half the money due Lowell Milken
for 1988 if he were indicted. His compensation in 198 $48
million, according to the indictment. A Drnt said the
Milkens had been placed on leave of absence.
   ``We are saddened by the terrible disruption to the lives and
cars of these people, especially when viewed againns made by Michael and
his department in the opening of
new captal markets to hundreds of companies and helping to create
hundreds of thousands of jobs,'' Drexel said.
