<DOCNO> AP890330-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MCorpFailure Bjt   03-30 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCorp Failure, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCorp's Failure Caused By Domino-Effect Of Energy Bust, Analysts
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, which declared itself ``a momentum
company'' when it was formed five years ago, was the victim of
Texas' downward economic spiral caused by falling oil prices even
though the bank holding company poured more money into real estate
than energy, analysts said.
   The $18 billion, 25-bank holding company was stripped of all but
five banks by Wednesday after federal regulators declared the banks
involvent. The government pumped in $300 million in what likely
will become the third largest commercial bank rescue ever.
   The 20 banks were combined into the government-owned Deposit
Insurance Bridge Bank NA, while officials search for a buyer for
some of all of the banks.
   ``Once the Texas real estate markets began to slip, there really
was very little they could do,'' said banking analyst Michael Starr
at Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago. ``What you're seeing in the real
estate market is simply what started a decade ago in energy
problems. ... MCorp is at the tail-end of feeling those problems.''
   MCorp probably was guilty of ``over-aggressive lending,'' Starr
said, but not to the extent of other Texas banks. Most of its
loans, he said, were made to reputable developers, unlike many
troubled thrifts that had backed inexperienced developers.
   ``The straightforward, honest answer is that the state of Texas
was hit by an economic H-bomb that had effects on real estate
portfolios, energy portfolios ...,'' said Robert D. Rieke, a
banking analyst with the Dallas firm of Rauscher Pierce Refsnes Inc.
   ``To its tribute, MCorp has been able to withstand the fallout
longer than anybody else,'' said Rieke, once a vice-president and
treasurer at MCorp.
   MCorp, which has yet to report annual earnings, also has blamed
its troubles on real estate, telling stockholders last December
that ``asset quality problems, largely related to loans secured by
real estate and assets acquired through foreclosure, adversely
affected the company's financial performance'' in the third
quarter, when MCorp posted a $517 million loss. The Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. has said MCorp's banks lost another $213 million in
the fourth quarter and $903 million for the year.
   While a weak real estate climate hurt MCorp, its final tumble
began last week when a Connecticut bond trader and two employees _
who together held just over $2 million in bonds _ moved to force
the company into bankruptcy because they had not been paid since
October when the company announced a moratorium on payments on $470
million in bonds and preferred stock.
   MCorp's response on Monday was to announce it would seek
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code. The resulting uncertainty apparently set off a run on
deposits.
   Federal regulators, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
between $50 million and $100 million was withdrawn Tuesday from the
flagship MBank Dallas. The withdrawals came both from individual
depositors and some of MCorp's other subsidiary banks, the
regulators said.
   The Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas called in a loan to MBank
Dallas, but the bank couldn't pay and was declared insolvent.
   ``Depositors at 19 of the failed institutions, including those
with funds in excess of the $100,000 insurance limit, were fully
protected,'' the FDIC said. At MBank Abliene, only deposits up to
the insurance limit were transferred.
   All the banks remain open for business as usual, with former
MCorp employees now working for the government.
   The remaining five MBanks, in Brownsville, Corpus Christi, El
Paso, New Braunfels and Waco, plus a trust and investment
subsidiary ``form the nucleus of a new beginning for MCorp,'' the
company said Wednesday.
   ``While the nature of MCorp has been altered dramatically, a
solid healthy core remains,'' said MCorp Chairman Gene H. Bishop.
   But analysts are unsure whether MCorp can survive in any form.
   MCorp still faces claims against its remaining assets by
bondholders and the FDIC, which Chairman William Seidman said holds
``substantial'' claims against the parent company.
   Analysts said it is unlikely those claims can be resolved in any
fashion other than liquidation.
   The government's rescue came almost six months after MCorp had
asked for federal assistance.
   Bishop and other managers had put together their own bid for the
bank, but the FDIC _ rather than acting on the plan _ opened up the
bidding to all comers, setting an April 3 deadline.
   Seidman said Wednesday that deadline may be extended. Several
groups have been reportedly looking at MCorp's books, including
Wells Fargo & Co.; leveraged buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co., apparently representing management; interests of Chicago's
wealthy Pritzker family, which controls the Hyatt hotel chain; and
First City Bancorp. of Texas Inc., itself the recipient of federal
assistance.
</TEXT>
