<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0831EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TaxReturns     03-30 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Returns,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Promise of Speedy Refunds Won't Last Long</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service, nearing the end
of a tax filing season that so far has been almost a breeze, is
still promising refunds within six weeks _ but not for long.
   ``Those who file closer to the (April 17) deadline will probably
have to wait longer for their refund,'' the IRS said Wednesday in
renewing its ``file early'' plea.
   The agency said that heading into the last three weeks of the
filing season, more than half the 109 million couples and
individuals who are expected to submit returns sometime this year
still had not done so. That means a crunch as the deadline
approaches, with nearly 32 million returns expected in the final
two weeks.
   But while that represents about 30 percent of the year's total,
it is about the same percentage of procrastinators as in 1988, the
IRS said.
   Through last Friday, the IRS had received 53.1 million returns,
up 0.7 percent from 52.8 million during the same period a year ago.
The agency's 10 service centers had processed 3.3 percent more than
at this time last year: 42.4 million compared with 41.1 million in
1988.
   Three of the 10 centers _ in Atlanta, Memphis and Austin, Texas
_ have processed slighly fewer returns than they had at this time a
year ago.
   That is not a matter of concern, said IRS spokesman Frank Keith,
because those three centers were given new territories this year as
the agency redistributed its workload and have received fewer
returns so far. The important statistic, Keith said, is that the
three have processed more returns than they had been scheduled to.
   The only black mark on this year's filing season from the IRS'
perspective is the low accuracy rate on answering taxpayers'
telephoned questions.
   In some areas of the country, IRS surveys found, the agency's
``assistors'' are correct barely half the time. Nationwide, these
5,000 employees gave incorrect responses to 30.8 percent of test
questions.
   Publicity about those wrong answers could account for the fact
that fewer taxpayers are calling the agency's toll-free answer line
with specific tax questions. Through last week, 19.3 million calls
had been received, down from 20.6 million during the same period a
year ago.
   On the other hand, the number of calls received by the IRS
Tele-Tax system has nearly tripled _ from 5.4 million to 15.1
million. Tele-Tax, whose toll-free numbers and subject list are
included in the back of the instruction packages mailed by the IRS,
offers tape-recorded advice on more than 140 tax topics.
   You may call the same number if you have not received your
refund. You will need the first Social Security number shown on
your return, your filing status and the exact amount of your refund.
   More than 74 percent (31.4 million) of the returns so far this
year have been certified for refunds totaling $25.6 billion, an
average refund of almost $816. At this time last year, 75 percent
of filers (30.8 million) had had refunds approved. Those refunds
totaled $25.2 billion and averaged $817.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
