<FIRST>r f PM-CrazyEddie     03-30 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crazy Eddie,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crazy Eddie Announces Widespread Store Closings To Restore Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crazy Eddie Inc. is closing 17 of 43 stores
in four states in a bid to revive its electronics retail business.
   The decision was made final late Tuesday, and workers learned of
the closings Wednesday, when the chosen outlets shut their doors,
said spokeswoman Omi Walden.
   ``Of course we would prefer not to have to do it that way, but
circumstances did not permit otherwise,'' she said.
   ``The objective here was to cut losses and to improve
profitability. There was a need to move as quickly as possible,''
said Walden.
   Ms. Walden said she did not know how many employees were
involved. The affected stores were in New York, New Jersey,
Connecticut and Pennsylvania.
   In a three-paragraph statement announcing the closings, the
financially troubled company said it wanted to concentrate on its
26 ``best performing and most competitive stores.''
   Crazy Eddie, known for its frenetic broadcast commercials and
claims of ``Our prices are insane!,'' said it would meet with its
major vendors to discuss ``liquidity problems'' and a possible
financial restructuring. Ms. Walden declined to comment on what
that might be.
   A ``massive inventory shortage, excessive long-term debt and
certain unprofitable store locations'' inherited from previous
management has drained working capital, said company president
Peter A. Martosella Jr.
   Compounding the problems was a big drop in sales, Martosella
said. Crazy Eddie said it lost $8 million for the third quarter of
1988, ended November 27. Fourth quarter figures are being prepared,
said Ms. Walden.
   Crazy Eddie's stock closed at 53 cents a share Wednesday,
unchanged from the previous close. It had been as high as $21 three
years ago.
   Elias Zinn, founder of Houston-based Electronics Marketing Inc.,
and turnaround specialist Victor Palmieri took over Crazy Eddie in
November 1987 from reclusive founder Eddie Antar. Palmieri is
chairman and Zinn, who stepped down as president earlier this year,
remains a director.
   Early on, the new management told of internal turmoil and
inventory shortfalls. Vendors complained of unpaid bills, and
investors sued.
   The new management has struggled to build the company back. It
lined up new credit, computerized the inventory, worked on customer
service and last summer restructured debt.
   The company closed three of 11 stores in New Jersey; 10 of 21 in
New York; two of seven in Connecticut; and two of four in
Pennsylvania.
</TEXT>
