<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-EEC-Tobacco     03-30 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Tobacco,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Seeks Strict Rules For Tobacco Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission Thursday proposed to
ban advertisements by tobacco makers for non-tobacco products and
said visible health warnings should be printed on all tobacco
advertising.
   Ads for clothing and other non-tobacco items using a symbol or
trademark of a tobacco brand will be banned if the 12 EEC states
adopt the European Economic Community Commsision proposal.
   It also suggested forcing tobacco makers to display any of 12
health warnings in their ads and that ads for a particular brand of
cigarettes only show a pack of cigarettes and their tar content.
   Any warning about the health hazards of smoking should cover at
least 10 percent of the advertisements' total space, the Commission
recommended.
   The Commission said in a statement it made its proposals as part
of its `Europe Against Cancer' program. Annually, 440,000 EEC
nationals die of diseases caused or aggravated by smoking, it said.
   The requirement that only a cigarette packet and the tar content
be shown in advertisements is already in effect in France.
   But of the 12 EEC states only Portugal and Ireland have a total
ban on tobacco advertising. Greece, Luxembourg and Spain have few
restrictions on such ads.
   In the other six EEC nations tobacco ads must carry the same
health warning that appears on the packet.
   The Commission's proposals for EEC-wide rules on tobacco ads
must be approved by the European Parliament and the 12 EEC states
before they can take effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
