<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AmocoCutbacks     03-30 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amoco Cutbacks,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amoco Production Plans to Cut 800 Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 800 Amoco Production Co. employees will be
cut from company payrolls as part of a reorganization this spring,
reflecting a trend by major oil companies to emphasize foreign
exploration and production over U.S. operations.
   Amoco Production is the oil and gas exploration subsidiary of
Amoco Corp., the nation's fifth-largest energy company, and
officials say the reductions are designed to reduce costs and
better focus resources.
   The cuts announced Wednesday amount to about 10 percent of the
U.S. employees, officials said.
   The subsidiary has 15,000 workers worldwide, including about
8,000 U.S. citizens who are paid in U.S. dollars no matter where
they work, according to spokesman Richard Judy of Chicago-based
Amoco Corp.
   The job cuts, slated to begin in May, would come through
placement of employees with other Amoco Corp. subsidiaries,
voluntary retirement, voluntary resignation and some firings, the
company said.
   The reductions will be made ``to reduce our costs and focus our
resources _ money, physical assets and people _ on those areas
where the projected financial returns are the most attractive,''
said Patrick J. Early, president of Amoco Production.
   Early said the changes reflect general trends of shrinking the
company's domestic organization while expanding international
operations.
   For the first time in its 100-year history, Amoco plans to spend
more money in 1989 searching for oil and gas abroad than in the
United States.
   The company said it plans to take advantage of its strong
natural gas reserve position, look into property trades with other
companies and continue divesting marginal and non-strategic
properties.
   The reorganization of Amoco's U.S. exploration and production
operations follows similar moves recently by Texaco Inc., Atlantic
Richfield Co. and Phillips Petroleum Co.
   ``The majors are looking in foreign areas because they've got a
better chance of finding a big field there,'' said Ray Beresford, a
principal of International Energy Consultants Ltd. in Morristown,
N.J.
   ``The Lower 48 (states) is pretty well picked over, and the only
hopes of a big field in the U.S. _ Alaska or offshore California _
you can't touch'' because of environmental concerns, he said.
   In the last year, U.S. oil production has dropped 5 percent.
   Amoco Corp. and its subsidiaries employ 55,000 people worldwide.
The energy and chemical company sold 6 percent of all refined
petroleum products in the United States last year, and had 1988
revenues of $23.9 billion, Judy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
