<DOCNO> AP890330-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 0934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Unisys     03-30 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unisys,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Expects First-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer giant Unisys Corp. expects to lose
up to $80 million in the year's first quarter partly because of the
Navy's suspension of bidding rights for three of its defense
divisions.
   The company also cited slow sales of its 1100 line of mainframe
computers, which was replaced by the 2200 series last month.
   In a statement Wednesday, Unisys said it anticipates turning a
profit in the second quarter as it steps up delivery of the 2200
series mainframes.
   The estimated loss for the quarter ending Friday would be about
55 cents to 65 cents per common share, the company said. It expects
to report final first-quarter results April 21.
   Michael Geran, an analyst with Nikko Securities International in
New York, said the projected loss was higher than the $20 million
to $25 million he had expected.
   ``But once you go negative, there's a natural tendency to throw
everything but the kitchen sink in,'' he said.
   Unisys said the government's ``Operation Ill Wind''
investigation and the indefinite suspension of three defense
divisions caused disruption and added costs during the quarter.
   The Navy announced earlier this month that it had suspended
bidding rights of the Shipboard and Ground Systems Group, the
Computer Systems Division and the Communications Systems Division
of Unisys.
   The former Sperry Corp. divisions _ based in Great Neck, N.Y.,
Eagan, Minn., and Salt Lake City, Utah _ provided 70 percent of
Unisys' defense-related revenues.
   Peter Hynes, a Unisys spokesman, said the suspended units
performed about $1.6 billlion worth of federal government work last
year. Unisys as a whole had $9.9 billion in revenues last year.
   The suspension came less than a week after a former Unisys vice
president and a former Unisys consultant pleaded guilty in federal
court in Alexandria, Va., to trying to bribe former Navy officials.
   Another Unisys executive and a second Unisys consultant entered
guilty pleas on Jan. 27 to making illegal campaign contributions to
members of Congress.
   Unisys was formed when Burroughs Corp. took over Sperry in 1986
in a $4.8 billion deal.
   The company also said first-quarter sales were affected by a
restructuring of its U.S. computer business, the formation of new
product groups and the integration of Convergent Technologies Inc.,
a California computer company acquired in 1988.
   The company said in February it had laid off 1,700 employees at
60 U.S. sites and would close an assembly plant in Nogales, Mexico,
terminating 400 jobs.
</TEXT>
