<FIRST>r f PM-Polaroid-Kodak     03-30 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Kodak,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Court Date With Kodak Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. and Eastman Kodak Co.
will meet in court May 1 in the damages phase of their patent
infringement case.
   U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone postponed the previous date
of April 17, Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said Wednesday.
   In 1985 Kodak was found guilty by U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel
in Boston of violating several Polaroid patents. But Zobel revealed
during preparation for the damages phase of the trial that she had
inherited $100,000 in Kodak stock.
   Kodak requested that Zobel disqualify herself from the case,
that all her orders in the 13-year-old dispute be nullified and a
new trial held. Zobel stepped aside, but Mazzone refused to have
her orders vacated. The First U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
Mazzone's decision on Feb. 17.
   Polaroid is seeking $5.7 billion, but Kodak lawyers have said
$200 million would be ``more than ample.''
</TEXT>
