<FIRST>r f PM-Prime-MAIBasic 1stLd-Writethru f0048 03-30 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime-MAI Basic, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0048,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Computer Firm's Bid Blocked Only By Disclosure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT that ruling by appeals court,
not judge; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `MAI Basic...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has effectively cleared
the way for a California company to pursue its $970 million
takeover bid for Prime Computer Inc., turning attention to an
expected proxy fight at Prime's annual meeting in May.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Wednesday that an
injunction blocking MAI Basic Four Inc.'s bid would be lifted after
the Tustin, Calif.-based company provided specific details of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s financial involvement in the deal.
   The court upheld a December ruling by U.S. District Judge A.
David Mazzone, who was ordered to lift the injunction once
appropriate discloures are made.
   MAI Basic has offered $20 a share for Natick-based Prime, which
is four times the size of its suitor.
   William B. Patton, MAI Basic's president, said the court
explicitly stated what information needs to be provided.
   ``Once that's provided, the injunction will be lifted,'' said
Patton.
   The court decision requires MAI Basic to provide Drexel
financial statements, records of recent stock trading activity and
identification of all Drexel-affiliated officers and directors.
   Patton said the legal fight over MAI's bid for Prime could prove
moot after Prime's shareholders hold their annual meeting on May 12.
   ``The whole thing is going to come down to a proxy fight
anyway,'' Patton said in a telephone interview from California.
``We've applied to the SEC for approval and we're expecting it any
day. After that, the court actions become nothing more than legal
jostling.''
   But Prime spokesman Joe Gavaghan said the appeals court ruling
affirmed the company's position that stockholders needed additional
information to make an educated decision in the takeover battle.
   ``Basically we feel that the lower court decision being upheld
will ultimately serve our shareholders in obtaining for them the
additional information that we've argued needs to be disclosed
here,'' Gavaghan said.
   Mazzone last month continued the order blocking MAI's bid while
asking for additional information about how Drexel Burnham would
finance the deal.
   In January, MAI Basic said officials at the New York firm were
confident they could raise the $875 million to finance the takeover
despite its guilty plea in a massive securities fraud settlement.
   Patton said Wednesday that MAI officials would work with Drexel
Burnham to comply with the court's guidelines and disclose all
pertinent documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
