<FIRST>r f BC-Centel-Cable     03-30 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Centel-Cable,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centel Completes Sale of Cable TV Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centel Corp. says it has found buyers for its two
remaining cable television properties and that it hopes to complete
the $1.4 billion, six-way breakup of the nation's 22nd largest
cable company this fall.
   The Chicago-based communications concern said Wednesday it would
sell its Kentucky cable operation to Simmons Communications Inc. of
Stamford, Conn., and its southeast Florida cable business to
Adelphia Communications Corp. of Coudersport, Pa.
   Centel's cable business in Kentucky has 60,000 subscribers and
its Florida operation serves 125,000 subscribers.
   Adelphia also will acquire the stock of Centel Cable Television
Co., the Centel subsidiary that ran the six cable networks, Centel
said in a statement.
   Centel would not reveal the sale price of each cable property
but said the gross proceeds from the sales of all six units would
be more than $1.4 billion.
   Centel announced the sales last week of its cable operations in
central Florida, Illinois, Michigan and Ohio in four separate
transactions.
   Centel said in late November that it planned to sell its cable
unit to concentrate on its telecommunications businesses, which
include local exchange service in nine states and a cellular
telephone subsidiary that operates in 13 states.
   The company said last week that it would break up its cable
subsidiary and sell the six parts separately.
   Centel said it expects to complete the sales in the third
quarter.
</TEXT>
