<FIRST>d f BC-OAPEC-Refining     03-30 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-OAPEC-Refining,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAPEC Needs More Capital For New Refineries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries urged its member states Thursday to invest in oil
refining industries to meet new trends in world demand for oil
products.
   An OAPEC statement issued at the end of a three-day seminar on
the Arab refining industry, affirmed ``the need to direct
investment toward building new refining units in the Arab countries
that can process heavy high-sulphur Arab crudes and handle surplus
fuel oil.''
   Such investement ``will increase the marketing potential of Arab
producers, since these crudes constitute a large portion of their
oil reserves,'' the statement said.
   More than 100 delegates and oil experts from Arab countries,
regional and international companies and organizations, including
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, attended the
meeting.
   The Kuwait-based 11-member OAPEC, in which seven countries
double as members of OPEC, provides a forum for coordinating Arab
oil policies.
   OAPEC members are: Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, the United Arab
Emirates, Iraq, Algeria, Libya, Bahrain, Syria, Tunisia and Egypt.
The first seven are OPEC members.
   The participants noted the share of light products in the total
demand for oil was growing steadily and that there is a trend
toward eliminating pollutants such as sulphur and lead from oil
products in line with new environmental regulations in major
markets.
</TEXT>
