<HEAD>Rain, Speculative Selling Pressures Crop Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were slightly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
reports of rain in major crop-growing areas and speculative selling
ahead of two important government reports.
   Soybean futures have fallen in the past four sessions and the
pattern continued this morning due to rain in the Midwest, slack
export demand and weakening chart signals, analysts said.
   Rainy weather in the Midwest and Great Plains also encouraged
selling of wheat and corn futures, although early losses in the
corn market were limited by the Agriculture Department's
announcement late Wednesday that the Soviet Union had bought
450,000 metric tons of U.S. corn _ Moscow's second major purchase
of U.S. corn this week.
   The USDA will release its quarterly grain stocks report and
annual spring planting estimates after the close on Friday. The
eagerly awaited reports will indicate whether grain prices are
likely to rise or fall this summer, assuming growing conditions are
favorable.
