<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Spain     03-30 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Spain,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spain Says It Intends to Join EMS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez
said Thursday that Spain intends to join the European Monetary
System in the near future.
   ``A lot of time will not go by before this decision is made to
join the EMS,'' he said.
   The 10-year-old system is a grid of eight European Economic
Community currencies that by common agreement must move in bands
between fixed upper and lower limits. If they exceed the limits,
central banks must intervene or governments take monetary action.
   Gonzalez said it did not ``seem reasonable to expect a country
to announce in advance precisely when it's going to ask to enter
the EMS.''
   Of the 12 EEC currencies, only the Spanish peseta, the British
pound, the Greek drachma and the Portuguese escudo are not part of
the EMS exchange rate mechanism.
   Spain has said it would join the EMS several other times.
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who has long been under
pressure to join, has said repeatedly she will do so ``when the
time is right.''
</TEXT>
