<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-OPEC 3rdLd-Writethru f0102 03-30 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0102,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Meeting Ends</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs meeting over, OPEC maintaining production
cuts; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Since the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers pledged today to stand by
an agreement to slash production in the next three months as they
wrapped up a two-day strategy session.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto said a panel of eight ministers
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries renewed their
intention to ``adhere very strictly'' in the April-June quarter to
a November pact to slash production.
   The meeting was the organization's first formal review of the
oil market since the accord, which covers the first six months of
the year.
   The ministers addressed tactics for maintaining the surprising
strength of the current market. There had been indications some
ministers ministers wanted to raise the production cap to keep oil
prices from rising too fast.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh said, ``Everything is
going very well. ... Everybody is satisfied with the current market
stability.''
   Diego Tamariz, the Ecuadoran oil minister attending the talks as
an observer, said the discussions centered on the market situation
and long-term strategy.
   Since the cartel agreed in November to slash production in the
first half of this year, prices have rallied, unexpectedly reaching
this week the OPEC benchmark of $18 a barrel.
   With firming prices, the ministers were already beginning to
turn their attention to the output accord that will be hammered out
in early June to cover the last half of the year.
   The November arrangement called for the countries to limit their
production to a total of 18.5 million barrels a day, well under the
level of last last year. It also set the target price of $18 a
barrel.
   The average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by the
cartel reached $18.01 a barrel Tuesday. The price is up more than
$5 a barrel since November.
   The May contract price for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, was up 39 cents in early trading today to
$20.59 cents a 42-gallon barrel after rising 29 cents Wednesday on
the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The price, the highest for the near-term contract since August
1987, was lifted partly by concern about the oil tanker spill off
Alaska on Friday.
   Prices for West Texas Intermediate and North Sea Brent blend,
the most widely traded international crudes, have climbed more than
the Middle Eastern crudes offered by the OPEC countries.
   The price surge has been linked to the reduction in OPEC
production as well as unforeseen accidents in producing regions
that have clipped supply. Demand also has been stronger than
forecast.
   Subroto said the monitoring committee would meet ``several
times, many times'' before the June meeeting.
   Sabah indicated in a recent interview with the Middle East
Economic Survey that he would like the daily output cap lifted to
20 million barrels in the last six months of the year.
   Asked Wednesday about the interview, he said, ``It is my
position, but we are reasonable people. We have to look at supply
and demand and decide on that basis. We're going to look at the
figures and then decide in June.''
   Other ministers have been more cautious about urging changes in
the accord. Several have insisted that the cartel must wait to see
how the market acts in the April-June quarter, when prices
generally weaken as demand slips with the coming of warmer weather
in oil importing nations.
   Indepednent oil exporting nations, including the Soviet Union,
have agreed to help OPEC in the second quarter by trimming their
exports to a total of about 300,000 barrels a day.
   Members of the monitoring committee are Algeria, Indonesia,
Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
   Other OPEC members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar and the
United Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv31   03-30 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 31,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, March 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>Creators Say SuperTrust Fund Proposal Could Be NYSE Volume Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the never-ending search for a strategy
to beat Wall Street, two professors and their partner have created
an innovative investment fund they say could become a New York
Stock Exchange trading leader.
   The SuperTrust investment fund, designed for all kinds of market
conditions, is the brainchild of University of California-Berkeley
finance professors Hayne Leland and Mark Rubinstein and their
associate, John O'Brien.
   The three principals of LOR Associates are better known as the
fathers of portfolio insurance, a hedging strategy that was
supposed to protect institutional investors against market declines
_ but fared poorly in the crash of Oct. 19, 1987.
   Portfolio insurance, in which traders sell stock index futures
and options to reduce the impact of a falling market on their
holdings, was blamed by some for accelerating the crash. LOR
managed more than $60 million in portfolio insurance before the
crash and has since dropped to about $20 million.
   To overcome some failings of portfolio insurance, Leland said,
he and his partners went to work developing the SuperTrust fund
``on Oct. 20.''
   The resulting fund would allow individual and institutional
investors to tailor their investments to different objectives.
Unlike portfolio insurance, SuperTrust would be collateralized by
underlying securities.
   ``This is an idea that has been around for some time in very
theoretical form,'' Leland said in an interview. ``The problem was
to engineer it to the point where we could bring it to the market.''
   SuperTrust is expected to be approved for listing by the
Securities and Exchange Commission in a few months. It will be
divided into two SuperUnits, one invested in stocks and the other
in interest-bearing securities.
   The underlying assumption is that when the stock market falls,
interest rates tend to move higher and vice versa.
   The stock SuperUnit will be a fund of the Standard &amp; Poors 500
index managed by Wells Fargo Investment Advisors. It will be
subdivided into two types of SuperShares _ Appreciation Shares that
would do best if the stock market soars and Index Income Shares
that would do best if the market rises only moderately.
   The other SuperUnit will be a money market fund invested in
short-term, high-grade securities, mainly Treasury bills. This
trust also will be split into Money Market Income Shares that would
do best in a flat market and Protection Shares that would do best
if the stock market falls.
   What SuperTrust doesn't do is eliminate the need for investors
to determine when to move from one fund to the other. There also
will be a charge for trading SuperShares, about 2.5 percent for
small accounts and 0.25 percent for large ones.
   Leland told analysts recently that SuperTrust's assets would
have to be large enough to provide liquidity for institutional
investors. He estimated the assets could reach $2 billion to $10
billion its first year.
   SuperTrust might confuse some small investors and retail brokers
initially, some analysts said, but it is already creating
excitement among institutional investors.
   ``I find it extremely fascinating,'' said Joel Damon, a vice
president at Bank of America who helps guide the investment of a
$850 million pension fund and $400 million savings plan. ``I think
it's a well thought out strategy, but it's too early to tell if our
pension fund can make use of these products.
   ``It doesn't help provide you with a crystal ball, but it does
provide you with alternatives to the futures and options market for
hedging your bet,'' he said.
   John Dolanm of Dolan Capital Management in Menlo Park, calls
SuperTrust ``sheer genius. It's going to change the way the world
thinks about investing.''
   Investors who lost money with portfolio insurance may avoid the
SuperTrust, Dolan said. ``But LOR won't necessarily be selling to
the same group of people. They'll be selling this to people who
weren't sophisticated enough to buy portfolio insurance. It's much
more straightforward. The potential market will be much higher.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for PMs Friday, March 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
