<DOCNO> AP890330-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bush-OilSpill 4thLd-Writethru   03-30 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Oil Spill, 4th Ld-Writethru,f0096,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Won't Take Over Cleanup Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Bush remarks; picks up at pvs 6th graf,
Transportation Secretary ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today called the massive oil
spill in Alaska's Prince William Sound ``a major tragedy'' as his
administration ruled out as counterproductive a federal takeover of
cleanup operations.
   ``The cleanup will not be easy,'' Bush said. ``But, as with
other serious disasters, we must and will work together at all
levels, public and private, to remedy the damage that's been done
and then to safeguard the precious environment for the future.''
   Separately, Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost said it was
``almost unbelievable'' that the supertanker Exxon Valdez could
have gotten outside a 10-mile wide shipping lane to run aground
last Friday.
   ``Obviously something went very badly wrong,'' Yost told a White
House news briefing after he and two other senior federal officials
reported to Bush on their two-day fact-finding trip to the site of
the largest oil spill in U.S. history.
   The president referred to the accident in a speech to the
Association of Community and Junior Colleges.
   Departing from his prepared text, he called the 100-mile long
oil slick ``a subject of concern to all Americans today.''
   ``There's no doubt this is a major tragedy, both for the
environment and for the people up there,'' Bush said. He said the
report from the three officials ``was not all negative. But let's
be frank. There are some very serious problems up there right now.''
   ``This was not a treacherous area, not treacherous in the area
where they ran aground,'' Adm. Yost told reporters. ``It's 10 miles
wide. Your children could drive a tanker up through it.''
   Yost said allegations of ``alcohol use'' by the ship's captain
would be thoroughly investigated by the government.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said cleanup operations
were now being well coordinated. ``All of us are convinced that the
effort, after a somewhat slow start, is going at full speed,''
Skinner said.
   He said there was ``no need to federalize this effort'' and that
such a move ``might be counterproductive.'' Bush had initially
mentioned a federal takeover as one option.
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William Reilly
called the spill, the nation's largest ever, ``obviously a disaster
of enormous magnitude.''
   He said ``it seems inevitable that there will be a very
substantial impact, particularly on the habitats of sea otters and
sea lions.''
   However, Reilly said, ``it's too soon to say in any conclusive
way what the impact on habitat or on the wildlife will be.''
   He said Bush had directed that environmental and wildlife
protection in the once-pristine sound be given ``top priority.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the officials
would continue to monitor the cleanup from Washington and would
report back in 30 days with ``broader recommendations,'' including
possible options for long-term action.
   Skinner said Exxon Corp. was making ``an all-out effort,'' but
that the federal government would make sure that the corporation
honored its commitments. He declined to criticize Exxon for its
current efforts but said its initial response ``could have been
quicker.''
   ``If we don't learn from this experience, we are just not
performing our job,'' Skinner said.
   He said most of the damage was done in the first few hours after
the 978-foot tanker ran around, spilling more than 10 million
gallons of crude oil into the once pristine sound.
   The transportation secretary said the tanker was moving at a
brisk 15 knots when it ran into the reef, well outside the regular
navigation channel.
   The three officials met with Bush for about 45 minutes, then
spoke with reporters in the White House briefing room.
   Skinner said Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper told the federal team
``that the effort is now going forward at the correct pace. Exxon,
the state and the federal government were working well together.''
   He said the prospect of a federal takeover of the cleanup ``will
be held in abeyance'' but was not a live option at this time.
   Reilly, the EPA administrator, said his agency would closely
monitor the environmental impact of the 500-square-mile spill.
   He said the officials did not see any direct evidence of impact
on wildlife in their helicopter tour over the oil-stained beaches.
But, he said, ``it has affected any number of coves and inlets.''
   The officials said that no decison has yet been made on a
request by the state to declare the sound a diaster area, but that
it is under consideration.
   One issue under review in the federal investigation, according
to James Kolstad, the acting head of the National Transportation
Safety Board, is why Joseph Hazelwood, the captain of the Exxon
Valdez, had a license to operate the tanker at a time when he
didn't have a license to drive a car.
   Hazelwood's driver's license was suspended because of a drunken
driving conviction.
</TEXT>
