<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted lower today, pausing
after its rally of the past three sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 38.48 points in the
week's first three trading days, slipped 2.56 to 2,278.96 by 2 p.m.
on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 608 up, 686 down and
551 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that new factory
orders declined 2.3 percent in February.
   That provided fresh support for the view that the pace of the
economy began to slow last month.
   But analysts have been reluctant to conclude from a single
month's data that the Federal Reserve has succeeded in its efforts
to subdue inflationary pressures by tightening credit.
   The first indication of whether the slowing continued in March
will come in the Labor Department's monthly employment report late
next week.
   In the meantime, stocks got little support today from the bond
market, where interest rates rose slightly.
   Illinois Power led the active list, down 1] at 14]. The Illinois
Commerce Commission granted a much smaller rate increase than the
company had sought.
   Genentech dropped 1| to 17}. An article in the New England
Journal of Medicine reported on a study suggesting that the
company's clot-dissolving drug for treatment of heart attacks is no
more effective than a much less expensive alternative drug.
   Sears Roebuck rose } to 43}. The company announced plans for a
major revamping of its organizational structure.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .03 to 164.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .84 at 324.74.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 107.50 million shares with two
hours to go.
