<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Oil     03-30 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Oil,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Require Oil Exporters to Obtain Licenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet oil producers will have to apply for
permission to export their wares abroad under new regulations that
cover manufacture of petroleum products by independent cooperatives.
   The Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations will be responsible
for issuing the licenses under the regulations that cover exports
for the period 1989-90, the weekly Ekonomicheskaya Gazeta newspaper
said in its latest issue.
   Until now, oil production has been a monopoly of the state and
regulated by the Soyuzneftexport organization of the All-Union
Foreign Trade Association.
   Now cooperatives and associations also have the right to try to
export oil on the world market.
   The regulations form part of a general decree issued by the
Council of Ministers on March 7.
   Oil, raw oil, gas, natural gas, and diesel fuel are among the
products covered by the rules.
   The Soviets export an estimated 1.8 million barrels of oil a day.
</TEXT>
