<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-30 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Collapse On Feelings Drought Is Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower across the board Thursday on speculation that the long dry
spell in the nation's heartland is drawing to a close.
   A night of heavier-than-expected rainfall in the drought-plagued
wheat fields of western Kansas kicked the selling into motion on
the Chicago Board of Trade and it simply snowballed, gathering
momentum as wave after wave of sell orders washed through the
markets.
   ``There's an old saying that rain begets rain,'' said Cathy
Leow, a grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
in New York.
   ``Watch out when a drought begins to break; it typically means
there'll be more rain,'' she said, noting forecasts for weekend
showers in the Great Plains and the Midwest.
   The selling also reflected a continued evening of positions
ahead of Friday afternoon's Agriculture Department quarterly grain
stocks report and spring planting estimates.
   At the close, wheat was 10 cents to 19} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.08{ a bushel; corn was 5{ cents
to 8} cents lower with May at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 6 cents to
8{ cents lower with May at $1.89 a bushel; soybeans were 17 cents
to 26\ cents lower with May at $7.36 a bushel.
</TEXT>
