<DOCNO> AP890330-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Milken-Drexel Bjt   03-30 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken-Drexel, Bjt,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Market Shrugs Off Milken Indictment; Competitors May Be
Drooling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A criminal indictment against the man who led
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s junk bond operations to the top of
the heap is considered unlikely to stir the multibillion-dollar
market in those securities, but some say it gives competitors an
added edge against the firm.
   Because the government's action against 42-year-old Michael
Milken had long been expected, ``nobody really cares,'' one trader
who spoke on condition of anonymity said Thursday.
   Prices of high-yield, low-rated bonds were little changed to
slightly higher in quiet dealing the day after a federal grand jury
indicted Milken and two others on 98 counts of racketeering and
fraud.
   Traders contacted seemed more interested to learn that Milken's
salary topped $1 billion between 1984 and 1987 than to ponder the
market impact of the charges.
   The nonchalant reaction was reminiscent of how the market
shrugged off news last December that Drexel agreed to admit guilt
to six felonies and pay a record $650 million fine to settle
sweeping government securities fraud charges unrelated to its junk
bond operations.
   It also seemed to indicate how the market for low-rated,
high-yield corporate debt securities, which Drexel almost
single-handedly expanded into a $180 billion industry, has become
an institution that can weather the storm.
   Under Milken's guidance, Drexel exploited the gigantic U.S.
corporate appetite for financing by using junk bonds _ so called
because they carry a greater risk of default than higher-grade
investment quality paper _ as a means of borrowing money to pay for
deals ranging from mergers and hostile takeovers to corporate
expansions.
   Junk bonds formerly were used primarily by borrowers with weak
credit ratings or scanty earning histories.
   Experts say Drexel has carved a niche so substantial that it
will continue doing well in the junk bond market.
   Last year, Drexel issued $11.59 billion in new junk bonds,
giving it 41 percent of that market, according to Securities Data
Co. Milken's department is believed to have generated more than
half of the firm's profits.
   There is lingering speculation that some Drexel clients who feel
particularly loyal to Milken will take their business elsewhere.
``They might feel Drexel treated him too harshly,'' one trader said.
   Under its settlement with the government, Drexel agreed to fire
Milken and deny him his 1988 bonus, although the firm continues to
pay Milken's legal fees. Drexel placed Milken on a leave of absence
following the indictment.
   Sources said some clients are establishing relationships with
other junk bond issuers as a hedge against possible future problems
involving Drexel.
   And those other players are out courting business.
   John Moran, a trader with Advest Inc., said a number of
investment firms have ``built up tremendously over the past six or
seven months. ... Anybody who wanted to compete with Drexel decided
to do that when the whole scandal broke'' more than two years ago.
   ``When the No. 1 people are in trouble, it gets the others
running in the door faster ... it gives (the others) an edge,'' he
said.
   In the 1989 first quarter, Drexel for the first time was
supplanted by Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. as the No. 1 new junk-bond
underwriter.
   Drexel's $800 million in sales ranked fourth with a 16 percent
share of the market, down from $1.75 billion and a 43 percent share
in the year-ago quarter. Goldman Sachs' first-quarter share totaled
$1.25 billion, or 25 percent, according to figures from Securities
Data.
   Other major players in the junk bond market include Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets, Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. and First
Boston Corp.
   But Drexel is likely to recapture its lead in the second
quarter. The firm has yet to repackage about $5 billion in junk
bonds that financed the mega-buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. Those
issues should be coming to market in the next few months.
   ``Other firms may have issues in the private market that
eventually will go public, but it's nothing like a $5 billion
deal,'' said Fran Wissak, an assistant vice president at Securities
Data.
   And there seems to be little concern that the market will have
anything but a healthy appetite for the Nabisco issue.
   ``They've already done their road show, and I understand they've
done a good job'' trying to generate interest in the issue among
investors, Wissak said.
</TEXT>
