<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     03-30 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $186.8 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 461 money market mutual
funds rose $186.8 million to a new record of $299.62 billion in the
latest week, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   It was the 12th straight week the fund assets hit an all-time
high, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
   The group said that in the week ended Wednesday, assets of 228
general purpose funds rose $262.7 million to $97.68 billion, assets
of 94 broker-dealer funds decreased $113.4 million to $128.93
billion, and assets of 139 institutional funds rose $37.5 million
to $73.00 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.04 percent from 8.95 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.89 percent from 8.78 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
31 days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.65 percent as of Wednesday from 6.53 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was 5.14 percent, unchanged from the previous week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.17
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 9.05 the
previous week. Yields were 9.38 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.25
percent; 9.29 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 9.19 percent; and
9.20 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 9.13 percent.
</TEXT>
