<HEAD>For Release Sunday April 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tim Matheson, Animal House `Otter', Becomes a Takeover Specialist</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It sounds like something from a Hollywood
script: An actor turned takeover strategist wrests control of a
movie company away from its founder.
   That's what Tim Matheson, better known as the philandering
frat-brother Otter in ``Animal House,'' has done with National
Lampoon Inc., which produced the 1978 hit film and publishes
National Lampoon magazine.
   Matheson and partner Daniel Grodnik don't see themselves in the
same vein as Carl Icahn or Ronald Perelman, the takeover
strategists who respectively bought Trans World Airlines and Revlon
Inc.
   ``We want to build a company,'' Grodni in an interview, with
Matheson chiming in: ``a significant entment company.''
   Yet the pair won National Lh some tried-and-true methods of
corporate acquisition _ perhaps because they were schooled by David
Batchelder, ex-adviser to another renowned takeover strategist, T.
Boone Pickens Jr.
   Matheson and Grodnik, an independent film producer, hankered for
their own movie company after they co-produced the film ``Blind
Fury.''
   They retained Batchelder, telling him they wanted to raise $50
million to form a production company.
   Buttchelder said it made more sense to buy an existing company
rat _ a lesson many corporate acquirers and entrepreneurs have
learned.
   Grodnik quoted Batche the pair, ``Just find a company that has
an operating history that you feel is undervalued inrketplace.''
   They settled on money-losing Nl Lampoon, whose stock price was
languishing at around $2.50 a
   Was it a coincidence they chose the producer of ``Animal House?''
   Not entirely. ``It l of our needs and purposes,'' Matheson said.
``It was the best company that we came up with.''
   With Batchr's help, Grodnik and Matheson persuaded nine National
Lampoon stockholders to assign the pair their voting rights. These
stockholders had bouat $7 or $8 a share, Grodnik said, and ``they
wanted some relief.''
   The agreements gave the pair control over 18.5 percent of the
stock, and a 3 percent stake they bought boosted the figure to 21.5
pe
   At that point, late last year, they approached National Lampoon
founder and chairman Matty Simmons and said they wanted to join the
company's management. Grodnik, Matheson and Simmons downplayed any
resemblance betw and a classic takeover fight.
   ``It wasn't ' Simmons said in an interview.
   But Matheson acknowledged that, ``It was a surprise (to Simmons)
that we ch over 21.5 percent of the voting stock,'' and that it
took some pressure to move the National n founder.
   ``It became very obvious to him that we're not g Matheson said,
adding that their voting stake ``became irresistible ... We had
this critical m of support.''
   Simmons may have balked at first, but he say, ``The idea came
from me of them buying my stoand taking over the management of the
company.'
   Simmons said he was tired of trying to run the movie producin
California and the magazine in New York, and wanted to concentrate
on filmmaking. So he soldercent stake March 16 to Grodnik and
Matheson at $6 a share, or corporate acquirers, the men who now
control National Lampoon must try to turne business around.
National Lampgazine, known for salacious humor after its founding
in 1970, has lost readers over the years.
   ``The company needs direction, money and management,''
Grodntheson and Grodnik admit they have little experience with
magazines, but with an injection of outside capital _ which
Batchelder will arrange _ they want to hire people who can revive
the magazine's former glory.
   ``The magazine's alnown as the cutting edge of comedy in
America,'' said Matheson, but ``the proper attention wasn't paid to
staythe cutting edge.''
   Would they sell the magazine or other National Lampoon assets?
   ``No way,'' said Matheson.
   ``We're not in here to do a Kohlberg Kravis Roberts we're going
to piece this thing apart and sell if off,'' he said, referring to
the investment firm that has financed multibillion dollar takeovers
partly through the sale of corporate assets.
   Grodnik said he expected that ``the movie company will
strengthen the magazine and the magazine will strengthen the movie
company.''
   Among the people working on movies for National Lampoon _ 11 are
in development _ is Matty Simmons.
   National Lampoon will continue mady films under its flagship
label, but Grodnik and Matheson als want to do more serious
pictures and action movies.
   ``We'll come up with our own version of the Touchstone label,''
said Matheson, referring to the Walt Disney Co. division that has
produced hits like ``Good Morning: Vietnam'' and ed Roger Rabbit.''
   Noting that they already have production experience, Matheson
and Grodnik sound confidl succeed.
   ``What we're doing here is not unlike any busineto try the
business end of movies _ Clint Eastwood and Michael Douglas are
producers _ and he rejects the suggactor may not be qualified to
run a business.
   , 41, started in the entertainment business 30 years ago as a
child actor in television. He appeared in ``Leave It to Beaver''
and was a regular on ``The Virginian,'' ``Bonanza'' and other shows.
   Besides ``Animal House,'' his movie credits include the Mel
Brooks film ``To Be Or Not To Be.''
   He turned to production with ``Blind Fury'' and last year did an
ABC comedy sies, ``Just in Time.'' He also starred in the t show _
playing a magazine publisher.
   Grodnik, 36, said he has always been an entrepreneur, starting
in childhood by selling soda and moving on to setting up high
school dances, ski trips and concerts.
   At the University of Southern California he studied film, and
found that producing a movie wasn't that different from putting on
