<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SearsRestructuring Bjt   03-30 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears Restructuring, Bjt,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Giant Pares Down, Tightens Up Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. on Thursday announced the
latest move in a campaign to slim down and tighten up _ a
reorganization of its central merchandising operation that will cut
some 800 management jobs.
   The changes in the Sears Merchandise Group, which will close 24
regional administrative offices, are the latest in a series as the
nation's largest retailer tries to hold its own in a fast-moving,
highly competitive market.
   Since October, Chicago-based Sears has put its trademark Sears
Tower, the world's tallest building, up for sale, moved to offer
more brand-name products and shifted to everyday low pricing.
   Thursday's announcement calls for streamlining the merchandise
group, which is structured ``horizontally'' with an ever-widening
chain of commmand.
   The goal is creation of six crisp new operations, with direct
reporting and accountability from the retail store to the group
vice president _ in appliances-electronics, home fashions, home
improvement, women's apparel, men's-children's apparel and
automotive, the company said.
   ``I think what is necessary for Sears to be competitive ...
given the change in pricing structure ...is to reduce cost of the
operation and this a step in that direction,'' said analyst Joseph
Ronning with Brown Brothers Harriman Inc. in New York.
   ``Each of these businesses in Sears stores will report directly
to a district manager for that distinct business, who will be
accountable for customer service, sales and profits in 10 stores
and report to a region manager for that business,'' said Michael
Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of Sears Merchandise
Group.
   ``The new structure will allow us to better execute the
strategies that will make us more competitive and more
profitable,'' Bozic said.
   The reorganization ``takes away the old structure and makes a
leaner company, one that has more room for profit improvement,''
said analyst Walter Loeb of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York.
   The merchandise group's restructuring, effective Aug. 1, will
eliminate numerous field offices, including the 24 regional
administrative offices that oversee Sears' 824 stores under the
current system. Ten regional locations will be retained to provide
support to retail store operations.
   The new field operation will operate with about 800 fewer
management positions than the current system, with 7,700 such jobs,
the company said.
   No layoffs are anticipated, said Sears spokesman Ernest Arms,
citing attrition and reorganization incentives that include a
salary continuation plan and early retirement benefits.
   A similar restructuring of a Sears headquarters organization is
under way on a department-by-department basis, Bozic said, and is
to be completed this year.
   Speculation about the sale of the 110-story Sears Tower
continued Thursday, with reports that Sears had moved back its
schedule and was seeking a sale in four years instead of two.
   But Arms said the two-year timetable had been just an example in
documents for perspective buyers.
   ``We're not being coy _ we just don't know.'' he said. ``First
we've got to determine where it is we're going.''
   All but 600 of the 7,400 Sears workers in the tower are to be
relocated, and the company is being wooed by several states though
``we've expressed the desire to remain in the Chicago area,'' Arms
said.
   Sears' prospectus does not mention a price. The Wall Street
Journal quoted unidentified industry sources Thursday as saying
Sears is asking $1.1 billion to $1.3 billion _ the most ever asked
for a U.S. office building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
