<DOCNO> AP890330-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USTrade-Soviet Bjt   03-30 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Trade-Soviet, Bjt,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, U.S. Consortium Sign Agreement On Rules For Joint Ventures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of U.S. corporations on Thursday signed a wide-ranging
agreement with the Soviet Union setting the framework for new joint
ventures worth up to $10 billion over 20 years.
   The group, calling itself the American Trade Consortium, has
been negotiating for a year to complete the deal with the Soviet
Foreign Economic Consortium, which establishes a legal and business
framework for the development of joint ventures between the groups.
   The U.S. consortium consists of giant food processer Archer
Daniels Midland Co.; Chevron Corp.; Eastman Kodak Co.; personal
products maker Johnson & Johnson; RJR Nabisco Inc., and the
Mercator Corp., a banking concern.
   Some of the possible joint ventures that now will be negotiated
include oilseed processing; manufacture of computer discs;
production of crackers, cereals, tobacco products and sweeteners;
and oil and gas exploration.
   But although at least one member of the ATC indicated it was
moving ahead with talks to set up joint ventures, several major
hurdles remain.
   Additionally, one original member of the group, Ford Motor Co.,
dropped out of the consortium saying there had not been enough
progress to warrant its continued participation.
   A significant issue is the repatriation of profits from the
Soviet Union, which has been a key obstacle in previous attempts by
Western companies to do business there. The Soviet ruble is not
convertible, and any profits earned in rubles are worthless outside
the country.
   James H. Giffen, president of the American group, said in an
announcement from Moscow that Thursday's agreement resolves that
issue in principle, but he declined to provide details.
   Feasibility studies will be conducted over the next year and
Giffen said the first of some 25 joint ventures could strt up
within 18 months.
   Kodak indicated it was negotiating seven joint ventures to
market cameras, film and other photographic products and to process
photographic film. Other ventures would sell computer discs and a
blood analyzer.
   Ford had planned to begin selling West German-made Scorpio
automobiles in the Soviet Union by the end of this year. Later, the
company hoped to begin an automobile manufacturing project in the
Soviet city of Gorky, where the Gorky Auto Works is making cars in
a plant built with Ford's help in the 1920s.
   ``Although there was progress, the framework of understandings
reached so far between the ATC and the Soviets was not sufficient
to make feasible a project of the scope and complexity of Ford's,''
said Philip Benton, president of Ford's automotive group,
   Ford spokesman Al Chambers declined to say how much money Ford
had spent on the project.
   ``At a later date, when the environment for doing business in
the USSR is better defined, it may be possible to complete such a
major project,'' Benton said in a prepared statement released in
Detroit. ``In those circumstances, we would certainly welcome the
opportunity to participate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890330-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-30 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned in an indecisive showing
Thursday, pausing after its rally of the past three sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 38.48 points in the
week's first three trading days, slipped back .18 to 2,281.34.
   But advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 726 up, 716
down and 498 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 159.95 million
shares, up from 144.24 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 188.41 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday morning that new
factory orders declined 2.3 percent in February.
   That provided fresh support for the view that the pace of the
economy began to slow last month.
   But analysts have been reluctant to conclude from a single
month's data that the Federal Reserve has succeeded in its efforts
to subdue inflationary pressures by tightening credit.
   The first indication of whether the slowing continued in March
isn't expected to come until the Labor Department's monthly
employment report late next week.
   In the meantime, stocks got little support from the bond market,
where interest rates rose slightly.
   Money-center bank stocks were strong for the second straight
session, apparently benefiting from increased confidence among
institutional money managers about their prospects for weathering
Third World debt problems.
   Citicorp climbed 1 to 29{; Bankamerica | to 24{; Chase Manhattan
1] to 37; Chemical Banking 1} to 35], and J.P. Morgan 1 to 39\.
   Illinois Power led the active list, down 1} at 14 on turnover of
more than 4.3 million shares. The Illinois Commerce Commission
granted a much smaller rate increase than the company had sought.
   Genentech dropped 1| to 17}. An article in the New England
Journal of Medicine reported on a study suggesting that the
company's clot-dissolving drug for treatment of heart attacks is no
more effective than a much less expensive alternative drug.
   Smithkline Beckman, which markets the alternative drug, rose ~
to 55|. Smithkline also has been the subject lately of takeover
rumors and speculation.
   Sears Roebuck rose { to 43{. The company announced plans for a
major revamping of its organizational structure.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $3.49 billion, or 0.12
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .13 to 164.38.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index lost .06 to 336.86, while
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up .17 at 292.52.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained .86 to 404.56. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 325.47, down .11.
