<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-30 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Rain Triggers Flood Of Selling In Grain Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Widespread showers brought relief to Kansas wheat fields and
triggered a flood of selling Thursday on the Chicago Board of
Trade, where wheat futures prices settled at a 3{ month low.
   Other grain and soybean futures also fell sharply in Chicago
amid perceptions of improving growing conditions.
   On other markets Thursday, oil futures soared while gold,
silver, copper, livestock and meat futures all finished lower.
   Wheat settled 10 cents to 19\ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel, the lowest settlement price for
a near-month wheat contract since Dec. 16. Corn was 5} cents to 9\
cents lower with May at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 6{ cents to 8
cents lower with May at $1.89 a bushel; and soybeans were 16 cents
to 26{ cents lower with May at $7.37 a bushel.
   The rain that fell Wednesday night and early Thursday in western
Kansas was not remarkably heavy _ about { inch overall _ but it was
heavier and more widespread than expected, touching areas where
extreme dryness has caused irreparable harm to the winter wheat
crop.
   ``There's an old saying that rain begets rain,'' said Cathy
Leow, a grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
in New York.
   ``Watch out when a drought begins to break; it typically means
there'll be more rain,'' she said, noting forecasts for weekend
showers in the Great Plains and the Midwest.
   The Midwest, heart of the nation's corn and soybean country, has
also received welcome showers this week, which contributed to the
sell-off. The advancing South American soybean harvest, which is
bringing new supplies to the marketplace, added to the bearish tone.
   Observers said the selling also reflected continued
position-evening before Friday afternoon's Agriculture Department
quarterly grain stocks report and spring planting estimates.
   Few traders are willing to go out on a limb ahead of the
reports, which could have a huge impact on prices.
   ``There's a good chance there'll be some surprises'' in the
reports, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader in Chicago with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Crude-oil futures skyrocketed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as major oil companies coped with a supply squeeze in the
wake of a giant oil spill off the Alaskan coast.
   Exxon Corp. and British Petroleum Co.'s BP America unit each
announced they were scaling back on deliveries of Alaskan North
Slope crude to their customers receiving that type of oil.
   Meanwhile, OPEC ministers winding up a 2-day strategy session in
Vienna indicated cartel members planned to stick to their current
production restraints through mid-year, which added another bullish
factor to Thursday's trading.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 31 cents to 61 cents
higher with May at $20.81 a barrel; heating oil was 1.56 cents to
1.99 cents higher with April at 56.18 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was 1.35 cents to 3.01 cents higher with April at 63.19
cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures slipped lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange on signs of a continued easing of inflationary pressures.
   Gold settled $1.30 to $1.60 lower with April at $382.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.3 cents to 4.3 cents lower with May at $5.78 an
ounce.
   Copper futures prices dropped sharply on the Commodity Exchange,
reflecting increasing supplies.
   Copper settled 2.4 cents to 5.1 cents lower with April at $1.324
a pound.
   Weakening cash markets and bearish chart signals prompted heavy
selling of pork futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, and the
selling spilled over into the cattle pits.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent to .65 cent lower with April at
78.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .38 cent lower
with April at 81.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .80
cent lower with April at 40.87 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to .80 cent lower with May at 38.07 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
