<FIRST>r f AM-MCIRates     03-30 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MCI Rates,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates To Be Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. said Thursday it will
reduce its long-distance rates by $200 million annually beginning
April 1 in response to federally ordered cuts in the charges it
pays to connect with local phone systems.
   The reductions will apply to residential and business customers
and could amount to cuts of as much as 12 percent for some callers,
the company said.
   The Federal Communications Commission has ordered the nation's
local phone companies to reduce their interstate calling access
charges by $705 million on April 1. The local companies charge
long-distance companies to help maintain the local phone systems.
   Since the breakup of the Bell system in 1984, the FCC has
ordered a series of reductions in the charges local phone companies
levy on long-distance companies. At the same time, it has required
the long-distance carriers to pass along the savings to their
customers.
   ``With this reduction, MCI will have dropped its rates more than
40 percent'' since 1984, MCI said.
   The $200 million reduction is subject to FCC approval.
</TEXT>
