<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-30 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls on Fed Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower Thursday as the
Federal Reserve stormed into the foreign exchange market, selling
dollars to squelch the currency's rally.
   Gold prices slipped in New York after rising overseas. Republic
National Bank of New York quoted a late bid of $381.55 for a troy
ounce of gold, down slightly from Wednesday's late bid of $381.80.
   The dollar advanced in early trading in response to rising oil
prices, said Jack Barbanel, an analyst with Gruntal &amp; Co. Inc.
   The Fed entered the market several times, selling small amounts
of dollars, but the U.S. currency continued its climb.
   However, in mid-afternoon, with the dollar at a peak for the day
of about 134.50 Japanese yen, the Fed made what Barbanel called ``a
massive intervention,'' selling dollars for West German marks and
Japanese yen.
   ``The Fed, when they really mean what they say, intervenes in
stages that over time become more sizable,'' said Barbanel.
   West German and Japanese officials ``don't want to see the
dollar gaining any more strength'' and the Fed acted in response to
those countries' wishes, Barbanel said.
   Traders took the hint, and sold the dollar down against other
currencies as well.
   The dollar ended the day in New York falling to 1.8910 West
German marks from late Wednesday's 1.8934 marks. It slipped to
132.00 Japanese yen from Wednesday's 133.115 yen.
   What the dollar does next depends on whether the intervention
continues Friday, Barbanel said.
   However, another factor that could affect the currency markets
is a possible hike in the Japanese discount rate, which was rumored
to be in the offing, Barbanel said.
   A hike in the key Japanese interest rate would likely be
followed by increases in West German and British rates. That would
boost those currencies and cause the dollar to decline.
   Overseas dealers described Thursday's trading as nervous
following intervention by central banks over several days.
   ``There's very little going on. People don't know what they want
to do,'' said one dealer at a West German bank.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6875 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's $1.6870. In New York trading,
the pound rose to $1.6888 from late Wednesday's $1.6875.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.6490 Swiss francs, down from
1.65125; 6.3855 French francs, down from 6.3905; 1,385.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,389.00; and 1.19345 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19415.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.8885 West German marks, down
from 1.8910; 1.6475 Swiss francs, down from 1.6490; 6.3750 French
francs, down from 6.3800; 2.1296 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1315;
1,383.25 Italian lire, down from 1,385.65; and 1.1925 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1935.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 132.80 Japanese yen, down
from 133.25 yen. In later London trading the dollar was quoted at
132.30 yen.
   Gold fell $1.30 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange in New
York, closing at $382.20.
   The late bid price for gold in London was $383.25 a troy ounce,
up from $382.75. The late bid price in Zurich was $383.40, up from
$381.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.45 bid, up from
$383.55.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.79 bid a troy ounce,
up from $5.78. But silver slipped 2.3 cents an ounce on the Comex
in New York, falling to $5.735.
</TEXT>
