<FIRST>r f AM-Manville-Holophane     03-30 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manville-Holophane,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manville To Sell Holophane Division For $102 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. announced Thursday it plans to sell
its Holophane Lighting systems division for $102 million to the Los
Angeles-based merchant banking firm Raebarn Corp.
   The Newark, Ohio-based division was put up for sale by Manville
in November.
   ``We're trying to focus on our core businesses and get rid of
businesses that are more on the fringe,'' said Manville spokeswoman
Tricia Bergeron.
   Holophane, which makes lighting fixtures and accessories for
commercial and industrial use, has been part of Manville's
Specialty Products Group, one of three groups of businesses
operated by the Denver-based manufacturer.
   The other groups are fiber glass and forest products. Specialty
products focuses on minerals businesses, Bergeron said.
   Holophane employs a total of 1,000 people at its eight plants,
located in Edison, N.J.; Newark, Pataskala, Utica and Springfield,
Ohio; Brampton, Ontario; St. Hyacinthe, Quebec; and Milton Keynes,
England.
   Bergeron said Raebarn intends to operate Holophane with the same
management and workforce.
   ``That was an important part of the negotiations,'' she said.
   Alfred B. Gough, Specialty Products Group president, said the
sale was expected to close within three months.
</TEXT>
