<FIRST>r f AM-Kroger-Shareholders     03-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kroger-Shareholders,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kroger Says Ready To Proceed With Shareholders' Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kroger Co. said Thursday that if there are
no more objections, it will proceed with a court-approved
settlement of a class-action suit by shareholders who challenged
the $4.6 billion restructuring the company announced last September.
   Under the settlement, the Cincinnati-based grocery company will
pay $1.275 million in attorneys' fees to about 20 law firms around
the nation which represented the suit's plaintiffs.
   Kroger also agreed in the settlement to make changes in the way
employee shares are voted in its worker benefit and compensation
plans, and to amend terms of debentures it issued to about 60,000
shareholders as part of the restructuring.
   The changes include shortening the maturity date by two years,
altering procedures for redeeming the debentures and providing
procedures in which employees can vote their shares in benefit
plans confidentially.
   Hamilton County Common Pleas Judge William Mathews conducted a
hearing earlier this month to allow lawyers for Kroger and the
shareholders to comment on the settlement, which was proposed Jan.
24. Mathews approved the settlement Tuesday and Kroger announced
its details Thursday.
   Anyone who wants to appeal Mathews' ruling must do so within 30
days.
   Cincinnati lawyer Gene Mesh, who represented several dissident
stockholders who objected to the settlement, was out of his office
Thursday when a telephone call was placed to ask whether he would
file an appeal.
   Kroger, which operates supermarkets and convenience stores in
much of the nation, began the restructuring in part to fend off
takeover bids last fall by Dart Group Inc. of Landover, Md., and by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. of New York City. Kroger defeated the
takeover bids, but has since sold assets including some stores and
food processing plants, and laid off 300 of its 800 headquarters
employees last October.
</TEXT>
