<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DebtTalks 1stLd-Writethru   03-30 0966</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debt Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0211,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Calls Reform of Latin Economies Vital to Ease Debt Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds last 3 grafs with announcement on insurance fund. Also
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As officials from 151 nations began arriving
for pivotal discussions on Third World debt, Secretary of State
James A. Baker III warned Latin American leaders Thursday that they
must make economic reforms to participate in the administration's
new debt reduction program.
   Baker said the Bush administration stood ready to negotiate
debt-reduction packages on a case-by-case basis as long as the
debtor countries accepted responsibility to make payments on their
reduced debt and to make internal reforms.
   Baker, a former Treasury secretary who crafted the debt approach
followed by the Reagan administration, said that there was no
``magic solution'' to the $1.2 trillion debt crisis which has left
developing nations facing mounting problems of economic and
political unrest.
   ``Democratic governments must try to reform bloated
state-dominated economies, service their debt and satisfy the real
needs of their citizens,'' Baker said in Atlanta at a conference on
Latin America hosted by former Presidents Carter and Ford.
   ``We understand that facing this challenge alone is a nearly
impossible juggling act,'' Baker told the gathering. It included
the president of Venezuela, a nation where 270 persons were killed
in rioting last month sparked by a new austerity program
implemented to please that nation's creditors.
   ``As you move forward to take the necessary but difficult steps
to restructure and reform your economies, we must be prepared to
hear your calls for help,'' said Baker. He urged a ``new bond of
cooperation and mutual responsibility'' between the United States
and the countries of Latin America.
   Baker's comments came as the administration stepped up efforts
to sell its new debt reduction proposals, which were unveiled on
March 10 by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady.
   The administration's plan will come under global scrutiny at
meetings beginning Friday of the 151-nation International Monetary
Fund and its sister lending organization, the World Bank.
   Both of the large lending organizations have a role to play in
the new initiative, which is being called the Brady plan, and the
administration is hoping to get general approval of the new policy
approach by the time the sessions end next Tuesday.
   Under the new plan, commercial banks would be asked to forgive
voluntarily a portion of the loans they have made to poor nations.
In return, the IMF and World Bank would provide assurances that the
remaining debt would be repaid.
   The administration has estimated that over the next three years
its proposals could result in wiping out about $70 billion of the
$340 billion in debt owed by 39 developing nations, a group which
includes all of the largest debtors and many of the smaller ones.
   The debt strategy represents a major about-face for the United
States, which under the Baker plan rejected all proposals for
broad-based debt forgiveness and instead emphasized obtaining new
lending for poor nations.
   While not admitting that his approach had failed to generate the
hoped-for new loans to spur growth, Baker said, ``Clearly, Latin
America must begin to grow again and the fruits of that growth must
be more widely shared.''
   At the White House, officials announced that Venezuela's
President Carlos Andres Perez and El Salvador's President Alfredo
Cristiani, both newly elected, would meet with President Bush in
the next week.
   Perez, who has taken a leadership role in the Latin American
debt crisis, said at the Atlanta conference that the
administration's new debt plan offered hope for the region's
troubled democracies, which he said were facing ``unsustainable
pressures'' from the debt burden they are now carrying.
   In a speech in his own country on Wednesday, Perez had been more
blunt, blaming the price riots which broke out on Feb. 27 on
``intolerable and obscene'' debt repayment terms and warning that
those riots could be repeated in any of the countries of Latin
America.
   Perez, who accompanied Baker back to Washington, was scheduled
to meet Bush on Saturday at a breakfast session to be attended by
Baker, Brady and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   Officials of both Venezuela and Mexico have been engaged in
intensive talks with U.S. Treasury officials in the past several
days. It is expected that those two nations will be the first to
qualify for debt relief under the Brady plan.
   Meanwhile, officials said that the IMF and World Bank were close
to resolving a turf battle between the two organizations that has
hampered their efforts to aid poor countries.
   An official of the World Bank, who spoke on condition that he
not be identified by name, said that the IMF board had already
reviewed the proposal and the matter was pending before the
directors of the World Bank.
   The agreement follows principles set out by a committee of
senior finance officials of the 10 leading industrial countries and
delineates areas of responsibility for both organizations.
   Officials said the accord should help to resolve tensions
between the two agencies, which have found their lending functions
increasingly overlapped in recent years.
   In another development, the agency that guarantees investments
by industrial countries against political risk in the Third World
said it will likely begin writing its first insurance policies this
June.
   Leigh P. Hollywood, an official of the new Multilateral
Investment Guarantee Agency, said that most of the 60 applicants
for insurance policies have come from companies located in the
United States.
   The U.S. government and 72 other countries have pledged $744
million to establish the new agency, which was created as an arm of
the World Bank to encourage foreign investment in the Third World
by protecting investors against such risks as war, civil
disturbances and expropriation of assets.
</TEXT>
