<FIRST>r f AM-HSN-GTE     03-30 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HSN-GTE,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Reinstates $1 Billion Damage Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Circuit judge on Thursday said he
would allow Home Shopping Network Inc. to ask for $1 billion in
punitive damages against GTE Corp. in a suit over telephone service
and set trial for June 5.
   Pinellas Circuit Judge Howard P. Rives reversed an earlier order
and said he would allow HSN to make the hefty punitive claim
against the telephone company.
   James V. Carideo, vice president and general counsel of GTE
Florida, said Rives' ruling was ``purely procedural.''
   The punitive damages are in addition to the $500 million HSN is
seeking from GTE in compensatory fines.
   In September 1987, HSN sued GTE claiming the utility knowingly
provided defective and inadequate telephone equipment and services.
HSN alleged that GTE deliberately concealed the defects and misled
the video retailer in order to keep the lucrative account.
   Last November, Rives ruled that it was necessary for Home
Shopping to present evidence of GTE misconduct before claiming
punitive damages.
   In asking to have the claim reinstated, HSN presented documents,
some from from GTE files, which the company says backs its
allegations. Rives' ruling Thursday means HSN may take its case
before a jury.
   ``HSN was convinced when it filed the lawsuit in 1987 that it
was entitled to punitive damages. Today's ruling will allow us to
present all our claims to the jury,'' said Nando DiFilippo Jr.,
executive vice president and general counsel for HSN.
   Rives said the case should take four- to six weeks.
   GTE Florida's Carideo said, ``We look forward to showing at
trial, as our counterclaim states, that HSN's suit is a `sham' and
`an attempted cover-up for management problems.'''
</TEXT>
