<DOCNO> AP890330-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 2331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Milken-Penalties 1stLd-Writethru f0320 03-30 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken-Penalties, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0320,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Multi-billion Dollar Fine for Milken Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `The $1.85 ...,' to RESTORE dropped words.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junk bond financier Michael R. Milken is as
unlikely to receive a multibillion dollar fine as he is a 500-year
prison term, even if he is convicted on every count of a mammoth
racketeering and securities fraud indictment, a federal prosecutor
said Thursday.
   Milken, head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high yield bond
department, and two others were indicated Wednesday on charges they
turned Drexel into a racketeering enterprise that engaged in
securities violations ranging from insider trading to stock market
manipulation.
   All three were charged with racketeering and conspiring to
violate federal racketeering laws, which each carry a maximum
20-year sentence upon conviction.
   Milken, his brother Lowell and former Drexel trader Bruce
Newberg each face maximum fines of $3.7 billion if convicted on
either or both of the racketeering counts, said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Bruce Baird.
   Those fines represent the highest possible amounts under federal
racketeering law _ that is, double the gains made from the
allegedly illegal enterprise _ that a judge may impose.
   The defendants also face fines of at least $250,000 and up to
five years imprisonment on each of the lesser charges of mail, wire
and securities fraud. In Michael Milken's case, that's an
additional 96 counts or a total of $24 million more in fines and a
possible 520 years imprisonment.
   But Baird conceded such totals were ``unrealistic.''
   ``Neither the possible maximum fine nor the possible maximum
prison term is a penalty that the government expects will be fully
imposed,'' said Baird, head of the securities and commodities fraud
unit at the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan.
   ``A fine, like a term of imprisonment, is something within the
discretion of the judge after conviction,'' said the prosecutor.
For example, he added, for Milken a judge could impose either no
jail time or the maximum 520 years upon conviction.
   But based on past sentencing practices in other major
racketeering and securities cases, it appeared unlikely a judge
would impose the fullest possible penalties against the three,
Baird indicated.
   Far more realistic, said Baird, was that if the three were
convicted of either racketeering count they would have to forfeit a
total of $1.85 billion in allegedly illegal gains made from their
enterprise.
   Forfeiture is a penalty unique to the federal Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, Baird said.
   The $1.85 billion represents virtually all the money Milken and
his co-defendants made from their dealings with Drexel or from
their financial stake in Drexel from 1984 through 1987 _ the years
covered by the indictment _ which is subject to forefeiture under
the federal racketeering law.
   That includes all salaries and bonuses, totaling $1.2 billion;
Drexel stock worth $112 million; $205 million in corporate finance
fees and $37.9 million in Drexel trading profits allegedly tainted
by fraud.
   Prosecutors also are seeking $257 million in interest.
   Baird said the trial jury would decide whether to order
forfeiture after a racketeering conviction.
   Baird said the government did not plan to seek a court order
freezing the trio's assets.
   ``We're going to give them an opportunity to post a bond
first,'' said Baird. He said the bond would be like posting bail
for their assets ``to assure the assets will still be there in the
event of a conviction on the RICO charges.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
